</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPIONSHIP MOLD COULD FIT LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Man the barricades, here comes the purple-and-gold
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Widely favored to lead the Western Conference when the season
began lo these several weeks ago, the Lakers have been reduced to a
level where an NBA title would be not simply an upset but downright
revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   If they get to the NBA Finals, let alone win it all, they'll
rewrite the book on building a champion.
</P>
<P>
   The book says you build a team with youth, plug holes with
veterans and give it a season to fit together. And hope Michael
Jordan isn't in the league when it does.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers built a team with youth, filled holes with veterans,
gave it a season to fit together, tore it up by switching to a
rookie head coach and signing Dennis Rodman, figured out in a month
that Rodman probably didn't belong but took another month to cut
him, changed three-fifths of the lineup in the Glen Rice trade, and
gave it 10 games to fit back together. Fortunately Michael Jordan
(begin ital)isn't(end ital) in the league, so anybody's got a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Even a team whose season has taken more turns than a low-speed
police chase?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capability to get there if we play our best
basketball and continue to improve in each round,'' coach Kurt
Rambis said at the Lakers' last practice session before their
first-round opener against the Houston Rockets today at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasis on ``capability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To expect the team to get there, with the number of changes
we've made and the lack of developmental time we've had, I think is
unrealistic for this ballclub,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasis on ``expect.''
</P>
<P>
   So don't say we never allowed the Lakers a pre-playoffs excuse.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, an excuse might be out of line. It's not as
if a team burdened by elements of the Lakers' unorthodox
preparation has never won the NBA title, just not in the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the year the Rockets followed one surprise title with
another in the first post-Jordan era, Houston went into the
playoffs as the No.6 seed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are No.4 seeds this year.
</P>
<P>
   In '95, shortly before the season's halfway point, the Rockets
made a major trade, giving up Otis Thorpe to get Clyde Drexler and
Tracy Murray from Portland. Thorpe had been their one true power
forward and they missed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of messed up the team for a while,'' said Robert
Horry, a Rocket then and a Laker now.
</P>
<P>
   The trade, and injuries to Horry, Drexler and Hakeem Olajuwon,
threw the Rockets into a slump that dropped them in the seedings.
Only at the season's very end did they establish some momentum.
</P>
<P>
   A jarring trade. A midseason slump. A late surge. Sound
familiar?
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets beat higher-seeded Utah, Phoenix and San Antonio
before sweeping Orlando and Shaquille O'Neal to win the title.
</P>
<P>
   Role models for the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   ``So much stuff is similar,'' Horry said of the '95 Rockets and
the '99 Lakers _ making allowances for the fact there was no Rodman
or Rambis in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The practical similarity being that those Rockets, playing well
in April, were No.6 seeds in name only, and these Lakers, winners
of their last four games by a 16-point average, are stronger than
No.4.
</P>
<P>
   But the quintet that will walk onto the Forum court at 2:30
today _ O'Neal, Rice, Kobe Bryant, Derek Fisher and trade
acquisition J.R. Reid _ has been together for barely three weeks.
In the Lakers' group-therapy sessions, they're up to the ``Hi, my
name is Glen'' stage of familiarization.
</P>
<P>
   To which the Rockets' Charles Barkley said: Big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of talent, and they're playing well,''
Barkley said of the Lakers, though he also could be talking about
the Rockets, who've won three in a row. ``What happened during the
regular season doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had a chance to say I told you so, having questioned the
Lakers' Western Conference-favorite's status before they and the
Rockets opened the regular season Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they were the favorite and (now) they're not
the favorite,'' Barkley said Saturday before the Rockets practiced
at the Forum. ``You all were swinging on their vines, like L.A.
people have a tendency to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Overrate the locals? Us?
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously thought they were overrated, or they wouldn't
have made so many changes,'' Barkley said of the Lakers' front
office.
</P>
<P>
   With the home-court advantage in the first-round, best-of-five
series, they'll beat Houston, which went 1-11 on the road against
playoff-bound teams.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll have to hold onto their recently acquired
confidence for three more rounds to win the championship. Don't
start rewriting that book just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult road, but it's not an impossible road,''
Horry said.
</P>
<P>
   Horry speaks as one who's been up a similar road before _ but
not quite as steep as this. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
