<HEADER>
A9874 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ADVERTISING-SIGNS     05-09 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ADVERTISING-SIGNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERICAL SIGNAGE IN BASEBALL: JUST GET USED TO IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox executive Larry Cancro has news for all those
fans who think baseball has become too commercialized, what with
billboards all over outfield walls and someday, perhaps,
advertising on player uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Green Monster _ the ultimate symbol of that bastion of
baseball tradition _ Fenway Park, has its roots in commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Monster wasn't built to keep balls in the park,'' Cancro
said. ``It was built as an advertising opportunity. It used to be
plastered with ads.''
</P>
<P>
   His point: Commercialism has always been a part of sport and
always will be, especially as sports franchises seek new sources of
revenue to meet rising player payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The never-ending battle for more revenue became a public issue
locally a week ago when Tom Schieffer resigned as Rangers
president. Sources said Schieffer had a philosophical conflict with
owner Tom Hicks over baseball's future. Schieffer much preferred
marketing the game's tradition; Hicks is a renowned financier
looking for all avenues to raise revenue, including adding signage
at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   But sports team officials here and elsewhere, along with
sports-marketing and media executives, agree that increased venue
advertising at ballparks and arenas, more commercials during
televised games and even advertising patches on player uniforms are
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing to stop the trend, experts say, unless demand by
corporate sponsors declines or club owners decide to cut back
because all that advertising is becoming unsightly. That's not
likely, though, except in extreme cases, because clubs depend on
the extra revenue to cover the ever-larger player payrolls needed
to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Sports facilities might never take on tacky names or bear
inappropriate advertising, but other than that there are few
restraints.
</P>
<P>
   Commercialism, Rangers vice president of marketing Charles
Seraphin said, ``has become kind of a whipping boy among people who
really haven't thought it through. There's concern about the
proliferation of corporate advertising in sports. But the reality
is that it's been around for a long time, and it's been done
tastefully and not detracted from the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People make a big deal out of it now when they see a rotating
ad sign board behind home plate,'' said Rick Burton, director of
the Warsaw Sports Marketing Center at the University of Oregon
College of Business. ``They talk like it's ruined the sanctity of
the game. But outdoor signs have been around for 75 years. It's
like, `C'mon kids ...' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey dasher boards, once ad-free, are now covered with
advertising. Even the ice surface bears advertising messages, such
as the Dr Pepper, GTE and Bud Light signs on the ice at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball arenas feature rotating sign boards at the press
table, often changing ads every few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Outfield fences at major-league stadiums, pristine for many
years, carry ads everywhere except for the prohibited area in
center field. Ads there could affect a hitter's vision, baseball
officials say. Baseball parks also have ads on dugout walls, on
upper-deck facades and on bullpen walls.
</P>
<P>
   At The Ballpark in Arlington, signs have sprouted this year in
the dugouts (New Era), along the left-field wall (Armitron) and on
the outfield fence (New Dodge).
</P>
<P>
   Football stadium advertising signs are confined to the upper
decks so as to not be part of ground-level TV shots. That is a
requirement of the National Football League, which doesn't want
visual conflicts between its national corporate sponsors and the
local sponsors of individual clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the increased advertising, particularly at
ballparks and arenas, is clear, said Roger Noll, a professor of
economics at Stanford University. The idea, he said, is to reach
people watching the game at home with the advertising message as
well as those sitting in the stands. Only 20,000 or 50,000 people
might see an ad on an outfield wall, along a dasher board, or on a
player's jersey. But millions can see an ad if it appears in the
background of a TV broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of money you can get from \Rstadium ad signage\S
has gone up dramatically in the last few years,'' Noll said. ``TV
advertising has become so expensive that this is a lower cost way
to get on the broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   While the focus of the furor over commercialization is on venue
advertising, fans are likely to see more advertising on TV, too.
In-game features could see more ``brought-to-you-by'' ads, for
example. Also, thanks to new technology, telecast sponsors can
project ad messages onto blank areas at a stadium (on the
center-field fence, for example) so that viewers at home see an
advertisement that fans at a game cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors typically buy all-inclusive advertising
packages from pro sports teams which might include stadium signage,
TV and game program advertising and promotional tie-ins. The value
of each element, therefore, is difficult to break out, but a
major-league team, for example, could earn anywhere from a few
million dollars a year from stadium advertising to $20 million,
depending on the size of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Those millions can help pay the salaries of several players,
maybe even make the difference between a winning team and a loser.
Seraphin says baseball executives weigh that reality when deciding
how much advertising to allow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked a baseball fan to choose between having a
pristine field and a team that loses 100 games,'' Seraphin said,
``or a stadium with some advertising and a club with a shot to go
to the World Series, they'll choose the advertising 100 out of 100
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan concern over increased commercialism centers on aesthetics.
The most common complaint is that all that advertising cheapens the
look of the ballpark and the sport itself.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a competitive concern about the increased
commercialization. Club officials said that the more successful
teams in the larger markets will earn far more revenue from stadium
and TV advertising than smaller market clubs, widening the growing
financial gap.
</P>
<P>
   Now that commercialism in sport is growing, fans shouldn't
expect it to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no end to it,'' says Bob Dorfman, a sports analyst with
the advertising agency Foote, Cone, Belding/San Francisco. ``What
happens is with each new threshold we cross _ signs on fences or
logos on uniform sleeves _ the purists raise hell. But then
everybody eventually gets used to it, they stop complaining, and
there it is.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, though, fans might have already become accustomed
to increased commercialization. Red Sox executive Cancro said he
received a letter of protest a few years ago from a Boston fan
angry about the placement of giant Coca-Cola bottles on light
towers high above the left-field wall at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Was he upset that the advertising monstrosity was ruining the
sanctity of one of baseball's cathedrals?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, Cancro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mad,'' Cancro said, ``because he said it blocked his
view of the Citgo sign behind the wall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
