<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' TRIUMPH TRULY A FRIGHTENING SIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars never seemed to get a grip on this wild, at
times wacky, hockey night.
</P>
<P>
   But the series _ all Ed Belfour excursions aside _ somehow
remains semi-firmly in their grasps this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   On the winged heels of Joe Nieuwendyk, the Stars oozed past the
St. Louis Blues in 8 1/2 minutes of overtime last night, 5-4, to
take a 2-0 lead in their best-of-seven playoff matchup.
</P>
<P>
   For Stars fans, that was the sudden and happy ending to what,
for the longest time, seemed like a Hitchcock movie.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Alfred Hitchcock, not the other guy.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it was like what you'd expect to see When Hockey
Goes Bad.
</P>
<P>
   Goalies freak out. Power plays turn into fire drills. Your
leading scorer starts thinking he's a shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams deserved to win. No _ wait. Both teams deserved to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   The home team's power play wanderings continued. Despite the
return of Derian Hatcher, heretofore in NHL drydock, the Stars'
defensive play was ... well ... choppy. The officiating was fickle
and, as usual, whistles turned mute in the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   But that apparently wasn't enough for the Stars, who added
lapses of poor positioning and Belfour's poorest night of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I never see that kind of game again,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Hitch's head likely added another layer of gray one particular
play 11 minutes into the third period. With the Stars on the
so-called power play, St. Louis' Mike Eastwood suddenly found
himself with the puck at center ice and with a clear path down the
left side toward Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, perhaps to practice something he once saw Tara
Lipinski do, Belfour sashayed out to greet the puck. He was all the
way to the red dot when he tumbled _ spreadeagled, so to speak _
onto the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Most fortunately, Eastwood couldn't bring the puck back under
control, to hit the yawningly empty net. Defenseman Darryl Sydor
was able to plug the hole until Belfour got back on his skates and
returned.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd oohed nervously. Nobody really expected the
score to stay tied, 4-4, until overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one revved-up hockey game,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   It started innocently enough, with both sides missing early
rushes and Jamie Langenbrunner's blast finally finding the net for
the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final seconds of the opening period, the Blues' Pavol
Demitra let loose from just inside the blue line, and the puck
somehow squirted through Belfour's legs. It knotted the game, 1-1,
and ended a Belfour shutout string that had reached 151 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie the Eagle never quite found the coop after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was a tough day for the goaltenders,''
Hitchcock said. ``There were a lot of odd-man rushes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock declined to agree that Belfour seemed to get a tad
frayed at the edges after the first two St. Louis goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it affected Eddie at all,'' Hitch said. ``Right
now you're just looking at trying to win hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was just a lot of tenacity. Some of each team _
\RPierre\S Turgeon for St. Louis, Nieuwendyk for us _ were able to
control the game. And when you have that, it is difficult on any
goaltender, because you're always on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the top-skilled players were really controlling the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Controlling,'' in this case, should be viewed as a relative
term. There was so much loose play on both ends, every puck that
slid near either Belfour or the Blues' Grant Fuhr was prompting a
gasp.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock blamed it on both teams' forwards forcing the action
and creating problems for the opposing defensemen. Well, yes and
no. The puck seldom found its way into the corners.
</P>
<P>
   But typical of the night, Mike Modano cost the Stars a two-man
disadvantage in the second period when he was sent to the box for
``closing his hand on the puck.'' In layman terms, he had lost his
stick and, with the puck at his feet, scooped it and seemed to try
to whistle it down to second base. The penalty ended up helping St.
Louis to a go-ahead goal.
</P>
<P>
   But so it went. Nobody expected either goalie to linger long
into overtime. And Nieuwendyk, who has been a difference-maker
throughout the playoffs, took care of that.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, this best-of-seven series remains firmly in their mitts
this morning. But don't show the tape to Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred _ or the other guy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
