<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-FUHR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUHR SHOULDERS BLAME FOR BLUES' LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ St. Louis played well enough to steal Game 2 from a
beatable-looking Stars bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Blues goalie Grant Fuhr said his play best explains why Dallas
escaped with a 5-4 overtime victory instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well enough to win,'' Fuhr said. ``I don't think I
played well enough to win. That's the bottom line. If I play well
tonight, that's an easy win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr faced 25 shots, stopping 20 of them.
</P>
<P>
   No. 25 came 8:22 into overtime, with Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk
firing a wrist shot past Fuhr to end Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Blues players and coaches were left frustrated and annoyed.
Playing good enough to win had failed to earn them a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we deserved better,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville
said. ``We had the higher quality chances, and we didn't capitalize
at the right moments. Certainly, we proved we've got a chance
against these guys. It's not a hopeless situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blues defenseman Chris Pronger: ``Definitely, it was there
for the taking. We let it slip a way a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis had chance after chance after chance to bury an
unusually loosey, goosey Stars bunch.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange situation midway through final period of
regulation, Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor was all that stood in the
way of a Blues goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' usual goaltender, Ed Belfour, had fallen down while
trying to play a loose puck. As he scrambled to get back, Sydor
minded net while Blues center Mike Eastwood wheeled behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the drama, St. Louis was unable to get a shot.
</P>
<P>
   So while Fuhr blamed himself, his Blues teammates were willing
to shoulder a bit of that load, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant has been winning some hockey games for us, and he's been
making some big saves. Tonight, too,'' Blues center Pierre Turgeon
said. ``He kept us in the game. We had some chances to score, but
we didn't put it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   He, in his mind, played poorly. He said goal No. 1 by Stars
winger Jamie Langenbrunner, a slapper that just trickled between
his legs, was stoppable along with Nieuwendyk's game winner that
sailed under his glove hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just gave him a little too much room,'' Fuhr said of
Nieuwendyk. ``I saw it, but he shot it up in a spot that's hard to
get at. If I'm on my angle like I need to be then he doesn't have
that spot to aim for.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Nieuwendyk: ``Fuhrsy is a good goaltender, and normally I
like to stay away from his glove hand because I know how good it
is. ... But I kind of like taking that kind of shot, too, and I was
just able to get it by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock summed it up best when he
said:,''It was a tough night for goaltenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour struggled as much, but St. Louis failed to finish.
</P>
<P>
   As for Fuhr, Quenneville hardly looked alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr hadn't exactly played stellar hockey to open the Phoenix
series. But in the final three games, when the Blues had to win or
go home, he was spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuhrsy is a competitive guy, and he knows his game pretty
well,'' Quenneville said. ``He'll bounce back from something like
that. He'll be the guy when it counts. That's for sure.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
