<SLUG> BC-SOC-RAPIDS-BURN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO RAPIDS QUENCH BURN IN SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ At the very least, all four of the Burn's home games
this season have been exciting.
</P>
<P>
   And until last night's game against Colorado, the Burn had
boasted a perfect home record to go along with those performances.
But a 2-1 shootout victory by the Colorado Rapids, after an
88th-minute equalizer from Burn forward Jason Kreis, ended that
streak for the Burn. The game also ended Colorado's all-time
winless streak at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn (4-4) still hasn't lost in regulation this season, but
last night's game was the fourth shootout loss. That didn't take
the sting out of having nothing to show for a second-half offensive
upswing that accounted for a team-high 21 total shots to offset a
sluggish start for the Burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really becoming way too much a part of the game for me,''
Burn coach Dave Dir said after the shootout. ``We played 90
minutes, and all of the strategy goes into who's taking the kicks.
I decided to just put that aside and play for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   That strategy prompted Dir to make three second-half
substitutions for an offensive boost. Two of those were midfielder
Ted Eck _ one of the Burn's most consistent shootout candidates _
and newly acquired forward John Jairo Trellez, another solid
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The third subsitute, forward Dante Washington, benched in the
first half when Trellez made his first Burn start, provided the
most significant punch. With two minutes remaining, Washington had
one of the grittiest plays of the game in assisting Kreis's goal.
He collected a cross from Mark Santel, but was unable to get a shot
off, slotted the ball over Rapids goalkeeper Marcus Hahnemann and
past defender Marcelo Balboa to Kreis, who slammed it into the net
to tie it at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Burn had less luck in finding its scoring touch after
regulation ended. Only midfielder Leonel Alvarez managed a goal off
Hahnemann, who recorded three shootout saves.
</P>
<P>
   Burn goalkeeper Matt Jordan came up big as well, with three
shootout saves of his own. In regulation, however, Jordan was
defenseless against a Colorado set piece _ a perfectly placed
corner kick from Limpar Anders to Paul Bravo for a header into the
net. Including last night's game, three of four regulation goals
against the Burn have come off corner kicks or free kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't disappointed with how I played,'' said Jordan. ``But
as a team we need to get sharper on set pieces. That's really the
only way we've gotten scored on this year. That's something we have
to keep practicing and working on.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
