<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' BELFOUR PROVES HUMAN IN OVERTIME VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ AND MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ed Belfour, almost superhuman for the first five
postseason games, returned to mere mortal status last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars goalie gave up four goals, including three in the
second period. He hadn't allowed more than two in any of the first
five games.
</P>
<P>
   But even on a night when he was human again, Belfour was good
when he needed to be. He shut out the St. Louis Blues in the third
period and didn't allow a goal in overtime, allowing Joe Nieuwendyk
to score the game-winner in the Stars' 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to stay with it and stay positive,'' said Belfour,
who stopped seven shots in the third period and another three in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour entered the game with a 1.18 goals-against average, best
in the NHL postseason.
</P>
<P>
   He had a shutout streak of almost 132 minutes, which he extended
to 150 minutes, 28 seconds by shutting out the Blues for most of
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The streak ended when the Blues' Pavol Demitra scored with 33
seconds remaining in the period. It was a soft goal, one Belfour
saw all the way but still let trickle between his legs and over the
line. Still, he is entitled to the occasional mistake, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   However, that one goal that shouldn't have been opened the
floodgates for the three-goal second period.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour is a temperamental goalie. In the past, mistakes have
unnerved him. But Stars coach Ken Hitchcock wasn't overly concerned
going into the third period and the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it affected Eddie at all,'' he said.
 &LR; subheds:America's funniest videos  &LR; body:Belfour did have a faux
pas in the third period that could have cost the Stars the game. He
strayed from his crease to play a puck, but caught his skate in a
rut on the ice and fell down. The Blues, trying to kill a power
play, had a chance for a shorthanded goal but didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to laugh about that when you win,'' Belfour said.
``Guys were saying that there was a sniper in the crowd.''
 &LR; subheds:Chambers hurt  &LR; body:Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers
injured his knee late in the second period and did not return after
``locking'' ankles with the Blues' Chris Pronger.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-injured Chambers said he couldn't tell how severe the
injury is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, it's a new one for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to be X-rayed today.
</P>
<P>
   Before the injury, Chambers had played 13 minutes and 27
seconds, more than Richard Matvichuk and just 19 seconds fewer than
Sergei Zubov. It was clear the Stars' coaching staff was working
hard to use Chambers, who had been exceptional in the absence of
Derian Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a player where the more \Rtime\S you give him, the better
he plays, and the less he plays, the more he distances himself from
the group,'' Hitchcock said before the game. ``We've got to find a
way to get him in \Rthe game\S as much as possible.''
 &LR; subheds:Hatcher returns  &LR; body:Stars captain Derian Hatcher gave
himself mixed reviews in his first game back after a seven-game
suspension for a hit on Jeremy Roenick that broke the Phoenix
Coyotes forward's jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little hesitant more than anything,'' Hatcher said.
``As the game went on I was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher was credited with four hits _ but only one after the
first period _ as well as a shot and a blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give the guy a break,'' Stars forward Brett Hull
said. ``He's nervous. He doesn't want to come into the lineup and
have things go wrong.''  &LR; subheds:Suspensions served  &LR; body:Stars
winger Pat Verbeek and St. Louis winger Jamal Mayers each sat out
last night's game because of suspensions handed out by the NHL
after slashing incidents in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek, who had just returned after missing seven games with a
knee injury, is expected to return for Game 3. However, its unknown
on what line he will play.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock played Verbeek on a line with Joe Nieuwendyk in
Verbeek's one game back. Hitchcock returned to the second line of
Nieuwendyk, Benoit Hogue and Jamie Langenbrunner last night and
that line clicked for two goals. Hitchcock broke up the line in the
third period, though, as he moved Hogue back to centering the line
of Mike Keane and Grant Marshall.  &LR; subheds:Record sellout  &LR; body:The
Stars played host to 17,001 fans last night, their sixth
consecutive playoff sellout and their 41st consecutive Reunion
Arena sellout _ a record for Reunion Arena. The old record was 40
games, set by the Mavericks in the 1986-87 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have set a total attendance record of 693,225 this
season.
nn
</P>
