<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX     05-09 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK'S OT GOAL WINS FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Call Stars team doctor Dan Cooper the prophet of the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   After Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk had major surgery on the
anterior-cruciate ligaments in both knees last May, Cooper told
Nieuwendyk it would be at least one year before he would completely
recover. A year and one day later, Nieuwendyk appeared to be back
to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars center celebrated the anniversary of the most
debilitating operation of his career one day late last night as he
an assist and two goals, including the overtime game-winner in a
5-4 Stars victory in front of a record sellout crowd of 17,001 at
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it would be one year before I felt any good,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``I feel pretty good tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was actually off by a few weeks. Nieuwendyk has felt good
throughout the playoffs. His performance last night gave him a
team-leading five goals and two assists for seven points in six
games. He's the biggest reason the Stars have won all six of their
playoff games and have a 2-0 series lead on the Blues in the
best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals heading into Game 3
tomorrow in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But if ever the Stars needed a hero in these playoffs, last
night was it. Goalie Ed Belfour had his worst game of the
postseason, allowing four goals on 34 shots, including two-long
distance goals that helped rev up a tired Blues team. The Stars'
defense also had its worst game, despite a strong return by
suspended captain Derian Hatcher. And the Stars' power play
continued to strike out, going 0-for-4 to drop the Stars' NHL-worst
power play to 2-for-33.
</P>
<P>
   But Nieuwendyk wasn't about to let that stand in the way of a
Stars victory. He set up Jamie Langenbrunner with a slick pass for
the first goal of the game at the 7:50 mark of the first period
then gave the Stars new hope with a second-period tying goal after
the Blues had taken a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And he saved his biggest show of heroics for his NHL-leading
third game-winning goal of the playoffs. After being sprung on a
rush by defenseman Sergei Zubov's pass, Nieuwendyk faded to the
right on his off wing and then fired a left-handed snap shot that
buried itself in the far upper corner of the goal at the 8:22 mark
of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just a shot that invigorated the crowd and took the
pressure off his teammates, it also stuck a dagger into a Blues
team that really thought it had stolen Game 2 and taken home ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, it was there for us today,'' Blues captain Chris
Pronger said.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Joel Quenneville added: ``I thought we deserved better. We
had the higher quality chances.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nieuwendyk finished his chances. The overtime shot was a
mirror image of Nieuwendyk's second-period goal and also a mirror
image of a third-period shot he took that caromed off the cross
bar.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk also went 13-11 in the faceoff circle, continued to
play physically in front of the net and continued to be a spark for
a series of wingers who are seeing success on his line. So far,
Langenbrunner, Pat Verbeek Benoit Hogue and Dave Reid have been
benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the line has played very well,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``But Nieuwendyk is the catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Nieuwendyk, who missed all but the first game of
last season's playoffs after wrenching his knee on a hit by San
Jose Sharks defenseman Bryan Marchment, is ``making up for lost
time.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates are simply amazed at his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it is, he's playing unbelievable right now,'' said
Hatcher, who returned from a seven-game suspension to play a
team-high 31 minutes and 39 seconds. ``Whatever reason he's doing
it, he needs to keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Nieuwendyk was the clear leader, he was not without some
help. Langenbrunner had a goal and an assist. Mike Keane and Grant
Marshall brought an intense physical presence, and Zubov chipped in
two assists and was a plus three.
</P>
<P>
   That helped the Stars run off a franchise-record six consecutive
playoff victories and also helped them push their career playoff
record to 105-105. It also helped defeat a Blues team that saw a
one-goal, two-assist performance from injured leader Pierre Turgeon
and a two-goal night for winger Pavol Demitra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everyone that Game 2 was the most important for the
home team, and now we still have home ice advantage,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Even if \Rwe lose the next two games and\S it comes down to
a three-game series, we still have two at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Quenneville added, though, that the Blues are not through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, we've proved we've got a chance against these
guys,'' he said. ``It's not a hopeless situation.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
