<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE RESCUES RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANGELS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The weekend easily could have become an exercise in
bemoaning what was lost. Instead, while Mo Vaughn struggles along
with the rest of the ailing Anaheim Angels, the Red Sox have seized
the opportunity to highlight what is still here and what may be
arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Righthander Juan Pena's coming-out party Saturday afternoon was
almost as sensational as Pedro Martinez's 15-strikeout command
performance the night before. The 21-year-old Dominican rookie, who
grew up not far from Martinez in Santo Domingo before moving to
Miami as a teen, held the Angels to three hits _ including a Vaughn
single _ over six innings, walked one, and struck out eight to
emerge as a 6-1 winner in his big-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not comparing their stuff, but in terms of maturity, he
reminds me of an 18-year-old Doc Gooden,'' said Red Sox bullpen
coach John Cumberland, who last season at Pawtucket taught Pena his
slider and 15 years ago was Gooden's pitching tutor with the Mets.
``They have the same kind of mental toughness. (Pena) has a quiet
cockiness. He's very confident in himself and his ability to pitch
in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena, called up Friday night only because Bret Saberhagen went
on the disabled list and starting only because Tim Wakefield was
needed in the bullpen, became the first Sox pitcher to win his
debut since Vaughn Eshelman beat the Yankees May 2, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, winners of three straight games after losing six of
eight, had a dozen hits, including three apiece by Troy O'Leary and
Jose Offerman, breaking open a 2-1 game with four runs in the sixth
off starter Tim Belcher (1-3).
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary began the surge with a double, Offerman singled home two
runs, and Scott Hatteberg (single), in his first game back from the
disabled list, and John Valentin (double) drove in the other runs.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra extended his hitting streak to 11 games with a
line-drive single off Belcher's shoulder in the second inning and
scored the Sox' first run on a bases-loaded sacrifice fly by Darren
Lewis, back after serving a three-game suspension. O'Leary's
two-out single in the third scored Reggie Jefferson, who had been
hit by a pitch, and gave him a team-best 20 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen Juan pitch, but I'm happy for him _ I know how
hard it is to establish yourself and win that first game,'' said
reliever Derek Lowe, who spelled Pena and breezed through three
scoreless innings of one-hit relief. ``He certainly didn't look
nervous. He came out and threw a lot of first-pitch strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena, who throws a variety of off-speed pitches, including a
split-fingered fastball, curve, and slider, did not allow a hit
until Darin Erstad's two-out double in the third scored Jeff Huson,
who had drawn the Angels' only walk. He set down six more in
succession until Matt Walbeck grounded a two-out single in the
fifth, an inning that ended with Lewis making a nice running catch
of Huson's drive to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's opposite-field single against an overshifted infield
with two out in the sixth was Anaheim's only other hit off Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fabulous,'' Hatteberg said. ``I can't think of one
pitch we'd take back. He threw whatever he wanted. It was fun to
catch because you could use your imagination. He could throw all of
his pitches on different counts. There were no parameters to do
whatever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when Mo came to the plate, he didn't change his game plan
for anybody. He did a great job of not giving in to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Pena so effective, Cumberland said, is his motion.
``He hides the ball very well,'' said the coach. ``It's so hard to
pick him up. He's not overpowering, but he uses his fastball very
effectively to get outs with his breaking stuff. I had no doubts
the kid could go out and do what he did today.''
</P>
<P>
   In two games against the Red Sox this weekend, the Angels have
one run and 10 hits. In their last six games, they've scored just
nine runs and collectively are batting .180 (35 for 194). Vaughn,
who has just resumed playing first base after injuring his ankle in
a fall into the visitors' dugout in his first game as an Angel, is
flailing along with his teammates; he has one single and four
whiffs in eight at-bats here, and is 3 for 19 on the team's trip.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Angels are on the disabled list, including outfielder Tim
Salmon, who led the team in home runs and RBIs until spraining his
left wrist last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everyone we face is Cy Young,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``We're striking out eight times a game. That's
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro Martinez? I can understand that. Pena, no. I don't have
an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   For one afternoon, at least, Pena was the answer for the Sox.
Beyond that, manager Jimy Williams refused to be drawn into making
any future commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We savor today,'' he said. ``Let's enjoy today for what it's
worth. The kid had a great first game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
