<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE WAS NO (PIT) STOPPING SAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
 200-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Jeff Green knew it. Elton Sawyer did, too.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly most everyone in the crowd of 28,000 at New
Hampshire International Speedway for Saturday's NASCAR Busch Series
200 race was well aware Green had the car to beat.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious in the way Green blew past Sawyer on the third
lap and pulled away from the field; in the way he grabbed the lead
back midway through the race after loaning it briefly to Dale
Earnhardt Jr. after a pit stop; and in the way he led 150 of the
race's first 173 laps.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on Green's way to Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer passed up a pit stop when the leaders went in for tires
and gas with 27 laps remaining. Sawyer took the lead from Buckshot
Jones and held off Green down the stretch through a series of
restarts after three late-race caution flags.
</P>
<P>
   For Sawyer, it was his second Busch Series win in 303 career
starts and first since 1994. He won with an average speed of
103.220 miles per hour and collected $45,435.
</P>
<P>
   Green was second and earned $28,875 and Jeff Purvis caught Randy
LaJoie for third place on the last lap. Casey Atwood was fifth
behind LaJoie.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer actually figured he had a third-place car behind Green
and Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, the series points leader in a chase that has
tightened considerably, got caught on the outside with seven laps
to go and ended up in the wall between Turns 3 and 4. Instead of
picking up a top-10 finish, Earnhardt was 34th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff and Junior were quick,'' Sawyer said. ``I led the laps
early and Jeff went by me and he was just gone. They were
incredibly fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But they were no match for Sawyer _ the husband of racer Patty
Moise, who is without a ride this season _ and crew chief Rick
Viers at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer was running 10th when Viers made the call to stay on the
track while Green and Earnhardt and the other leaders pitted for
fresh tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think anyone would stay out,'' Green said. ``I
was kind of surprised. But I needed new tires. And if things had
gone the way we had planned, I probably would have been able to get
to the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were way too many cautions.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Green was unable to get his new tires heated up to
make a good enough run at Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, who finished a career-best fifth in the standings last
year, will take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost with cars that were very dominant and you lead a
bunch of laps,'' he said. ``This one we'll chalk up to maybe we had
a third-place car but we took home the trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   And chalk it up to perseverance, too.
</P>
<P>
   While Sawyer ran well at the start and was in the top three for
the first half of the race, he then ran into a rough spot in his
Lysol Ford.
</P>
<P>
   He missed second gear on a restart on Lap 108 and then drove too
hard into a corner on the same ugly lap and quickly slipped back to
12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have gotten disastrous,'' Sawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't. He battled back and before long was celebrating
his first win in five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt continues to top the Busch Series standings, but his
lead went from 95 points to 19. Earnhardt has 1,482 points, Matt
Kenseth 1,463, and Sawyer 1,453. Green jumps from sixth to fourth
with 1,330 . . . Adam Petty finished 24th after starting 39th and
retained his lead in the Busch rookie standings over Tony Raines,
who was 13th . . . Green, who hasn't had full-time rides the last
couple of seasons and was 32d last week, could not be too
disappointed with his runner-up finish. ``We've been in contention
to win every race this year,'' he said. ``I let us down last week
and we lost a bunch of points. I still feel we're in the hunt to
win this championship and we're still in the hunt to win a bunch of
races before the season is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
