<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENA GETS CAREER OFF GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One game and the kid's already a legend. He's the stuff
of major league mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one-year-old Juan Pena made his major league debut for
the Red Sox Saturday and beat the Anaheim Angels, 6-1, with six
innings of three-hit, one-walk, eight-strikeout pitching.
</P>
<P>
   As Sox debuts go, it was something less than Billy Rohr's
one-hitter against the Yankees in 1967, but it was still pretty
good. And it got even better when the Red Sox told everyone that
Pena worked with the Fort Myers grounds crew last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters went to Pena and asked about raking the infield,
mowing the lawn, and putting the tarp over the diamond. We thought
he might be able to help Joe Mooney between starts. Juan wasn't
having any part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there working on baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He must have done some fine work. The Dominican righty was 8-10
(including a no-hitter) and led the International League with 146
strikeouts last year, but didn't have much of a chance to make the
Boston rotation this spring. He was in the visitor's clubhouse in
Durham, N.C., Thursday when he got the call to The Show. Instead of
hurling against the Durham Bulls Friday night, he was to start
Saturday at Fenway against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a performance. Pena fanned Mo Vaughn (swinging) on
four pitches to complete a 1-2-3 first. He didn't give up a hit
until the third and turned the game over to Derek Lowe after the
Sox made it 6-1 in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a lot of first-pitch strikes,'' said Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``He got his breaking ball over. There was a lot of
deception out there. He showed composure and mound presence. The
kid had a great first game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena doesn't pop the catcher's mitt like his countryman, Pedro
Martinez, but his mixed bag of curves, changeups, and
split-fingered fastballs kept the Angels off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said all along that we had a lot of depth on this staff,''
said proud pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``This is a tribute to our
scouting and our system.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena moved from the Dominican to Miami when he was 16 and was
drafted by the Red Sox in the 27th round of the 1995 June draft
(the month he turned 18). He pitched four seasons of minor league
ball before the Sox invited him to spring training in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen him before,'' admitted Williams. ``I wasn't
sure who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena pitched only seven innings (giving up four hits and no
runs) before he was cut in Florida. He was 3-1 with Pawtucket when
the call came Thursday. Tim Wakefield was in the bullpen, Bret
Saberhagen was bound for the disabled list, and the Sox needed an
emergency starter.
</P>
<P>
   Nice start. Williams would not say what's next for the kid
(``let's savor today''), but he'll be hard to send down after this
performance.
</P>
<P>
   While Pena politely answered questions about his extraordinary
introduction, pitchers and ex-pitchers in the Sox clubhouse
recalled their first appearances in the big leagues:
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen: ``I was in the bullpen and Dick Howser brought me in
to face the Yankees (in 1984). I don't even remember who the hitter
was, but Don Slaught was catching and I threw a curveball which I
thought was a strike but it went back to the backstop because
Slaught had called for a pitchout. So my first pitch in the big
leagues went to the backstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan: ``I had a 1-2-3 inning of relief against Houston. It
was Larry Dierker's no-hitter. I knocked him down with a pitch in
the eighth inning, and all the fans were booing me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Corsi: ``It was in 1988 and I was with the A's in relief in
Milwaukee. Rob Deer, the first batter, hit a double off a hanging
slider. Then I balked. I also had a walk and a strikeout, but I
didn't give up a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield: ``I beat the Cardinals, 3-2, in 1992. It was a
complete game and I struck out 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez: ``I was with the Dodgers and had been in the bullpen
for 12 days and we were losing, 8-0, and we had made seven errors.
They called for John Candelaria but he said, `No, I'm not gonna
pitch.' That's what got me in. I pitched two innings. I did good.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena did even better Saturday. Memo to Globe readers: Learn some
Spanish. If Ramon Martinez comes back and Pena stays around, the
Sox could be working toward baseball's first all-Dominican pitching
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell Juan Pena he worked for the grounds crew. He
wasn't mowing the lawn. He was mowing down the Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 0124EDT &QL; 
