<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHOOT FOR SOMETHING FOR NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Walter Zenga could save neither the
Revolution nor himself Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. Zenga departed midway
through the second half with a strained right groin, and the
Revolution held on for a 0-0 regulation-time tie against the Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution did gain something from the match _ a point
from the shootout, their first at Foxboro Stadium this season. And
they discovered a viable backup to Zenga in Jeff Causey, who kept
the defense organized and allowed the Revolution to coordinate the
attack late in the match.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution have struggled at home, they remained tied
for third place with Tampa Bay with 7 points in seven games. Now,
they face three successive road matches with Zenga questionable,
but they can likely count on the return of players such as John
Harkes from injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 0-0 game is never fun for a forward,'' Revolution striker
Joe-Max Moore said. ``But we can only improve. I'd like to see what
we will be like when we are 100 percent. We could be an exciting
team, but nobody has seen it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution did demonstrate resourcefulness, and they are
fortunate that other teams in the conference are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping to get some 3-point victories and separate
ourselves a little bit,'' Moore said. ``We've done it before on the
road, and that could put us at the top of the standings.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami clogged the midfield and counterattacked with lone striker
Diego Serna. The tactic was effective in the first half, as Serna
was stopped by some shirt-tugging from behind and a controversial
offside call.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution improved their midfield play in the second half,
as Edwin Gorter played his first full game of the season. Gorter
lined a 30-yard blast off the left post in the 85th minute, and
substitute Jamar Beasley threatened on the left side late in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution's best chance might have been a Kris
Kelderman shot that was cleared off the line by John Maessner in
the 11th minute of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, which remained in last place with 5 points in eight
games, absorbed the Revolution's early pressure. And the Revolution
simply did not display the midfield coordination to break down a
resolute and well-organized defense.
</P>
<P>
   An early play typified the Revolution's inability to penetrate
through midfield: Johnny Torres and Mike Burns failed to connect on
a give-and-go at the halfway line, and the Revolution surrendered
possession instead of breaking on what would have been a dangerous
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Fusion threatened as Serna crashed through the
Revolution defense but was pulled down from behind by Brian Dunseth
in the ninth minute. This was the type of foul only the home team
or veteran players are usually allowed. But Dunseth, returning to
his best position in central defense, gained the benefit of the
doubt from referee Bob Sheker.
</P>
<P>
   Serna set up Maessner in the 29th minute, but Zenga saved with
the bottom of his feet. In the 43d minute, Serna sent Nelson Vargas
through, but again Zenga blocked the shot, and Serna sent the
rebound high and wide.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign of Zenga's trouble came early in the second half,
when he scuffed a goal kick, which nearly resulted in a Miami goal,
but Burns recovered to stop Serna in front of the goal. Causey
entered in the 67th minute and soon saved a Vargas shot. He then
deflected a Serna header off a Vargas cross and punched away the
rebound in the 88th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Dos Santos scored the deciding goal in the shootout, the
first shootout victory for the Revolution this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
