<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING CHANCES A RISKY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When it comes to risk-taking, the Bruins will not be
confused with riverboat gamblers. Club Casino this is not.
</P>
<P>
   Their defensive game is a trap. On the attack, they emphasize
methodical puck control, not skate-and-shoot. If all the world is
racing to the craps tables, they're looking for the bingo hall,
where the payout can be huge and the risk mere pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe none of that makes for great tape at 6 and 11, but in 1999
the Bruins are one step closer to the Stanley Cup than they've been
since 1994. From conservatism comes reward.
</P>
<P>
   High-end risk, by the Bruins' definition, was Kyle McLaren
giving up his defensive post in Thursday night's series opener with
the Sabres. As Jason Allison swooped behind the net, McLaren
meandered down from the blue line, anticipating a pass as Allison
turned out from behind the right post.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' said McLaren, ``I thought he was going to
throw it to me sooner. For a second, I didn't know what he was
doing, and I'm thinking, `OK, what am I gonna do now?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He could have done the safest thing of all: Retreat to the blue
line and give up the opportunity. He could have pressed even deeper
in the zone, but that would have increased the chances of Buffalo
breaking out two-on-one or three-on-two.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if that happens,'' mulled McLaren, ``I'm going to get that
look, I'm going to get that stare that we're all familiar with.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the cobalt-piercing glare, with a word or two
tossed in, from coach Pat Burns. Had the puck eluded McLaren, the
Sabres easily might have turned it up ice and cashed in for a 1-1
tie. In that case, McLaren's skate back to the bench would have
been his own dreadful trek up Heartbreak Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching Jason, trying to see if he sees me,'' recalled
McLaren. ``You've got to make that eye contact, hope that you see
each other, and if you don't know . . .''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know, it's probably going to mean trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going for offense there,'' said McLaren. ``I was
kinda out of position, sort of the wrong spot at the wrong time.
Sometimes, if the chance is there, I'll take it. Usually, I'll
circle and go back to the point.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, McLaren stayed put and Allison saw him. In a
flash, the feed came out front and McLaren swatted it toward the
net as he simultaneously made his turn for the blue line. Parked at
the left post, Dmitri Khristich banged McLaren's shot/pass past
Dominik Hasek for the 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The risk won out over reliability.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do that sometimes,'' said Allison. ``There's a
difference between gambling and being stupid. You can gamble if the
chances of it working are 70-30 and not 30-70. A situation like
that, he's got to go. Now, if he's coming in there hoping that I
can get the puck through three of their guys, well then that's not
a good decision. But that play, you have to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will take a 1-0 series lead into Sunday's matinee at
the Vault. For the remainder of the series, much will be made about
the teams' growing hate for each other, the one-on-one
confrontations won and lost, the battle of the goalies, and all the
usual fabric that comes with playoff hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting always draws a lot of attention, because there is more
of it at this time of year and two bodies colliding at high speed
brings out the barbaric best in all of us. No matter how many suits
and ties and bottles of chardonnay we see in the Vault's lower
bowl, some of that old Garden thunder always returns when a Bruin
pastes someone against the boards.
</P>
<P>
   What ultimately wins games, however, is the far more subtle risk
factor, which fits hand in hand with a team's talent and skill
level.
</P>
<P>
   Was there much risk in Guy Lafleur racing down the wing at warp
speed and cranking off those feathery, lethal slappers? Not unless
they were 3 inches off net, banged off the rearboards, and got
turned up ice. Most of the time, as we know, they dotted the top
corners for spectacular goals.
</P>
<P>
   Risk decreases as skill increases. If your team has enough
talent, enough skaters and shooters, then no one much worries about
the defenseman sinking low in the play. Paul Coffey made his share
of mistakes when he played on those great Oilers teams of the '80s,
but they generally got erased in the tidal wave of goals scored by
Mssrs. Gretzky, Messier, Kurri, and Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston's first-round series with Carolina, Don Sweeney scored
a critical goal, also with an uncharacteristic dash (shall we say
``gamble''?) down from the blue line. Burns has his backliners
conditioned to think defense first and foremost, but when
conditions are right, they can jump into the play. He'll save that
stare if the odds are right, even if the results turn out wrong. He
has no choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston defensemen will have to jump up more in this series
than we're accustomed to seeing. Sweeney, McLaren, and Ray Bourque
won't be counted on to join the rush or force the puck, but with
Hasek in net, ultimately the time will come when they'll have to
play the odds, be cautiously aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be gambling, but it's the playoffs, and the time will
come when the chance not taken is the greatest risk of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
