<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-TAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR EXPECTS SHARPER EDGE FROM SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you were to encounter Tim Taylor in street clothes,
he would seem the picture of an English teacher _ intelligent,
soft-spoken, articulate.
</P>
<P>
   If you encounter him on the ice, you are more apt to feel him
before you see him. A quick stab from a stick in your shin, a
secret slash to the ankle, a sneaky maneuver during a faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins' top defensive center talks about most aspects
of pro hockey, he is serious and analytical. When he talks about
getting under the skin of opponents, however, he is almost gleeful.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the 1996-97 Stanley Cup-winning Detroit Red
Wings and learned what it is to go after an opponent with the
ferocity of a jungle cat. Taylor now is doing his best to pester
the always-aggravating Buffalo Sabres in the Eastern Conference
semifinals against Boston, which resume Sunda with Game 2 at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said it was too soon for there to be any
playoff-style hatred between Boston and Buffalo. He believes it
will come, perhaps as soon as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to see a personal battle? Watch Colorado and
Detroit,'' said Burns. ``I don't think we have any personal
battles. It's too early in the series. This is what playoffs are
all about. As the series goes on, as you play more games, the hate
factor comes into effect.''
</P>
<P>
   It took almost no time at all for familiarity to breed contempt
in the Bruins' opening-round series with the Carolina Hurricanes,
less than one period even.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was going to be a tough series but I think the
first 10 minutes of the first game developed the rivalry pretty
quick,'' said Taylor. ``You'd think one or two games and then it
would start, especially teams that don't play each other a whole
bunch. But the chippiness brought the rivalry out.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has had some hard-fought rivalries with other foes when
he was with the Wings. He and then-Chicago defenseman Chris
Chelios, now with Detroit, did big-time battle when they faced each
other in the postseason. He also was fighting tooth and nail with
Colorado's Claude Lemieux, another favorite villain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically everyone who comes across your path in playoff
time,'' said Taylor, suppressing a smile. ``You just try to play as
hard as you can and get away with as much as you can, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that first game against Carolina, I battled with (Keith)
Primeau a little bit. As the series went on and got more fierce,
he'd come at me a little harder. Early in Game 5, he hit me twice
good a couple of times. That just carried on in games as they
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the series progresses, the hits become harder and they
become more intent on you noticing they're there. Early, it's
bumping and hitting to try to get the puck, later it's trying to
put you through the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob DiMaio, Taylor's linemate, said there was a great deal of
emotion early in the Carolina series that lasted throughout. He
expects it to develop with Buffalo, too. He and his teammates
already have seen things that they don't like.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like to hit, bang and crash, same as we do,'' said
DiMaio. ``They're not a fun team to play against and they have a
lot of guys who can get under your skin. A couple guys have taken a
few shots at Ray (Bourque) and that doesn't sit well with guys in
here. You can pick one and they all seem the same as that one. They
all seem to play the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the first game against the Sabres was more of a
feeling-out process, whereas the Carolina series was a dogfight
practically from the opening moment. However, after the last couple
of days, he can sense that things are starting to heat up between
Boston and Buffalo. He said the emotion, the ferocity, the
desperation, and the iron wills of everyone are likely to make for
a long, exhausting series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're standing in the way of what we want and we're standing
in the way of what they want and that's to go on to the next
round,'' he said. ``When someone tries to take that away from you,
you're obviously going to go after them in a good fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
