<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-VAUGHN-BOS     05-09 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRUSTRATION BEDEVILING THIS ANGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Somehow you knew the mood Mo Vaughn would be in. When
he was with the Red Sox, losing hurt him deeply. That hasn't
changed now that he's in the visiting clubhouse at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 6-1 Red Sox victory over the Angels, Vaughn
greeted reporters with the grim face and cliches that always seemed
to get the message across when he played for Boston. He said he is
dealing with ``reality,'' which is to say it is a long season and
he is just starting to get comfortable after missing action because
of an injury sustained in Anaheim's opening game. He said the
Angels must stay ``focused,'' getting the most out of the players
they have until injured veterans Jim Edmonds, Gary DiSarcina, and
Tim Salmon can play regularly.
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughn, coming back to Boston and going 1 for 8 over the
series' first two games _ both Red Sox wins _ has not been the
worst of it. He's more disappointed that the Angels are falling
behind in the American League West and he is not able to stop the
slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big personal thing,'' said Vaughn, perhaps the
most-watched man in Boston this weekend. ``My main concern right
now is the ball club. We've got to do things on a consistent basis
to be successful. This division is so crazy.'' Indeed, Saturday's
loss dropped Anaheim to 13-18 and last place, but no team in the
West is having a good year _ Texas, Oakland, and Seattle all are
hovering around .500.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hasn't allowed the fanfare surrounding his return to
Fenway to change his focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weekend hasn't been a distraction,'' he said.
``Personally, I won't worry about my game too much. I work too
hard; it will flow. Being a part of this team, you have to do some
things to get some positive action going on. That's what we all
have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Vaughn is by no means satisfied with the numbers he's
compiled since coming back from a severely sprained ankle. Vaughn
has hit safely in 12 of his 17 games as an Angel, but he is batting
.258 and in the last five games, all on the road, he is 3 for 19.
The load for a team leader can get heavy, especially on a weekend
in your old hometown. Fortunately for Vaughn, he's been down tough
roads before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew coming in here that I haven't been swinging the bat the
way I wanted,'' said Vaughn. ``But things will come in time. It's
part of the game, and you go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn certainly didn't catch a break in his first post-Sox
appearance at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro Martinez is not a good guy to have to face when you're
coming back,'' he said of Friday night's 0-for-4, two-strikeout
game.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since Vaughn has had to carry so much of
the load. In Boston, he had the help of other veterans and could
lead the younger players by example. But the Angels, without
Edmonds, DiSarcina, and Salmon, have few answers for a Cy Young
pitcher like Martinez. Saturday, they were stymied by a long, lean
rookie named Juan Pena. Vaughn got one of the three hits off the
righthander, but he also struck out twice.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim manager Terry Collins refuses to allow his team to use
injuries as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are supposed to be major leaguers,'' he said.
``Major leaguers make adjustments _ I don't care who they are.
Today I believe I watched about seven (Boston) hits to the opposite
field. I saw guys from the other team making adjustments at home
plate. We're just not doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to (Angels coach) Rod Carew talk about approaches.
He's talking to a wall. We're striking out eight times in a game.
That's ridiculous. Pedro Martinez? I can understand that. Pena,
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn agrees with his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to make adjustments,'' he said. ``A guy like Pena
likes to move the ball away from the plate. You have to go out
there and get the ball where it is pitched. It took me to my third
at-bat to do something different. But that's the key to hitting.
It's not just adjusting game by game or at-bat by at-bat. It should
be pitch by pitch. You have to do something different to make
things happen. By the time we did it, it was much too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
