<DOCNO> NYT19990509.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-OFFERMAN-B     05-09 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERMAN'S A NICE PICKUP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-OFFERMAN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For Jimy Williams, it constituted a speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is what you get,'' the Red Sox manager was saying
after Saturday's 6-1 victory over the Anaheim Angels at Fenway
Park. ``And what we see is someone who is very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally that would be enough for Williams, who tends to keep
his answers economical, if not informational. But in this instance,
Williams liked the subject matter: the success of second baseman
Jose Offerman through the first month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done everything we have asked him to do,'' said Williams
after watching Offerman raise his average to a team-high .368 with
a 3-for-4 afternoon that included two RBIs and a walk. ``We asked
him to DH, to play first, to play second. And he's been productive
in everything we asked of him. He's been nothing but a positive
influence.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which should provide a degree of satisfaction for the Red
Sox, who were met with considerable skepticism when they signed the
30-year-old veteran away from the Kansas City Royals, with a $26
million contract through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman has been the Red Sox' most consistent player. He leads
the team in average, hits, doubles (he leads the league), stolen
bases, total bases, and multihit games. He has had at least one hit
in 25 of the Red Sox' 29 games and has had 14 multihit games.
</P>
<P>
   All of this he has done with the label of ``not being Mo
Vaughn,'' which was stitched to Offerman when he signed as Boston's
marquee free agent acquisition as Vaughn headed west to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to compare myself with him,'' said Offerman,
repeating a mantra he has used since he joined the Red Sox last
Nov. 13. ``Mo Vaughn left. I didn't come here to replace him. I'd
love to have him on my team, there is no question about that. But
he's not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he were surprised to be near the top of the American
League in batting average, Offerman shook his head. ``I'm doing
what I've been doing the past three years,'' he said. ``I'm not
surprised at all. I've been able to get on base. Any time I can do
that, I'm pleased with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He should be. He has been more than advertised, a steady hitter
who can play a variety of a positions for a team that has needed
all the production he has provided.
</P>
<P>
   If there was an extra sense of satisfaction with Vaughn in the
house this weekend, Offerman has not noticed it. ``I'm not out to
prove anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, at least, he proved that he is what the Red Sox said
they wanted when they signed him: a catalyst for offense.
</P>
<P>
   He led off the Boston first with an infield single off starter
Tim Belcher. He added another single in the third and capped his
performance with a two-run single to right in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said,'' said Williams, closing out his Offerman
monologue, ``nothing but positives from the young man. We couldn't
ask for more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
