<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDE CHANCE FOR CREDIBILITY SQUANDERED 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After all of its hype and hoopla about radical change
following the Salt Lake scandal, the International Olympic
Committee is playing into the hands of skeptics who claimed the
Lords of the Rings would never really reform themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The all-outsider ethics panel that was supposed to handle the
remaining Salt Lake payoff cases promptly bounced the two most
delicate (South Korea's Kim Un Yong and Australia's Phil Coles)
back to the IOC's executive board, claiming it had enough to do
drawing up an ethics code. And the IOC 2000 commission, which was
supposed to have two dozen members split between Lords and global
luminaries, has ballooned to 80 _ 44 of them IOC members and
another 10 either international federation presidents or national
Olympic committee members.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're saying is, we only trust people with our own
DNA,'' says John Hancock president (and chief IOC critic) David
D'Alessandro. ``It's all about Olympic cousins. What's happening
here is what usually happens when you marry your cousin. You get
cross-eyed results.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC insists that the reform commission's 26-member executive
board _ half Lords, half outsiders such as former United Nations
secretary-general Boutros Boutros-Ghali, former US Secretary of
State Henry Kissinger, and Nobel laureate Oscar Arias Sanchez _
will have the real power in changing everything from how the IOC is
structured to how Olympic host cities are picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real calls and shaping of things will be done by the
executive board,'' insists vice president Richard Pound of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coles case has created an uproar Down Under, with critics
demanding that he resign from his post on the Sydney organizing
committee board as embarrassing revelations keep popping up. First,
it was Coles getting a Super Bowl junket from the Salt Lake people.
Then he and his ex-wife got $6,000 in jewelry from the Athens
people. Now, Coles is accused not only of funneling his personal
dossiers on fellow IOC members to the Salt Lake bidders but also of
trying to sabotage Melbourne's 1996 bid by giving advice to
Atlanta. ``There are certain people out to get me,'' says Coles,
who vows to soldier on . . . The abrupt departure of US Olympic
Committee business chief John Krimsky after 13 years and the
arrival of International Management Group as marketing hired gun
shows how dire the sponsorship issue has become. The USOC and Salt
Lake Organizing Committee were already running behind schedule
because they couldn't agree on their OPUS partnership deal until
two years ago. Then the payoff scandal stopped them cold; OPUS has
raised only $13 million since last June. Though several deals are
said to be in the pipeline, they're still more than $350 million
short of their goal . . . After nearly five months of rough
headlines, the Salt Lake organizers finally get to release some
balloons Saturday. They'll not only unveil their mascot (which
they'd planned to do in February) but also start the 1,000-day
countdown clock to 2002 . . . After the traditional global search,
SLOC chief Mitt Romney chose former Bain Capital cohort (and fellow
BYU alum) Fraser Bullock to be his chief operating officer.
``Another white male Mormon wasn't first preference,'' Romney
conceded to SLOC's trustees. But given SLOC's battered image and
fiscal woes, Romney wanted a seasoned manager (Bullock now runs a
Utah merger-and-acquisition firm) whom he knew well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging showing so far by the US men's ice hockey team at
the World Championships in Norway. After cruising through the
prelims, the Yanks lost to defending silver medalist Finland by
only a goal and should make the medal round if they beat the
Canadians Sunday. It's already a dramatic upswing from last year,
when a patchwork post-Olympic squad finished 12th and had to
survive a relegation tournament to stay in the A pool. The roster,
the usual blend of non-playoff NHLers, European clubbers, and
collegians, includes former Bruin Ted Donato, Boston College's
Brian Gionta and Mike Mottau, and Eagle alum David Emma plus Boston
University product Scott Lachance . . . This from the Twilight
Zone: Whose face appears on the Canadian media guide for the World
Championships? Steve Chiasson, the Carolina defenseman who died in
a car crash hours after the Hurricanes were ousted by the Bruins
last week. Chiasson played for Team Canada last year . . . Pleasant
opportunity to mingle with New England Olympians over cocktails and
hors d'oeuvres at Wednesday evening's ``Gathering of Olympians'' in
Weston. The event at Regis College's fine arts center (6-9 p.m.) is
open to the public, and tickets ($25, partially tax-deductible)
will be available at the door . . . First US team for next year's
Olympics will be chosen next month when synchronized swimming holds
its trials. Odds-on favorites in duet (there's no solo event) are
Anna Kozlova, who wore a nose clip for the Unified Team (ex-USSR)
in 1992, and Tuesday Middaugh. Banned from the trials is Bill May,
who woulda been a contendah with partner Kristina Lum if he hadn't
been born male. FINA, the international federation, still insists
synchro is for women only . . . Looks as though women's bobsledding
and skeleton sledding (i.e. headfirst luge) for both genders will
be added to the 2002 Winter Games program in June. The
international federation has given thumbs-up and SLOC agrees. All
that remains is for the IOC to go along.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inspiring comeback by Boston triathlete Karen Smyers, who made
the US team for this summer's Pan American Games after two
injury-plagued years. ``This was great for my psyche,'' said the
37-year-old Smyers, who sliced a hamstring in a freak household
accident in 1997, then was hit by a semi truck while biking last
year . . . How far have the US males slipped in beach volleyball
since they went 1-2 in the Atlanta Olympics? The victory by
14th-seeded Ian Clark and Bill Boullianne in the recent Mexican
Open was the first by Americans in 29 international events since
1996 . . . After being ripped by women's soccer fans for not
showing the 1996 Olympic final between the US and China, NBC has
promised to broadcast ``virtually every second'' of every US
women's soccer, basketball, and softball contest from Sydney next
year. Not necessarily in network prime time, of course. Odds are
they'll be on CNBC or MSNBC, but that will still include most
American households . . . Olympic rings for figure skater Kristi
Yamaguchi and hockey player Bret Hedican (now of the Florida
Panthers), who met at the 1992 Winter Games in Albertville. Wedding
date is July of next year . . . Brochures for ticket-and-travel
packages for the Sydney Olympics are now available from Cartan
Tours, the California-based firm that is the official US agent for
the Games. Call 1-800-818-1998 or check www.cartan.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
