<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' BROWN STOPS MARLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown has been good, he just hasn't been
Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, that all changed with an 8-1 victory over the
Florida Marlins that reminded the crowd of 36,595 at Dodger Stadium
just why Brown is on the short list of the game's top pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   He limited the Marlins to three hits and a late-inning run
before giving way to closer Jeff Shaw in a game that was close
until the Dodgers scored six runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In his first six starts, Brown had a 3.32 ERA but was not
dominant. In his last start, he allowed six runs in six innings in
a loss to Philadelphia's Curt Schilling that broke a Dodgers
winning streak at five games.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Brown (3-2) wasn't being mentioned with Schilling,
John Smoltz and Pedro Martinez as baseball's best right-handers.
Even though some might say beating the lowly Marlins should come
with a disclaimer, Brown's name is back on the marquee.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley, the long- struggling catcher, extended his hitting
streak to seven games with a double and two singles. During that
stretch he has raised his average from .141 to .256.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a battery with some charge.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White added three RBI, and if that wasn't enough,
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek had a bases-loaded single that scored
two runs in the eighth inning. Grudzielanek entered the eighth with
just two hits in 33 at-bats with runners in scoring position and
had stranded two runners earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also got a productive night from third baseman
Adrian Beltre, who doubled and scored the first run and drove in
the second. With all the big-name talent on this club, second-year
third baseman Beltre has become one of the most consistent players
on the Dodgers. In his last 24 games, Beltre is 29 for 77 (.377)
</P>
<P>
   The six runs in the eighth came off a Florida relievers Antonio
Alfonseca and Vic Darensbourg.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, it was a pitching duel that featured former
teammates from the 1997 World Series champion Marlins. Florida
starter Livan Hernandez (1-4) allowed two runs and nine hits in
seven innings. He struck out seven and did not walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   But facing a vintage Brown gave the Marlins little chance of
repeating Friday night's late-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were coming off that painful loss, when Marlins
rookie Bruce Aven beat them with a pinch grand slam. Saturday was
exactly the kind of game the Dodgers hired Brown to pitch. One loss
to the lowly Marlins upset the team. Any more would be too many.
</P>
<P>
   Although Luis Castillo opened the game with a base hit, Brown
clearly had his sinking fastball. He retired the next three on
ground balls and got 14 overall in eight innings. He allowed a
one-out opposite-field double to Cliff Floyd with one out in the
fourth but retired the next 10 batters in order.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive out came in the sixth inning when
Castillo rolled a bunt 10 feet beyond home plate. Brown ran it down
and threw an off-balance strike to first for the out. He fell to
ground and rolled in the grass after the play, receiving a huge
ovation from the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
