<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-NCAA-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYU SWEEPS TO TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The final showdown in the NCAA Men's Volleyball
Championship between the nation's top two teams never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a short spell in Game 3, second-ranked and No. 2 seed
Long Beach State barely showed any semblance of staging a serious
attempt to challenge top-ranked Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   What worked for the 49ers back in March, when they took the
Cougars by surprise and stunned them in Provo, Utah, was all but
missing Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This time BYU kept the 49ers out of the match, with 24 team
blocks and overall more aggressive play, to avenge its only loss of
the season, 15-9, 15-7, 15-10, in the national championship match
in front of 8,026 at UCLA's Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the way we wanted it to end,'' team captain Matt Prosser
said. ``The ball just bounced their way tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who concluded their season 22-4, had their lowest
offensive output of the season, hitting .156 and were outblocked by
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't our night tonight,'' Long Beach coach Ray Ratelle
said. ``We didn't do anything particularly good. Everything seemed
to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Tournament most valuable player Ossie Antonetti, who had 22
kills, 13 digs, and six blocks ran around the court hugging the
trophy while as many as 20 BYU fans jumped over the press tables to
join the Cougars in celebration before being toted off.
</P>
<P>
   Antonetti kept the pressure on the 49ers in Game 1 with nine
kills, and Ryan Millar had five of his 15 kills and five of his 13
blocks to help the Cougars win the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach had 13 errors in that game and hit a paltry .129.
</P>
<P>
   It got progressively worse for the 49ers in the second game,
when they matched their number of kills with 14 errors to hit .000.
</P>
<P>
   As he had on other occasions during the season, Ratelle subbed
Neil Mason for Dave McKienzie after the 49ers top hitter committed
an attack error that gave the Cougars a 8-3 edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely want to change things up when things are going
bad,'' said McKienzie, who led the 49ers with 19 kills, but
struggled offensively with a .115 hitting percentage. He set an
NCAA record 58 kills and hit .302 in the five-game winner at BYU
earlier in the season. ``We were hoping to get a momentum change.''
</P>
<P>
   It never came in that game, but it seemed possible in Game 3
when returned energized from a five-minute break and scored the
first seven points. But then BYU woke up from its stupor and made
incremental steps to hold the 49ers and tied the score, 7-7. They
took the 11-10 lead on a kill by Millar and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a matter of time, getting back into it,''
Millar said.
</P>
<P>
   For the 49ers, the match ended the way it pretty much started.
Off cue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, a little out of sync,'' setter Chris Seiffert
said. ``WE just never got a long run going. We hd one good run in
the entire match. We weren't jelling. We didn't put plays together
consistently. It was tough.''
</P>
<P>
   BYU, which leads the nation in hitting, had a .308 attack. The
49ers had 43 hitting errors, twice as many as BYU.
</P>
<P>
   Lambourne had 1 3 kills, 11 digs and six blocks, while Steve
Hinds had 14 kills, only one error, and 12 digs and five blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought for a long time that we had a good team,'' BYU
coach Carl McGown said. ``I think that tonight we had six players
on the court that played every well. There was no one star.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way BYU played tonight, they probably could have beaten us
even if we'd played well,'' Ratelle said.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach's season, however, has been marked by incredible
rallies. In their first match against BYU, they rallied from a
14-12 deficit in the fifth game to upset the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   The comebacks that had saved them in so many other matches,
never happened in this match.
</P>
<P>
   ``As hard as we tried the more things went wrong,'' McKienzie
said. ``Maybe it's not our year, but we worked real hard and we
didn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were seeking the program's second national
championship. Overall, it was a successful season for the 49ers,
who began it ranked seventh in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really disappointing, but realistically this team
achieved more than any team I've ever had,'' Ratelle said, choking
up. ``We hope to now build on this success.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA NOTES: McKienzie and Seiffert made the all-tournament team
along with Millar and Antonetti, the MVP, from BYU, Scott Lane from
Indiana-Purdue Fort Wayne, and Jose Quiones from Penn State. ...
The 49ers will hold their team banquet next Saturday at Papa's
Western BBQ and Saloon in Long Beach. Tickets are $25 for adult and
$15 for children 5-12. To make reservations, call Therese Butler,
(714) 842-9094. Tuesday is the deadline. ... The match will be
replayed on ESPN2 May 13 at 11 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
