<DOCNO> NYT19990509.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9908 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOL-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     05-09 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WASN'T LONG BEACH'S NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Cosby has an old comedy routine in which he plays a
football referee at the coin flip before the Battle of Little Big
Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby flips the coin. General Custer wins, and says ``we will
receive.'' And he did, from the entire Sioux Nation.
</P>
<P>
   That was the way things went for Long Beach State's men's
volleyball team Saturday in the NCAA title game against BYU, and
you'll forgive the 49ers if they don't laugh. It hurts to lose a
national title game in any fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But the perspective that comes from time will allow them to
realize some things are unavoidable. There's no good or proper way
to catch an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   BYU won in three games, 15-9, 15-7 and 15-10, dominating most
every aspect of the game while the 49ers did nothing right, or at
least nothing right with any frequency. If that alone wasn't enough
abuse, the 49ers had to hear the passionately pro-BYU crowd of
8,026 in UCLA's Pauley Pavilion crow and exult. The BYU fans evens
co-opted 49er cheers, intimidating the 49er fans into silence.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Ratelle had nothing but nice things to say about the
Cougars, but he couldn't help but note the match went into a
serious nosedive early and that his team played perhaps its worse
game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were seriously discombobulated (SP?), with wrong
players in the wrong place receiving the wrong pass. ``We were so
out of synch,'' he said. ``They're a great team, but everything
that happened was on our side of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   As the third set began to go in BYU's direction, the 49ers were
reduced to prayer. ``You just desperately try to hang on,'' Ratelle
said, ``hope things turn around, maybe string things out long
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   What the 49ers did best Saturday was take the hit on the chin.
</P>
<P>
   At game's end, one could find Jim Polster clapping his hands in
preparation for the next point, which didn't exist. David
McKienzie, who plays hard and feels deeply, put his hands on his
knees and glared in defiance at the BYU celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Faber couldn't bring himself to believe the match was
over, so he pulled his jersey over his head and kept walking back
to the court, seemingly hoping someone would say there had been a
mistake and the game would keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I knew we would win,'' Faber said. ``That's what
is so frustrating. There's no quit in this team. Even when things
looked worst, we still thought we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like BYU did anything different than they did when the
two teams met during the regular season, the 49ers winning that
match in five games. BYU attacked with 6-8 Ryan Millar in the
middle and All-American Ossie Antonetti and Steve Hinds from the
wings.
</P>
<P>
   Game one turned when BYU scored off three stright blocks. The
49ers self-imolated in the second, with six service errors and
McKienzie trying to overcome the flow with sheer force.
</P>
<P>
   ``As hard as I would try, things just continued to go wrong,''
said McKienzie, who bounced at least three spikes off BYU domes,
one catching Antonetti full in the face and bouncing ten rows up
into the stands. ``At least they go home with some scars.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the 49ers ran off to a 7-0 lead in the third, their
play was still choppy. Once BYU got back into the game, the scent
of the kill was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of solace available to make up for the loss. The
49ers began the season as just one of the many contenders from the
Mountain Pacific Sports Federation, with a young team that lacked
any break out star. They might be the first team in NCAA Final Four
lore without a first-team all-conference selection.
</P>
<P>
   (And before we let BYU slip out of town, something needs to be
noted: They may be only the second team outside the state of
California to win a NCAA volleyball title, but they did it with
nine Californians on their roster. There should be a NCAA rule that
teams have at least one homegrown player. BYU has zero players from
Utah. The closest you get to Utah on this roster is a reserve from
Muskogee, Oklahoma. Plus, I'm willing to bet 80 percent of the BYU
fans were from their zealous SoCal alumni base and were seeing
their first volleyball match.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, this team achieved more than any team I've ever
had,'' said Ratelle, who won a NCAA title in 1992. ``When you look
at all the parts of the season, it was quite a performance.''
</P>
<P>
   And they return all six starters for 2000 and add three new
recruits. The 49ers may begin next season ranked No. 1 in the first
preseason poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it wasn't our year. All I know is that we're all back,''
said McKienzie. ``There were bigger and better teams than us this
year.'' He hit the rewind button. ``Well, there were bigger
teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
