r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     05-09 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN STOPS MARLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown has been good, he just hasn't been
Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, that all changed with an 8-1 victory over the
Florida Marlins that reminded the crowd of 36,595 at Dodger Stadium
just why Brown is on the short list of the game's top pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   He limited the Marlins to three hits and a late-inning run
before giving way to closer Jeff Shaw in a game that was close
until the Dodgers scored six runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   He threw the nasty sinker and overpowering pinpoint fastball
that made the Dodgers lust after him last December. And when it was
over, there were no cartwheels. Brown knows this is why he's here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt outstanding tonight,'' he said. ``I moved the ball well
inside and out.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first six starts, Brown had a 3.32 ERA but was not
dominant. In his last outing, he allowed six runs in a loss to
Philadelphia's Curt Schilling that broke a Dodgers winning streak
at five games.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Brown (3-2) wasn't being mentioned with Schilling,
John Smoltz and Pedro Martinez as baseball's best right-handers.
Every time his name came up, so did his record $105 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for him because I think a lot of the time he feels the
weight of the world is on his shoulders,'' manager Davey Johnson
said. ``He certainly is strong enough to handle it. He gave us a
great pitching performance tonight. He's been upset with himself
because he's been missing spots, but I haven't seen much to
complain about. Kevin thinks he has to do it all. He doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though some might say beating the lowly Marlins should come
with a disclaimer, Brown's name is back on the marquee.
</P>
<P>
   So is Todd Hundley's. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers scored only two runs until the eighth,
long-struggling catcher Hundley extended his hitting streak to
seven games with a double and two singles. During that stretch, he
has raised his average from .141 to .256.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a battery with some charge.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White added three RBI, and if that wasn't enough,
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek had a bases-loaded single that scored
two runs in the eighth. Grudzielanek entered the inning with just
two hits in 33 at-bats with runners in scoring position and had
stranded two runners earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also got a productive night from third baseman
Adrian Beltre, who doubled and scored the first run and drove in
the second. With all the big-name talent on this club, Beltre, the
second-year third baseman, has become one of the most consistent
players on the Dodgers. In his last 24 games, Beltre is 29 for 77
(.377)
</P>
<P>
   The six runs in the eighth came off Florida relievers Antonio
Alfonseca and Vic Darensbourg.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, it was a pitching duel that featured former
teammates from the 1997 World Series champion Marlins. Florida
starter Livan Hernandez (1-4) allowed two runs and nine hits in
seven innings. He struck out seven and did not walk a batter. But
facing a vintage Brown gave the Marlins little chance of repeating
Friday night's late-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched good today, all my pitches were working,'' Hernandez
said. ``I went pitch for pitch with Kevin Brown, but unfortunately
he is the best pitcher in the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were coming off that painful loss when Marlins
rookie Bruce Aven beat them with a pinch grand slam. Saturday was
just the kind of game the Dodgers hired Brown to pitch. In the
eighth, he blew away Aven, making him look more like a guy who has
played in 24 big-league games.
</P>
<P>
   Although Luis Castillo opened the game with a base hit, Brown
clearly had command of his sinking fastball. He retired the next
three on ground balls and got 14 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who did not walk a batter, allowed a one-out
opposite-field double to Cliff Floyd with one out in the fourth but
retired the next 10 batters in order.
</P>
<P>
   He left after eight innings for pinch-hitter Dave Hansen. Brown
had made 106 pitches, but 21 came in the eighth inning when Derrek
Lee tripled and scored on a ground out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hadn't made those pitches, I'm sure he would have stayed
in,'' pitching coach Charlie Hough said. ``To me he has thrown this
hard all season. But tonight his control was great. That was the
difference. That was the real Kevin Brown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
