<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY - ATLANTA _ When will it end? This week, a judge
overseeing the JonBenet Ramseygrand jury struck down a request for
television cameras in any initial courtroom proceedings, saying no
indictment was imminent. But that was just the latest in a series
of no comments and mixed signals regarding the conclusion of the
grand jury's work. Those believing the grand jury is wrapping up
note that the group has gone to meeting once instead of twice a
week, and that the jury alternates have been sent home. Also, the
district attorney from a neighboring county, who lent a prosecutor
to the grand jury, said he has reason to believe he'll be getting
the guy back by the month's end. But speculation continues to
swirl, especially considering that the grand jury was recently
extended for up to six months. Meanwhile, friends of the Ramseys
say they are taking it all in stride, and remain confident in their
innocence. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PRAYER _ COLORADO SPRINGS. Colo. _ This parched mountain valley
at the foot of Pikes Peak is the new epicenter of American power
evangelism. At its core is an unprecedented urgency about prayer.
It radiates from dozens of Christian ministries such as the
conservative Focus on the Family, major promoters of the National
Day of Prayer, as well as the newly opened World Prayer Center,
Intercessors International and the Promise Keepers, farther south
in Boulder. As the millennium comes to a close, their message has
penetrated sanctuaries throughout the country, including churches
in the Miami Valley. (Lyles, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-PREVIEW _ NEW YORK _ A report from the preview of what
to expect when you see ``The Phantom Menace,'' something that stops
short of a review, but which hints at the movie's success or
failure. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   The following stories originally moved for Sun. May 9, have been
re-sent for those
</P>
<P>
   Cox papers that did not use them :
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CASUALTIES-0510 _ SPANGDAHLEM, Germany _ Like no other
major conflict in history, the NATO air war against Yugoslavia is
being fought to save lives and combat repression. With
humanitarian, not strategic, goals at its core, the mission is
perilously undermined every time an allied bomb kills or injures
civilians, as has happened at least eight times since the bombing
began March 24. The latest such incidents ? inadverdent hits on the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade and a hospital and residential complex
in the Serbian city of Nis _ are precisely the kinds of disasters
that have the potential to galvanize and even inflame global
opinion against the air campaign. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in both International and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-0510 _ KUKES, Albania _ For a week refugee
Filip Kolgjeraj sat every day outside the tent that was his
hospital ward, smoking cigarettes and waiting to get back the use
of hands and feet swollen like a grotesque Popeye caricature. The
43-year-old Kosovar Albanian, who doctors said could not walk when
he arrived, is a candidate to become a witness for war crimes
trials already being planned. Kolgjeraj, however, has disappeared.
Much improved, he walked out of the field hospital of a refugee
camp on Thursday and melted into the tens of thousands of Kosovars
swamping this city and dispersing throughout Albania. The mobility
of the refugee population _ the people who are victims as well as
eyewitnesses to what has transpired in Kosovo _ is one reason
prosecutions will be so tough. The refugees tell their stories and
then they scatter, and no one is keeping track of where they go.
(Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
