<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9995 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-PREVIEW-COX     05-09 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Previewing Star Wars: Along time ago, at a junket far, far
away....
</P>
<P>
   By Chris Garcia
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``We're going to whoop, right?'' said Natalie Portman
to the gangly young man sitting next to her before the lights
dimmed at Saturday night's New York press screening for ``Star
Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman, the 17-year-old actress who plays a young queen in the
feverishly anticipated space epic, was sitting three rows in front
of me, speaking excitedly to her friend, Ahmed Best, the guy who
supplies the squeaky voice for the film's amphibious,
computer-animated sidekick Jar Jar Binks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Best replied emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   And whoop they did. Well, sort of. When the lights went out and
the familiar words ``A long time ago in a galaxy far, far away''
appeared on screen, Portman issued a curt ``Yow!,'' and Best, with
many others at the crowded screening, applauded the way people do
when a band plays their biggest hit in concert. The room's
crescendo of giddy energy was palpable and catching.
</P>
<P>
   It was by far the strangest press preview I have ever attended.
I mean, I've never watched a movie in the company of Howard Stern,
``Phantom'' co-star Samuel L. Jackson, the future Darth Vader
(8-year-old Jake Lloyd) and his Earthling father, let alone Portman
and Best. There were
</P>
<P>
   scads of other important-looking people in attendance, too, but
I couldn't ascertain what their connections were.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, these seeming V.I.P.s weren't part of the press
corps _ they actually had some fashion sense, and weren't wearing
white tennies with slacks.
</P>
<P>
   So Saturday and Sunday was the big ``Star Wars'' press junket
for the national media, where most critics will have seen the movie
when they review it the day of its opening May 19.
</P>
<P>
   They call it a ``junket'' because the studio traditionally
heaves a bunch of cool junk on the attending journalists _
T-shirts, handbags, caps and all manner of non sequitur items
emblazoned with the movie title. (At one junket, no joke, I was
given a switchblade comb.)
</P>
<P>
   I think we were all looking forward to the goodies-blitzkrieg
Twentieth Century Fox would unleash on us, this being ``Star Wars''
and all, which has knocked out the Second Coming for most
anticipated event this millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we got: Two ``Phantom Menace'' posters. That's it.
Believe me, I'm not complaining, but I bet Roger Ebert, who was
sitting next to the goodies suite at the Regency Hotel wearing a
suspicious grin, got at least a Yoda shaving kit.
</P>
<P>
   Invited journalists registered Saturday at the Regency in Uptown
Manhattan. This is where we slept, as well, and where Sunday
interviews were conducted with a portion of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Director-mastermind-bazillionaire George Lucas didn't do
interviews, opting instead for one big press conference, the way
President Clinton does it at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas spoke with candor Sunday morning about the film's critical
prospects and the need for fans to lower their expectations _
private screenings were held last week for theater owners and
specially recruited audiences and the early reaction has been
tinged with disappointment. ``I certainly expect the film not to do
well critically,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in a situation like this, with so much hype, you
can't possibly live up to that,'' he said. ``Some of the fans have
put themselves in an unfortunate situation ... they have these
amazing expectations about the film, which the film can't possibly
meet.''
</P>
<P>
   After a ``cocktail reception'' for the press Saturday evening in
the hotel lobby (the highlight: chilled prawns the size of a
Labrador's tail), we were herded to a pair of tour-style shuttle
buses, the dorky kind with tinted windows. It was raining.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-minute ride through much of chi-chi Uptown ended at the
new United Artists Theater 8 at Union Square on Broadway. That's
right _ a cookie-cutter multiplex, except that in New York stadium
seating is shockingly novel. This is the only theater in Manhattan,
according to a resident source, with stadium seating. Compared to
Austin's stadium seating, the place was itty-bitty, like baby
stadium seating.
</P>
<P>
   After the journalistic throng was nudged through four
checkpoints _ our passes were scanned with ultraviolet light beams,
our hands were stamped, etc. _ we entered the theater and took
seats. That's when I spotted Portman.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny and casual in low-watt mode, she held a small bag of
popcorn and let out a loud ``Ahmed!'' when the lanky,
floppy-hat-wearing actor strolled in. She picked a tooth (pesky
popcorn) with her left index finger. It had a shiny ring on it.
</P>
<P>
   There was Stern, with a small but scary entourage. In came
Jackson, looking slick in a long black leather coat and black
Kangol cap, the kind he wore with such rakish panache in ``Jackie
Brown.'' Little attention was paid the celebrity entrances.
Everyone was playing it cool.
</P>
<P>
   Portman to Best: ``The weirdest thing anybody asked me was when
I was signing an autograph and they wanted me to write 'The Force
equals God.' I was like, 'I will not write that!''' She giggled.
</P>
<P>
   Someone from the studio finally spoke into a microphone to
introduce the movie. But not without a bit of advice telling us to
narc on anyone we saw video taping the movie. ``It would be
horrible for the movie to end up on the Internet,'' he said with no
trace of irony.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell how ``Phantom Menace'' played to this
unusual, invited crowd. People clapped and whooped when Liam Neeson
and Ewan McGregor's Jedi warriors doffed hoods to reveal their
faces and when loyal droids R2-D2 and a stripped-down C-3PO
appeared. Portman's first showing was met with modest response
(during the scene, she whispered to a young woman next to her), as
did the ridiculous Jar Jar's. He got fewer laughs than was
obviously intended, probably because most of the audience was over
7.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is frenetic and loud, and bloated with as much
computer-animated critters as ``A Bug's Life.'' Overheard from a
middle-aged woman on my way out: ``I loved it, much to my
amazement.''
</P>
<P>
   During a bathroom run half-way through ``Phantom Menace,'' I
stumbled upon a man and his small child having difficulty
re-entering the theater. Their hands weren't stamped.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you get in?'' asked the doorman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stamped hands? This is Jake!'' yelled the man. He pointed to
Jake Lloyd, the boy who plays Anakin Skywalker, also known as Darth
Vader.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Jake how he liked his film so far. ``Good,'' he chirped.
``How 'bout you?''
</P>
<P>
   In all the noise coming from the screen, I don't think he heard
my response.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman. He
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at cgarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
