<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly. The late supervisor is Sam
Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO spared Belgrade from bombing
overnight Sunday, but said military targets there had not been
taken off the list despite Friday's mistaken attack against the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTELLIGENCE (Washington) _ The administration seeks
answers to intelligence targeting failure in the face of domestic
political reaction to the Chinese embassy attack. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ American diplomats said they were
``hostages'' in their offices, as tens of thousands of furious
demonstrators for the second day pelted embassy buildings with
eggs, stones, paint balloons and chunks of concrete, part of an
angry protest against NATO bombings of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ Through their extended campaign
to portray the United States and NATO as evil aggressors in
Yugoslavia, and now their endorsement of mass demonstrations,
China's leaders may have unleashed forces that will come back to
haunt them. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Podujevo, Serbia) _ Three months ago, Milos Savic
was frantic. He had been stopped at a checkpoint by the Kosovo
Liberation Army close to this northern Kosovo city and dragged out
of his car at gunpoint. The fear took him over, he said, and he
lost nearly 40 pounds. Today, Savic says he's feeling much better,
even as NATO airplanes bomb in the hills to the west. The KLA
checkpoints that began less then a mile from the city center are
gone, pushed back by the Serb offensive. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA-LEADER (Tirana, Albania) _ Hundreds of thousands of
uprooted ethnic Albanians are huddled in woods and fields inside
Kosovo under the protection of Kosovo Liberation Army fighters,
Hashim Thaci, prime minister of the rebel provisional government
said in a telephone interview Sunday from inside the embattled
province. `'The food supply is running very low, the medical care
is minimal and hygenic conditions are very bad,'' Thaci said. ``We
have the first signs of epidemics of various diseases among the
children.'' By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BULGARIA (Sofia, Bulgaria) _ On the political effects of
the Kosovo conflict. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BRITAIN (London) _ On Tony Blair and the war. By Warren
Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-VETS (MOSCOW) _ Russia lost as many as 27 million
people in World War II, and even a half-century later, the nation
honors its war veterans to a degree unimaginable in the United
States. Sunday's Victory Day celebration drew tens of thousands,
but the conflict in Yugoslavia seemed almost a subtext, popping up
in sermons, speeches and demonstrations. ``The Americans who fought
in the war must be ashamed today,'' said Victor Chumakov, 73, a
fighter pilot-turned-sniper in what Russians call the Great
Patriotic War. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL NEWS: &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-U.S.-CHINA-SPYING (Washington) _ A 1997 case involving
a Taiwanese-American scientist working on a classified Pentagon
project demonstrates that the U.S. government knew that China
successfully engaged in espionage during President Clinton's second
term. By Jeff Gerth and James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Soweto) _ In a country with a jobless rate
that may be as high as 40 percent and a crime rate that includes
140 murders or attempted murders a day, unemployment and safety are
the issues that top the agenda for most South Africans. But with
only four weeks to go before this country's second post apartheid
elections, corruption is emerging as a key issue too. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-ISRAELI-EMBASSY (Bueno Aires) _ In a new twist in the
investigation of the 1992 bombing of the Israeli embassy that left
29 people dead, a tape recording of a police radio call has
suddenly emerged suggesting that officials purposely removed guards
from the facility three minutes before the blast. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-JOURNALIST (New Delhi) _ A prominent Pakistani
journalist who has been harshly critical of the government has been
detained and is being held in an unknown location. His wife said
Sunday that police dragged him from his bedroom, shoeless and
without his eyeglasses, early Saturday morning. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli and Palestinian
officials hold talks to avoid a showdown over orders to close
Palestinian offices in east Jerusalem by early evening. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ROMANIA (Bucharest) _ John Paul II's three-day visit to
Bucharest, which ended Sunday, is the first papal trip to a
predominantly Orthodox country in more than a 1,000 years, a bold
mission to mend the breach between the Eastern and Western branches
of Christianity. But for many Romanians, the visit was more than an
ecumenical milestone. It was also an opportunity to bask in rare
international attention and make its case to the West that Romania
belongs in Europe. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PENSIONERS (Ludony, Russia) _ Aleksandra Varfolomeyeva, a
vivacious 75-year-old who spent her working life on the local
collective farm, long ago stopped trying to figure out when she
will get her government pension of 400 rubles a month. As she sees
it, retrieving a pension from the backlog that has piled up is sort
of like a lottery. Either your number comes up, or it doesn't. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VIOLENCE-CONFERENCE (Washington) _ In a search for a
meaningful public response to yet another outbreak of schoolhouse
violence, President Clinton will convene a White House meeting on
Monday to address the causes of violence by teenagers. But behind
the White House summit is the president's fabled political realism
and a desire not to alienate two powerful groups with broad
political influence and very deep pockets: the NRA and Hollywood.
By John M. Broder and Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-POLITICS (Seattle) _ While presidential candidates once
seemed to look mostly to Wall Street in their corporate
fund-raising pleas, the technology industry has emerged as an early
battleground for cash. And while the industry long prided itself on
its libertarian streak and almost dismissive attitude toward
whatever was happening in Washington, D.C., it is now contending
with so many major issues requiring federal attention that its
executives are responding to the candidates' appeals. By Sam Howe
Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-PRESCRIPTIONS (Washington) _ Prescription drugs were
not much of an issue when Medicare was created in 1965, and thus
not included as a benefit. But 30 years later medicine has been
transformed by expensive new drugs to treat the ills of old age,
leaving millions of the elderly struggling to pay the bill, and
creating a struggle on Capitol Hill over coverage for outpatient
drugs. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CIVIL-RIGHTS (Washington) _ In a sign of the ways that
both Congress and the leading civil rights groups have changed, the
big civil rights battles now are not about affirmative action or
school choice, but about access to bankruptcy courts and bank
loans. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE-SURGERY (Undated) _ More and more surgery is being done
in doctor's offices, setting off a debate on how to insure
patients' safety outside of the more regulated setting of
hospitals. Although only a handful of states have enacted
legislation on office surgery, virtually all are examining the
issue because of a few widely publicized deaths and injuries. By
Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-GOATS (Denver) _ Denver puts a herd of goats to work to
keep the weeds down in city parks. By Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by William Safire;
details later.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
special section stories will move by 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1 will move at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 7 p.m.
</P>
