 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for Monday,
May 10.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The choice of Don Zimmer _ in his
crimped and cranky condition _ to be the temporary replacement for
Joe Torre as manager of the Yankees should raise a question that is
disturbingly decades-old: To what lengths will a professional
sports team go before it turns to a minority aspirant, if only to
fill in? By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN (New York) _ Ricky Ledee, who was something of
a World Series hero and seemed ready to blossom, instead is off to
a terrible start. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LEFTY-RELIEVERS (Undated) _ Tony Fossas is a left-handed
relief pitcher and, though he is 41 years old, rarely throws above
86 miles per hour and has been with seven major and minor league
teams in the last two years, he is a precious commodity in a
baseball world where lefty relievers are so scarce that even
recycled veterans are valuable. Why are lefties so precious? Mostly
because they are so difficult to find. By Jack Curry. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-MARINERS (New York) _ Seattle at Yankees, 1:35 p.m. By
Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS (Phoenix) _ Mets at Arizona, 4:05 p.m. By
Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Miami) _ On the Knicks-Heat series. By
William Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ITALIAN-OPEN (Rome) _ Venus Williams wins the Italian Open
and makes herself one of the favorites to win the French with an
impressive 6-4, 6-2 victory against Mary Pierce. By Christopher
Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BROWN-NBA (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ The National Basketball
Association this season has suffered through a long, antagonistic
labor fight and glumly weathered the retirement of the matchless
Michael Jordan. Soon, however, it could face truly bad news. Giants
running back Gary Brown has almost run out of things to buy at the
NBA Store in midtown Manhattan. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-PREAKNESS (Baltimore) _ Advance to the Preakness, possibly
focusing on Silverbulletday. By Joseph Durso.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SYDNEY-2000 (Sydney, Australia) _ In the countdown to the
Sydney Olympics _ now fewer than 500 days _ the recent focus has
been more on political problems than progress in preparations.
Sydney is ahead of schedule on construction and organization for
the 2000 Summer Games, which are scheduled to open on Sept. 15. Yet
controversies involving an Australian delegate to the International
Olympic Committee and the planned site on a Pacific bay for the
beach volleyball competition have entangled the local organizers.
By John Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox
News Service, Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
