<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE &LR;  (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-IMAGE-TV (Hollywood) _ The small-screen perspective on Los
Angeles, focusing on the banal, the superficial and the glitzy, has
been beamed out in dozens of television shows over the decades,
reflecting an image of Los Angeles that has acquired the undeniable
patina of truth for many viewers. But the city's image, like
television, is changing. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-ART-LAWSUIT (Paris) _ Embarrassed by persistent rumors that
it collaborated with the Nazi occupiers of wartime France, the
Wildenstein family, the powerful French-Jewish dynasty of
international art dealers, has brought a lawsuit seeking $1 million
in damages against an American writer who repeated some of these
allegations in a recent book. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   PROULOUX-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ A whole set of metaphoric
shovels is part of my tool collection, and for me the research that
underlies the writing is the best part of the scribbling game. The
American Letters series. By Annie Prouloux.
</P>
<P>
   DRAMA-AWARDS (New York) _ ``Parade,'' the financial flop about a
1915 Atlanta lynching, led all contenders in the 1999 Drama Desk
Awards, taking six awards, and ``Wit,'' which was awarded the
Pulitzer Prize for drama last month, was named outstanding play. By
Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   ELEMENTALS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``How do you decide when to
stop looking at something?'' This is the riddle that haunts the
protagonist of ``Crocodile Tears,'' the fine opening story of A.S.
Byatt's kaleidoscopic new collection, ``Elementals.'' By Hilma
Wolitzer.
</P>
<P>
   GUYS-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Our Guys,'' the ABC film, is the
story of the 1989 gang rape in Glen Ridge, N.J., of a mentally
retarded 17-year-old girl. It is also the story of a value system
that reveres and protects good looks and success. By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   FAD-DIET (Undated) _ Just a week after orlistat, a diet pill
developed by Hoffman LaRoche Inc. and sold under the brand name
Xenical, gained regulatory approval for sale in the United States,
all the signs are pointing to an explosion in demand like that last
seen in the fen-phen craze of the mid-1990s. And that has many
health specialists worried about potential abuses and untested drug
combinations, among other things. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-CEO (Undated) _ Meg Whitman, chief executive of the
Internet auction company E-Bay, is one of the new generation of
Internet executives who is bringing conventional corporate bona
fides and consumer product-style marketing to the Web. In the
process, executives like Ms. Whitman are changing the way Web
companies are run _ even as they are developing a new management
style suited to this emergent medium. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TV-ANALYSIS (Undated) _ Has William H. Gates become
the Captain Ahab of the information age? Gates' white whale remains
an elusive digital set-top cable box that his company, Microsoft
Corp., is hoping will re-create the personal computer industry by
blending the PC, the Internet and the television set into a
leviathan living-room entertainment and information machine. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTING-GOODS-INTERNET (Undated) _ Some of the nation's biggest
sporting goods retailers are banding together to back a single
company that will run Internet stores for all of them. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-INTERNET (Undated) _ US West Corp. intends to announce
Monday that it will introduce a new phone developed by Alcatel of
France that includes a color screen, pop-out keyboard and one-touch
access to the World Wide Web. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Free PC, a hatchling from the Idealab
technology incubator in Pasadena, Calif., announced earlier this
year that it would give away PCs and network access to 10,000
households between April and June. To be considered, applicants
agreed to accept continuous on-screen advertising. By Denise
Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Shares in National
Semiconductor Corp. evidently got a lot more attractive last week,
after the company announced it was quitting the personal computer
microprocessor business. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ Claritin is one of the most popular
prescription allergy treatments on the market, with $1.9 billion in
national sales for its maker, Schering-Plough, &UR;  &LR; last year. Because
of its patent protection, Schering-Plough enjoys a monopoly on
crucial chemical compounds in Claritin. The weekly patents column.
By Teresa Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   CHIAT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Jay Chiat, who had been chairman and
chief executive at Chiat/Day, the agency known for campaigns for
advertisers like Apple Computer, Energizer and Nissan, is seeking a
shop to handle the account of Screaming Media, a New York company
in which he holds a minority stake and is temporarily acting as
chief executive. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIA-BUSINESS &LR;  (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   TVHITS-PRODUCER-MEDIA (Undated) _ Brad Gray, the chairman of
Brillstein-Gray Entertainment, has a track record that includes the
television programs ``The Sopranos'' as well as ``Just Shoot Me''
and ``News Radio,'' both on NBC. His company also produces ``The
Steve Harvey Show,'' on Time Warner Inc.'s WB and ``Politically
Incorrect'' for ABC, and it was the production company that created
the groundbreaking series ``The Larry Sanders Show'' for HBO. By
Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDIA (Undated) _ In the last three years,
start-up technology companies have pushed forward with plans to
make electronic books as ubiquitous as mass market paperbacks. But
the culture of technology has collided with the slower-moving book
industry, which is engaged in a tense, early clash over how to
divide up the spoils of an infant business that is still difficult
to picture in scope and potential. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   ADVICE-POPSONG-MEDIA (Undated) _ Never before has such mileage
been milked from 675 words. The Chicago Tribune columnist Mary
Schmich's column on June 1, 1997, dispensing life advice in a mock
graduation speech, has gone on to become a mass E-mail message, a
novelty book, and, now, a hit pop song. By Sreenath Sreenivasan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ The weekly Media Talk column, including
items on new Time-CNN reporters, magazine awards and the Wall
Street Journal's colorful ad campaign.
</P>
