<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Monday, May 10. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Sam Weiss; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO spared Belgrade from bombing
overnight Sunday, but said military targets there had not been
taken off the list despite Friday's mistaken attack against the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ American diplomats said they were
``hostages'' in their offices, as tens of thousands of furious
demonstrators for the second day pelted embassy buildings with
eggs, stones, paint balloons and chunks of concrete, part of an
angry protest against NATO bombings of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ Through their extended campaign
to portray the United States and NATO as evil aggressors in
Yugoslavia, and now their endorsement of mass demonstrations,
China's leaders may have unleashed forces that will come back to
haunt them. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-U.S.-CHINA-SPYING (Washington) _ A 1997 case involving
a Taiwanese-American scientist working on a classified Pentagon
project demonstrates that the U.S. government knew that China
successfully engaged in espionage during President Clinton's second
term. By Jeff Gerth and James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-PRESCRIPTIONS (Washington) _ Prescription drugs were
not much of an issue when Medicare was created in 1965, and thus
not included as a benefit. But 30 years later medicine has been
transformed by expensive new drugs to treat the ills of old age,
leaving millions of the elderly struggling to pay the bill, and
creating a struggle on Capitol Hill over coverage for outpatient
drugs. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CIVIL-RIGHTS (Washington) _ In a sign of the ways that
both Congress and the leading civil rights groups have changed, the
big civil rights battles now are not about affirmative action or
school choice, but about access to bankruptcy courts and bank
loans. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUS-CRASH _ A chartered bus on a Mother's Day gambling excursion
flipped off a highway Sunday morning, killing at least 20 people,
police said. By Anthony Ramirez. (Summary from wires)
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-FAMILY (New York) _ After six terrifying weeks spent
fleeing war at home in Kosovo, Sytkije Deva and her family had
finally arrived at Kennedy International Airport late Saturday
night. When it came time to leave, Mrs. Deva, 67, looking frail and
bewildered, asked her sister Lili Erbeli whether they were going to
a refugee camp next. Mrs. Erbeli took her eldest sister's hand and
broke the good news in rapid-fire Albanian. ``You're coming home
with me,'' she said. Then Mrs. Erbeli, 55, and her husband, Rex,
59, brought home to their 3-bedroom duplex 14 of their Kosovo kin _
undoubtedly among the world's luckiest exiles of war. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FAD-DIET (Undated) _ Just a week after orlistat, a diet pill
developed by Hoffman LaRoche Inc. and sold under the brand name
Xenical, gained regulatory approval for sale in the United States,
all the signs are pointing to an explosion in demand like that last
seen in the fen-phen craze of the mid-1990s. And that has many
health specialists worried about potential abuses and untested drug
combinations, among other things. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-LOST-JOBS (LOS ANGELES) _ Seamstresses, steel workers
and electronics assemblers have all lost jobs as manufacturing
moved from the United States to countries where costs were lower.
Now complaints about similar job losses are coming from workers in
a quintessentially American industry: Hollywood's film and
television studios. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
</TEXT>
