<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI TO UNDERWRITE CBS' COSTS ON HDTV
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Calif., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to jump-start the nation's sluggish
transition to digital television, the Mitsubishi Electric Corp., a
major maker of television sets, has agreed to underwrite CBS' costs
to broadcast most of the network's prime-time schedule in high
definition beginning in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   With this deal, most of the network's regular series, other than
movies or news programs, would be broadcast in the digital,
high-definition format during the 1999-2000 season _ 10 to 15 hours
of programming each week, at a cost to Mitsubishi of about $20,000
to $25,000 an hour. The money is meant to cover the cost of
converting filmed entertainment series, like ``Everybody Loves
Raymond'' and ``Chicago Hope,'' to the HDTV format.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV can bring cinema-quality clarity to pictures viewable on
sets now retailing for $4,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would more than double the amount of HDTV
programming now transmitted by the nation's major
broadcast-television networks. And Mitsubishi hopes that it will
``eliminate the chicken and egg problem bothering the industry,''
said Robert Perry, director of marketing for Mitsubishi, a Japanese
company with a significant manufacturing presence in the United
States. Not incidentally, the company also hopes the arrangement
will help it sell more HDTV sets.
</P>
<P>
   For CBS the deal seems to have few negatives. At virtually no
additional cost to itself, the network can meet its public pledge
to be a leader in high-definition programming. And with the
Mitsubishi pact in hand, said Martin Franks, a senior vice
president at CBS, ``we will turn to movies and sports and specials
and see if we can find manufacturers who want to underwrite that.''
The company also hopes that by being a leader in high-definition
programming, it will get much of the advertising for HDTV sets.
</P>
<P>
   Other networks have quietly received limited subsidies from set
makers like Sony and Matsushita Electric Industrial's Panasonic to
broadcast shows in HDTV. But executives have been reluctant to talk
publicly about those agreements, and no manufacturer has previously
made a deal on this scale.
</P>
<P>
   The transition to digital broadcasting began more than six
months ago, and the National Association of Broadcasters reports
that 66 of the nation's television stations are now broadcasting
programs on their separate, digital channels. Federal rules
required that every ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox station in the 10 largest
cities begin digital broadcasting on May 1. Most began months
earlier, but with a few exceptions the remaining network stations
turned on their digital transmitters last week.
</P>
<P>
   But a digital broadcast does not have to be high definition. So
far, most of the programming on the new channels is digital
versions of the shows being broadcast on the regular, analog
channels _ perhaps manipulated a bit so that the picture looks
somewhat sharper. Such digital programming is far less expensive to
broadcast than true HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, six digital stations are on the air; in Los
Angeles, San Francisco and Boston the number is five. But New York
has only two _ WCBS and WNYW _ and Chicago just one because in both
cities, the broadcasters are having trouble finding places to build
new towers that will hold the digital antennas. Beyond the 10
largest cities, one or more stations in 18 other cities have also
chosen to begin digital broadcasting before they are legally
required to.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, more than half of the nation's TV viewers are in
range of at least one digital station. Still, consumers have been
exceedingly slow to embrace the new technology. The first digital
televisions required for watching the new broadcasts went on sale
almost 10 months ago. But the consumer electronics industry
estimates that fewer than 25,000 people nationwide have bought a
digital television receiver.
</P>
<P>
   One important reason is cost. Manufacturers, generally, are
selling only high-definition sets, the highest quality and most
expensive form of digital television. And the cheapest of these
sets costs more than $4,000, including the price of a digital
receiver, which is often sold separately.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, more than 100,000 Americans spend several thousand
dollars each on a conventional television set with an extra-large
screen and other special features. But retailers report that even
these consumers remain unwilling to buy an HDTV set because there
is so little high-definition programming. Networks, conversely, say
they are reluctant to spend the extra money to produce
high-definition shows that will be watched by an insignificant
number of viewers _ the chicken or egg quandary that Perry of
Mitsubishi noted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Network executives have long said they believe television
manufacturers have the most to gain from widespread acceptance of
high-definition TV; for it is they who will make money from the
sale of all those new HDTV sets. As a result, Franks said, the
network approached several manufacturers with the idea of
underwriting the high-definition broadcasts, ``and Mitsubishi
really stepped up to the plate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, NBC, which is owned by General Electric, is
broadcasting ``The Tonight Show'' in high definition, and Walt
Disney's ABC broadcasts one high-definition movie each week. The
Public Broadcasting System airs a high definition show about once a
month. Fox has shown none.
</P>
<P>
   But even when networks air a high-definition show, there is no
easy way for a viewer to know it is happening. TV guides do not
delineate the programming on the digital channels. And most of the
time, the networks give no notice that a particular show on a
conventional channel is also available in high-definition format on
the digital channel.
</P>
<P>
   Under the CBS-Mitsubishi deal, not only would the amount of
high-definition programming increase, but an on-screen message
would appear at the start of each of these programs, on both the
regular channel and the new digital channel, saying in effect:
``Brought to you in high definition by CBS and Mitsubishi.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi will spend ``millions of dollars'' on this deal,
Perry said, though he refused to be more specific. But for that,
the company would get a year's worth of publicity on CBS that could
serve to make viewers associate HDTV with Mitsubishi. Last weekend,
the company showed its new line of eight HDTV sets.
</P>
<P>
   All of the CBS programming that Mitsubishi would convert to high
definition will be entertainment series produced in Hollywood on
35-millimeter film, which is the quintessential high-definition
format. But to be shown on television, a program shot on film must
be transferred to videotape. Even as CBS conducts these
conventional film-to-tape transfers, Mitsubishi will pay the
additional production costs of using high-definition transfer
machines, which are now in short supply, and high-definition tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitsubishi contract runs from September 1999 to September
2000. But Franks said, ``I hope Mitsubishi is so thrilled with the
results, and they sell so many of their HDTV sets, that they come
back for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
