<SLUG> BC-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL COMMERCE: AN UPFRONT APPROACH TO INTERNET PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every consumer study on the subject of online privacy has been
unequivocal: People fear being bled by data vampires on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this gnawing contradiction: If consumers are so
fearful of their privacy, why did more than a million people reveal
virtually everything personal, short of their DNA sequences, in
hopes of getting free computers and Internet access?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is more subtle than the polar arguments of either
free-market or privacy advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Free PC, a hatchling from the Idealab technology incubator in
Pasadena, Calif., announced earlier this year that it would give
away PCs and network access to 10,000 households between April and
June. To be considered, applicants agreed to accept continuous
on-screen advertising. They also had to complete an exquisitely
detailed personal survey so that if they were chosen, Free PC could
create their household's custom advertising profile.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, collecting personal information solely to
deliver custom advertising sounds like the epitome of what most
would call data abuse. But what Free PC has started, albeit
clumsily, appears to be precisely the model for handling personal
data that privacy advocates have been championing for years.
</P>
<P>
   And if it succeeds, it may also signal a death rattle for
today's multibillion-dollar industry for personal data.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, no one really cares about privacy; they care
about being surprised,'' said Seth Godin, an online marketer whose
book ``Permission Marketing,'' was just published by Simon &AMP;
Schuster (www.permission.com).
</P>
<P>
   People claim to cherish their privacy, he said, but ``your
credit card company already knows everything about you _ when
you're having an affair or trouble at work, when you're seeing a
bankruptcy counselor _ and this doesn't bother anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   What does bother people, Godin contends, is when the possessors
of such personal information do something unexpected with it. Say,
when e-mail in-boxes suddenly start filling with pitches for cable
descramblers or Viagra-by-mail ads. Or when, the day after closing
the deal on a new home, unsolicited letters from mortgage insurance
and interior design companies start arriving.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite their deep distrust of most companies that
collect data on the Web, a majority of consumers say they are
interested in providing personal data to marketers _ under the
right circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Vanderbilt University analysis of consumer responses,
``Building Consumer Trust in Online Environments: The Case for
Information Privacy'' (www2000.ogsm.vanderbilt.edu/papers.html),
reported that more than 72 percent of Web users would relinquish
their data if they were assured of ``a cooperative relationship
built on trust'' _ specifically, if the sites would provide
statements about how the data were going to be used.
</P>
<P>
   In Godin's lexicon, that cooperation is the essence of
permission marketing, which has three basic components: It is
anticipated, it is personal and it is relevant.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one successful permission-style online promotion,
for H&AMP;R Block, started with banner ads that said, ``Click here if
you want H&AMP;R Block to pay your taxes next year.'' Those who
responded, Godin said, were obviously interested in both the
subject _ taxes _ and the prize.
</P>
<P>
   Then the respondents were asked whether they would participate
in an eight-week e-mail contest. The incentive was that H&AMP;R Block
would pay the winner's taxes for a year. The campaign's response
rate was a remarkable 35 percent, Godin said.
</P>
<P>
   Before being acquired by Yahoo several months ago, Godin's
company, Yoyodyne, created and ran 150 of these permission-style
promotions. He says that the typical response rate for them has
been 10 to 20 percent, compared with about 2 percent for
traditional direct-marketing techniques.
</P>
<P>
   So why haven't more companies embraced the permission model?
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct marketers are scared,'' Godin said. ``The key to their
multibillion-dollar industry is the buying, renting and selling of
mailing lists. Permission marketers know that selling your list
guarantees it becomes worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   And though permission is Free PC's marketing model, Bill Gross,
the company's founder, says he has been shocked by the vehemence
with which privacy advocates have attacked him. ``The issue is not
privacy,'' Gross said. ``It's disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
   Free PC never made any bones about what it would do with the
data, Gross said. It has also agreed to protect information about
its customers rigorously. The privacy policy on Free PC's Web says:
``Rest assured that we will never give out your personal
information to anyone. No one, including our advertisers, will be
able to identify you individually. And we will never sell, trade or
give away your information.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gross described even more fastidious
protections: customer data will be used only within Free PC and not
by any other company affiliated with Idealab. ``We've even said
that our agreement with you is transferable to any potential
acquirer of the company,'' he said, ``so we can't sell the company
to anyone who would potentially change our privacy policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these important provisos, however, is stated on the
company's site (www.free-pc.com), nor does it state whether
advertising partners must match its stringent privacy rules. And
Gross might also want to state the company's intentions for the
data submitted by the million-plus applicants who will not receive
free PCs. (He has not decided, he said.)
</P>
<P>
   Another good idea might be to tell people whether accepting a
free PC means that they subject themselves to a lifetime of e-mail,
or whether Free PC will expunge them from the company's database if
they decide they no longer want the service.
</P>
<P>
   These questions are too serious to leave unanswered. But despite
_ or maybe even because of _ the controversy that Free PC has
generated, the company finally may have forced open the door to a
marketing model that puts control of personal information in the
hands of consumers, and even gives them something in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go to a consumer and say, `I'll pay for your attention,'
that is so much more interesting than an advertiser who can
interrupt your life without you getting any benefit out of it,''
Godin said of Free PC's strategy. ``People calling you at home
during dinner, you can't stop. Billboards on the highway, you can't
stop. But if you don't like their deal, you can stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
