<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALKING HEAD BECOMES A HYBRID, WITH A CNN DEAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, James Carney, a prolific reporter who covers
Washington politics for Time magazine, signed a contract with CNN
and became a multimedia machine.
</P>
<P>
   Carney _ who has worked as a Time reporter for 10 years _ will
be a joint employee of both Time and CNN. He is the first of what
his editors hope will be a new breed of journalist: men and women
who can write and report for print, and write and appear on camera
for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our folks make appearances on CNN,'' James Kelly, the
deputy managing editor of Time, said. ``Jay is a terrific reporter
and terrific writer and he just happens to be very telegenic. We
thought, why not try something like a hybrid print-television
journalist?''
</P>
<P>
   In his new position, Carney, 33, will continue to cover politics
and the Congress for Time, but the energy he has spent in the past
as a talking head on programs like ``Inside Politics,'' ``Hardball
with Chris Matthews'' and ``The McLaughlin Group'' will now be
devoted to reporting long television pieces about politics
exclusively for ``CNN Newsstand.'' Kelly said that Carney got a
raise _ although his pay did not reach the stellar level of the
network news programs, where an annual starting salary of $300,000
is standard for reporters. ( Carney would not say how much he was
being paid.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Time's corporate parent, Time-Warner Inc., acquired CNN in
1995, the network has made vigorous use of Time's reporters, Kelly
said. Time reporters already appear on ``CNN Newsstand'' as unpaid
guests. This is the first time that a Time reporter will be
regularly paid for producing and appearing in CNN pieces, Kelly
said, but others are likely to follow in Carney's footsteps. ``He's
not going to be the only one,'' Kelly said. ``We have very high
hopes for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive producer at ``CNN Newsstand,'' Civia Tamarkin,
said she ``would love to do this with more reporters from Time.
Inc.'' She added that around the CNN offices in Atlanta, Carney is
referred to as ``the journalistic genome project.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans yet for CNN staff members to offer bylined
pieces in Time, as a CNN correspondent, Peter Arnett, and a
producer, April Oliver, did last summer, setting off the Tailwind
scandal. ``But if the opportunity arises, if the person gets into a
place that is difficult for one of our folks to get to, I can
definitely see that,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Carney is lucky enough to have his own personal television
trainer at home; his wife, Claire Shipman, is a White House
correspondent for NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her influence is sobering,'' he said. ``I realize watching her
that there's a big difference between being able to do reasonably
well on a talk show and putting together the different elements of
a television piece.'' He added: ``And in the end who knows? I might
be awful.''
</P>
<P>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   As Awards Cascade, New Yorker Weighs In
</P>
<P>
   It is the oldest trick in the Publicity 101 handbook: Need
press? Give an award. The magazine industry is handing out
statuettes faster than editors can say, ``You like me! You really
like me!''
</P>
<P>
   The congratulatory trend gathered steam in 1996, when GQ
introduced its GQ Men of the Year Awards, a celebrity-laden concert
and awards ceremony that is broadcast live on VH-1, but this year,
the industry is amplifying the honorifics. In April, there was the
Teen People Twenty Teens Who Will Change the World awards luncheon,
at which 20 teen-agers received $1,000 college scholarships. Then
last week, there was the Ladies' Home Journal One Smart Lady
Awards. (This year's one smart lady: Elizabeth Dole.) Later this
month, George magazine will host the Newman's Own George Award, at
which Paul Newman and John F. Kennedy Jr. will present $250,000 to,
as the invitation reads, ``the American company that best
exemplifies good citizenship through philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Vogue magazine will introduce its own awards show,
the Vogue VH-1 Awards. In February 2000, The New Yorker will throw
its hat into the ring: as part of its 75th anniversary celebration,
the magazine will inaugurate The New Yorker Book Awards, begging
the question: Does the world need more than the National Book
Critics Circle Awards, Pulitzer Prizes and National Book Awards?
How many gold-foil stickers can one book jacket carry?
</P>
<P>
   ``All kinds of magazines and newspapers and publications do
things to promote the magazine and at the same time exemplify the
magazine,'' David Remnick, The New Yorker's editor, said. ``We
thought it was perfectly legitimate and appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards, to be judged by panels headed by New Yorker editors,
will be given in five categories _ fiction, nonfiction, poetry,
lifetime achievement and best debut _ and the ceremony will cap a
weekend-long arts celebration The New Yorker is hosting for its
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Remnick said only time will demonstrate the awards' legitimacy.
``The prizes only begin to matter when the prize itself has a
certain integrity and consistency.'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Papers Find a Common Advertising Theme
</P>
<P>
   The Newspaper Association of America may have hired Sergio
Zyman, the former head marketer at Coca-Cola, to lend spark to the
business, but three New York-area dailies are not waiting for
pointers. The Daily News, The Wall Street Journal and The Journal
News, which is published in the city's northern suburbs, have found
a common theme.
</P>
<P>
   Television spots for The Daily News feature a surgical patient,
in need of anesthetic, being offered The New York Times to read. It
works.
</P>
<P>
   Spots for the Gannett Co.'s Journal News show commuters _ one
with The Times, the other The Journal News. ``Do you know the
Rockefellers are granting 88 acres of parkland in Mount Pleasant?''
The Journal News reader asks. ``How would I know?'' comes the
response.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a billboard appeared along the side of the Ford
Center, across 43rd Street from The Times Building. A part of The
Wall Street Journal's new ad campaign, which fits slogans in the
middle of the newspaper's name, the billboard reads: ``The Wall  &UR; we
save the color for the writing &LR;  Street Journal.''
</P>
<P>
   A coincidence? No, said Richard J. Tofel, a vice president of
Dow Jones &AMP; Co., which owns The Journal. ``Times Square is one of
the crossroads of the world and would be an important part of any
outdoor advertising campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be outlandish to think the ad might be aimed at The
Times, which has used color daily for 19 months? ``That would be a
little bit self-absorbed,'' Tofel said.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the billboard, Arthur Sulzberger Jr., the publisher of
The Times, said: ``I say this with a smile. We're delighted The
Wall Street Journal needs to advertise in a square named after The
New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER &QR;
</P>
