<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTANDING THE SQUIRREL IN YOUR COFFEE
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers who have scoffed at character analysis methods reported
recently herein _ indicators being one's choice of salad dressing,
for example, or one's choice of ice cream flavor _ may have been
dieting. Readers seeking lower-calorie truths may find answers in
``Fortune in a Coffee Cup'' (Llewellyn; $9.95), in which the
author,  &UR; Sophia &LR; , describes how to foretell tomorrow by reading
leftover grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The author recommends using ``organic coffee picked by people
who are treated decently,'' to be made in a French press. While the
water is coming to a boil, ``circle the collected cup'' (white is
best), ``boiling water and coffee three times with your left hand,
clockwise. Make the coffee in the press, as usual. And after it is
poured into the cup, add a pinch of grounds. After drinking the
coffee, the consumer/fortune-seeker should turn the cup three times
counterclockwise, leaving the dregs to be read.
</P>
<P>
   Some sample interpretations: If you see a bicycle at the bottom
of the cup, ``you are on the path to obtain your goals''; if you
see a squirrel, ``hard work is not a stranger to you''; any
vegetable in the bottom of the cup ``is a symbol of prosperity''
(unless you were clumsy enough to drop a carrot into it
accidentally).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - At a theatrical fund-raising event in New York last week,
 &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR;  told U.S. negotiator  &UR; Richard Holbrooke  &LR; she
wanted to make a goodwill visit to refugees in Yugoslavia, says the
New York Post. Holbrooke said it was a possibility and took her
phone number.
</P>
