<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTANDING THE SQUIRREL IN YOUR COFFEE
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers who have scoffed at character analysis methods reported
recently herein _ indicators being one's choice of salad dressing,
for example, or one's choice of ice cream flavor _ may have been
dieting. Readers seeking lower-calorie truths may find answers in
``Fortune in a Coffee Cup'' (Llewellyn; $9.95), in which the
author,  &UR; Sophia &LR; , describes how to foretell tomorrow by reading
leftover grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The author recommends using ``organic coffee picked by people
who are treated decently,'' to be made in a French press. While the
water is coming to a boil, ``circle the collected cup'' (white is
best), ``boiling water and coffee three times with your left hand,
clockwise. Make the coffee in the press, as usual. And after it is
poured into the cup, add a pinch of grounds. After drinking the
coffee, the consumer/fortune-seeker should turn the cup three times
counterclockwise, leaving the dregs to be read.
</P>
<P>
   Some sample interpretations: If you see a bicycle at the bottom
of the cup, ``you are on the path to obtain your goals''; if you
see a squirrel, ``hard work is not a stranger to you''; any
vegetable in the bottom of the cup ``is a symbol of prosperity''
(unless you were clumsy enough to drop a carrot into it
accidentally).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - At a theatrical fund-raising event in New York last week,
 &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR;  told U.S. negotiator  &UR; Richard Holbrooke  &LR; she
wanted to make a goodwill visit to refugees in Yugoslavia, says the
New York Post. Holbrooke said it was a possibility and took her
phone number.
</P>
<P>
   - People magazine reports that on his way from Los Angeles to
San Francisco a few weeks ago _ apparently for his appearance at
the Rafael Film Center opening _  &UR; Nick Nolte  &LR; threw a tantrum when
he showed up late at the airport and his first-class seat had been
given away. United Airlines thereupon managed to get his seat back.
A spokesman told People, ``There is a degree of flexibility we have
with all our rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Kevin Kline &LR; , in Canada shooting a Warner Bros. remake of the
1965 movie ``Wild, Wild West,'' is unhappy about stories on movie
Web sites reporting that the movie's special effects have been
problematic, that there have been huge cost overruns, and that
there's no chemistry between co-stars Kline and  &UR; Will Smith &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet,'' he told the Ottawa Citizen, ``is the death of
civilization. ... Now, &LR;  we have all this useless information.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; 's been hanging out in New York with  &UR; Camryn &LR; 
 &UR; Manheim &LR; , star of ``The Practice,'' reports the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   - Paintings in Hitler's private art collection went on display
in Weimar, Germany yesterday, &LR;  as part of an exhibition called
``The Rise and Fall of the Modern.'' The Times of London said his
paintings depict ``muscular peasants who never sweat, village
scenes without a speck of visible mud and above all, young women
who seem to be passing the time, in various states of undress,
waiting for their chance to bear children.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLLOWING UP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Laurie Roberts  &LR; says she recycled her wedding gown by dyeing it
black (and thereafter got divorced), and  &UR; Deborah Agre  &LR; makes the
following suggestion for bridesmaid-dress use: ``If there is a
major earthquake and you can't get home and you have to stay at a
co-worker's house with one or two other co-workers, a really good
way to relieve the stress ... is for all concerned to put on the
hostess' old bridesmaid dresses and wait for the news to come on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore,  &UR; Trauma Flintstone &LR;  recommends the conversion of
bridesmaids' dresses to gowns for drag queens, who particularly
favor ``the use of excessive yardage of taffeta and organza,'' as
well as ``the unnatural cut and design.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally,  &UR; Stosh Wychulus &LR;  points to www.broadpoint.com, wherein
callers can right now subscribe to advertising-infested phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; k2  &LR; WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``If a woman wants style in an office, she should dress simply &LR; 
 &UR; and as well as she can afford. If she has an important position, &LR; 
 &UR; she should be nice to everyone working in the same office, &LR; 
 &UR; including the younger women secretaries. She should have lunch &LR; 
 &UR; with them occasionally, and once a year have a little women's &LR; 
 &UR; `office party' in her apartment. If she becomes private &LR; 
 &UR; secretary to the boss, she must never forget where she &LR; 
 &UR; started.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Brooke Astor &LR; 's advice on manners _ newly minted, it should
be stressed, not a reprint from an antique document _ in the
current issue of Vanity Fair. Astor is 96 years old and a major New
York philanthropist, factors that must have made the editors think
this wisdom was worth sharing.
</P>
</TEXT>
