<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTING-GOODS-INTERN     05-09 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTING-GOODS-INTERNET-ART-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS RETAILERS JOIN TOGETHER TO WIN AT E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the nation's biggest sporting goods retailers are
banding together to back a single company that will run Internet
stores for all of them. It is a novel plan fraught with potential
conflicts. But the retailers hope that by joining forces with some
of their traditional rivals, they will be able to block any of the
Internet-only sporting goods companies, now small, from growing to
dominate all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Like retailers in many industries, the sporting goods chains
have watched with trepidation as Amazon.com &UR;  &LR; captured most of the
online book business and Etoys &UR;  &LR; quickly became the biggest Internet
toy store. And it is hardly consolation, for any but the biggest
retailer, that Barnes &AMP; Noble &UR;  &LR; and Toys ``R'' Us &UR;  &LR; are spending tens
of millions of dollars each to try to replicate their
physical-world leadership in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   These fears led the Athlete's Foot, &UR;  &LR; a national chain of
footwear stores, and three regional sporting goods chains _ Jumbo
Sports, MC Sports and Sports Chalet &UR;  &LR; _ to join the venture. It is
being organized by Global Sports, &UR;  &LR; until now a dealer in surplus
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Global will design and run separate Internet sites for each of
the retailers taking part. But they will use common software,
inventory and shipping operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows us to enter e-commerce without having to build the
back room and all the infrastructure we need,'' said Robert J.
Corliss, the chief executive of the Athlete's Foot. ``We're
confident that Global will be able to pull this thing off better
and in a more timely fashion than if we tried to do it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Few industries have undertaken such joint efforts. One related
approach, however, is being tried by the Wine and Spirits
Wholesalers of America. That trade group recently endorsed a plan
in which orders that are placed on a site called Wineshipper.com
will be routed to a network of local liquor stores.
</P>
<P>
   So far sporting goods have sold modestly on line, and the
biggest players have been chains that already have mail order
operations _ including REI &UR;  &LR; and Venator, the nation's largest
sporting goods retailer, which owns the Eastbay mail order concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global's idea levels the playing field a little bit for those
who aren't set up to run a business like this,'' said John Horan,
the publisher of Sporting Goods Intelligence, a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many competitors looming, from manufacturers like
Nike, &UR;  &LR; which will open a big Internet store in June, to
Internet-only stores like Fogdog.
</P>
<P>
   The Global deal is the brainchild of Michael Rubin, the
25-year-old entrepreneurial prodigy who founded Global Sports.
Rubin started selling skis in his parents' suburban Philadelphia
basement at the age of 13, with $2,500 from bar mitzvah gifts. By
16 he had a chain of ski-gear stores. At 18, he switched to buying
up surplus goods and selling them to retailers. And in recent
years, he started selling shoes, buying up the ailing Ryka and Apex
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was bitten by the Internet bug last fall after seeing
stocks of other companies shoot up when they announced Internet
moves. He considered opening his own online store to sell the
close-out shoes. But he was put off by the business model,
pioneered by Amazon.com, in which companies plan to lose a lot of
money for years as they build their brands. So he concocted this
hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at what was really good about the Web-centric
retailers _ they can act quickly, they can raise unlimited capital,
they can use their stock as compensation and they are not measured
on traditional measures like earnings,'' Rubin said. ``And we
wanted to combine that with what the traditional retailers had:
brands, customers and relationships with vendors so they can get
the best prices and the best products.''
</P>
<P>
   Global will put up all the capital, pay all the expenses and
take all the risk of owning inventory. It will also have the
potential to earn nearly all the profits from the business, if
there are any. It will pay what is in effect a royalty to each
store _ something less than 10 percent of sales under its brand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of expensive Internet advertising deals, Global will
rely mainly on its partners for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every retailer who works with us is obligated to put the Web
site address in every ad, on every billboard, shopping bag even
every register receipt,'' said Michael Golden, the head of Global's
Internet effort.
</P>
<P>
   Global hopes to start the sites for these four retailers and
possibly others this October. To prepare for a surge of investor
interest, Global moved its stock to the Nasdaq market last week.
Its share price has quadrupled since the beginning of the year,
most likely because word of its Internet plans has leaked out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An unusual aspect of this arrangement is that Global will
operate several sites that will appear to consumers to be direct
competitors of each other. Golden said that Global would have
separate teams of people to design and operate each store's site.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the same pair of running shoes could well have a
slightly different price on each of the sites, because Global
intends that the site it runs for each retailer will match the
prices that the chain has in its stores.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little price competition in the sporting goods
business, however, because the big manufacturers discourage deep
discounting. Still, the prospect of joining a group with some of
its biggest rivals has so far kept Modell's Sporting Goods, &UR;  &LR; the
New York area chain, from joining Global's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder when they are working on six or eight accounts, who
will get top priority,'' said Mitchell Modell, the president.
Still, Modell said he was intrigued by the arrangement and might
yet join. ``There are very few ways to get involved in the Internet
where you are guaranteed a return on your investment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
