<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
MICROSOFT LOOKS TO NORTEL IN EARLY TEST FOR NETWORK 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To expand the capacity of its internal data network, Microsoft
has turned, at least tentatively, to Nortel Networks of Canada. The
two companies plan to announce Monday that Microsoft has agreed to
try a new Nortel optical networking technology.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which does not plan to revamp its network until early
next year, wants to take the next six months or so to determine
which communications equipment makers will get the bulk of its
business. But the Microsoft trial is a big vote of confidence in
the optical networking group at Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NATIONAL SEMICONDUCTOR PRAISED &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Shares in National Semiconductor got a lot more attractive last
week after the company announced that it was quitting the personal
computer microprocessor business, saying that fierce price wars
between Intel and Advanced Micro Devices had made the business
unprofitable. Analysts cheered the move as a recognition of the
realities of the marketplace. Market Place.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPLE VS. WINDOWS COMES TO TV
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the history of the personal computer, the truth
is as good as fiction, at least as far as a TV movie is concerned.
``Pirates of Silicon Valley,'' which will be shown on TNT on June
20, seeks to retell how an orphaned Steve Jobs invented Apple
Computer in a suburban garage with his friend Steve Wozniak and how
William H. Gates persuaded IBM to give Microsoft the contract for
the first PC operating system and later developed Windows to
compete with Apple's Macintosh. The role of Jobs went to Noah Wyle,
above; Anthony Michael Hall plays Gates.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U S West to Introduce Web Phone
</P>
<P>
   U S West intends to announce Monday that it will introduce a
phone developed by Alcatel that includes a color screen, pop-out
keyboard and access to the World Wide Web.  &QL; 
CANADA'S LONG-DISTANCE COMPANY WILL INCREASE NETWORK CAPACITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teleglobe, Canada's largest international long-distance phone
company, plans to spend $5 billion over the next five years to
increase the capacity and reach of its network.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPORTS RETAILERS IN WEB VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's biggest sporting goods retailers are
banding together to back a single company that will run Internet
stores for all of them. The retailers hope that by joining forces
with some of their traditional rivals, they will be able to keep
Internet-only sporting goods companies from dominating them.  &QL; 
A NEW MODEL FOR INTERNET PRIVACY
</P>
<P>
   When Free PC announced earlier this year that it would give away
computers and Internet access to 10,000 households, applicants had
to accept continuous on-screen advertising and complete a detailed
survey. Collecting personal information to deliver custom
advertising sounds like data abuse. But Free PC seems to have come
up with a model for handling personal data that privacy advocates
have long championed.  &QL; 
TV DEAL MAKER TRIES AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, Brad Grey, the chairman of
Brillstein-Grey Entertainment, has made deals for 50 percent
interests in his television production company with no fewer than
three separate partners: ABC, Universal and Sony. The changes that
have undone Grey's deal-making are mainly rooted in the volatility
of the television business. What has remained constant is the high
quality of his shows, from ``The Sopranos,'' the most-talked-about
TV show of the season, to the comedy ``Just Shoot Me,'' starring
Laura San Giacomo and Wendie Malick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990509.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBAY-CEO-ART-700(2TAK     05-09 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-CEO-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBAY'S MEG WHITMAN EXPLORES MANAGEMENT, WEB STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a Valley of unexpected millionaires, Meg Whitman is the
unlikeliest of billionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitman recalls the day in November 1997 that a headhunter
urged her to leave her comfortable job promoting Teletubbies at
Hasbro Inc. The proposition: to head up a no-name Silicon Valley
startup that needed a chief executive. Her answer was ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Like legions of graduates coming out of elite business schools
in the late 1970s, Ms. Whitman had taken her Harvard MBA and
slipped quietly into a successful career at a blue-chip consulting
firm. She later moved to corporate America, happy to work for the
likes of Disney and Stride Rite.
</P>
<P>
   So it would take more than Internet stock options in a company
she had never heard of for Ms. Whitman to give up the peaceful life
she enjoyed with her husband and two sons in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   That was until Ms. Whitman visited the cramped San Jose, Calif.,
offices of Ebay Inc., the person-to-person Web auction community
that was already attracting a following so devout it bordered on
the cultish. After a few days being wooed by venture capitalists
and hearing the testimonials of users so addicted they slipped out
of business meetings to monitor their auctions, Ms. Whitman was
hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought something was very right here,'' she said. ``They
had touched a consumer nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitman's ``No'' became ``Yes.'' And 14 months ago, she
packed up her family and moved to California to begin preparing
Ebay for the initial public stock offering that the company's
founder, Pierre M. Omidyar, was already mulling.
</P>
<P>
   Since its $735 million offering last September, the company's
market capitalization has blossomed to $22.1 billion _ the stock
price skyrocketing 1,019 percent. And the 42-year-old Ms. Whitman,
along with a cadre of early investors, has become very rich _ at
least on paper.
</P>
<P>
   But more to the point, she is also one of the new generation of
Internet executives who is bringing conventional corporate bona
fides and consumer product-style marketing to the Web. In the
process, executives like Ms. Whitman are changing the way Web
companies are run _ even as they are developing a new management
style suited to this emergent medium.
</P>
<P>
   With no technology background to speak of, Ms. Whitman leaves
the heavy lifting to the tech experts. But what she does seem to
have are many of the skills that may be necessary if Ebay is to
prove itself more than a hot stock or consumer fad and become an
established brand. In some ways, executives like Ms. Whitman are
becoming to technology what Ray Kroc, the founder of McDonald's,
was to fast food and consumer culture in the early 1960s. In those
days, an executive didn't need to understand the chemistry of
ground beef to deliver a hamburger people wanted. Likewise, today's
Internet executives don't have to be computer geniuses, but
seasoned brand managers who immerse themselves in the culture they
are trying to foster online.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kagle, a partner at the venture firm Benchmark Capital,
an early Ebay investor who hired Ms. Whitman, may put it best: ``I
was looking for a brand builder to help make Ebay a household name.
Understanding technology was not the central ingredient. You have
to get the emotional component of the customer experience in your
gut.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Ebay brand is becoming synonymous with Ms.
Whitman, something she is not entirely comfortable with. A man
moving furniture at Ebay's headquarters last week pointed at her, a
spark of recognition lighting up his face. ``There she is,'' he
shouted. ``My wife said she's seen you on TV. Maybe 10 times.
You're real popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitman smiled and waved at the man. But the grin faded as
she turned away. ``That's what I hate,'' she said. ``I even have
the furniture man noticing me.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention isn't all that surprising, though. Ms. Whitman
campaigns for Ebay as fervently as any candidate on the trail. In
recent weeks she attended a press conference with the governor of
Utah; spoke to reporters at the National Press Club in Washington,
where she also met with congressional leaders to discuss online
privacy, and been interviewed for a handful of upcoming profiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't care,'' she said, commenting on the media
swirl. ``But it is the right thing to do for Ebay.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitman never planned on a Web career. After a summer
selling advertising for her college magazine at Princeton
University, she switched from pre-med studies and graduated with an
economics degree in 1977. She got her MBA from Harvard Business
School two years later, and briefly worked at Procter &AMP; Gamble
before moving to San Francisco in 1981 with her husband, Griffith
R. Harsh IV, who landed a neurosurgery residency at the University
of California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   There, she was hired by the consulting firm Bain &AMP; Co., where
she worked for eight years. But the demands of her husband's career
(they moved to Boston in 1992 when he became director of the brain
tumor program at Massachusetts General Hospital) and the fact that
headhunters called every time a new job surfaced, led to a number
of jobs at several companies.
</P>
<P>
   It was her two years as chief executive of Florists' Transworld
Delivery in Michigan, though, that proved her biggest
disappointment. Ms. Whitman had been hired by the florist-owned
member association in 1995 _ better known as FTD _ to help smooth
its transition to a privately held company. But several key members
opposed the idea, quick decisions were politically impossible and
competition was eroding market share. Conceding defeat, Ms. Whitman
quit in 1997, moved briefly to Hasbro and the next year found
herself at Ebay.
</P>
<P>
   As if to test the new chief's technical mettle, Ebay's Web site
crashed during her first day on the job, crippling trading for
eight hours. ``The No. 1 job at Ebay is keeping the site up,'' she
said, so she assembled a team of senior managers to assess the
site's reliability. As a result, Ebay added enough backup software
and computer servers to increase trading capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But intermittent problems have persisted, and Ms. Whitman has
not hesitated to tap powerful Silicon Valley connections to help
her. ``Last January, we were having short outages _ 10 to 15
minutes,'' she recalled. ``It made everyone here crazy.'' So she
called Scott G. McNealy, chairman of Sun Microsystems Inc., who she
has known for a decade. ``I said, `Scott, I need a nanny for this
system until the baby gets better.' '' Now Sun technicians are on
call 24 hours. But the baby can still be fussy; just last Monday
trading was interrupted for four hours because of a computer
glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Ms. Whitman's job is understanding who uses the auction
service. About a year ago, Ms. Whitman set up a consumer insight
and analysis group to find out. Unlike traditional retail
companies, she said, ``there is no one between us and the
consumer.'' So twice monthly Ebay posts customer surveys on the
site. Among the suggestions that were adopted is ``Ebay Life,'' a
newsletter chock full of feel-good stories _ like the woman who
collects wedding cake decorations, 50 of which she found on Ebay,
or the stay-at-home mom who is an avid Ebay trader at night.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay, at times, can come off as a bit homespun, but that doesn't
concern Ms. Whitman. ``I didn't create this culture, but I want to
maintain it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kagle can attest to that. It was he who prodded her to set up a
feature that customers had been requesting: notification by e-mail
whenever favorite items are up for bid. And everyone is a source of
feedback. Even the architects who redesigned their headquarters
were asked to buy something and report back to Ms. Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Three times a week, Ms. Whitman meets with staff members to
review what competing auction sites have that Ebay does not. Ebay's
recent $260 million acquisition of auction house Butterfield &AMP;
Butterfield was spurred, in part, by the threat of competition, she
said. And Ebay is rushing to expand into untapped regional as well
as foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the sense of urgency that drives her, Ms. Whitman
displays a calming, down-to-earth veneer _ perhaps a result of her
upbringing as the youngest of three children in the comfortably
affluent village of Cold Spring Harbor on Long Island's North
Shore.
</P>
<P>
   Her father was a businessman, her mother a full-time homemaker
with a sense of adventure. Ms. Whitman recalls the summer she was 6
years old when her mother, the three Whitman children and a family
friend with five children of her own, embarked on a three-month
camping trip across Canada to Alaska. Driving for long stretches in
a camper with canvas bunks in the back, the children would
sometimes get antsy and start to squabble. So Ms. Whitman's mother
came up with an unusual solution to tire them out.
</P>
<P>
   She would stop the camper, order the children out on the
deserted Alaskan highway and let them run ahead, creeping behind in
the camper until they were weary. More than once, a passing trucker
would stop to ask if something was wrong. ``You could always hear
the hiss of the air brakes,'' Ms. Whitman recalled. ``We finally
put up a sign on the back of the camper that said, `We're OK'''
</P>
<P>
   And one year, during the family's annual Christmas camping trip
on the island of St. John in the Virgin Islands, her parents were
too late to make a reservation at the usual campground. Undaunted,
the family bivouacked in a toolshed.
</P>
<P>
   That willingness to make do may help explain why Ms. Whitman was
willing recently to move with her husband and children into a
subdivision in Menlo Park that the locals refer to as ``Woodside
training houses,'' because executives there typically aspire
eventually to the exclusive homes in that nearby town. ``We didn't
want to buy a statement house,'' she said (although not buying a
statement house is a statement in itself). They do plan to move
once they have finished remodeling a 3,800-square-foot home they
bought in well-heeled Atherton.
</P>
<P>
   Working for Ebay will be her last job, Ms. Whitman said. Her
stock options _ worth about $1.3 billion as of Friday's closing
price _ vest over four years, and she plans to stay at the company
at least five years. But by then, if she has not delivered, her
options could be worth significantly less or, depending on the
capriciousness of the market, nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   For it is not yet certain whether the new brand-conscious
executive is indeed the blueprint for the future, or simply an
expensive experiment in Internet management. Yahoo and Amazon.com
are already fast on the heels of Ebay hoping to grab the company's
loyal customers for their own. And more are sure to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this constant roar,'' Ms. Whitman said. ``The
challenge is to reorganize your business every three months.'' And
being on the run makes missteps inevitable. ``You will be wrong
sometimes,'' she said. ``That is just going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But uncertainty is a condition with which Ms. Whitman, and any
investors in Internet stocks, for that matter, must learn to live
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has done a great job so far with the stock,'' said Alberto
Vilar, president of Amerindo Investment Advisors, and one of Ebay's
largest shareholders. ``Anyone who wants to pick her off as a
second-rate manager is barking up the wrong tree.''
</P>
<P>
   But though a fan of Ms. Whitman, Vilar sounded the kind of
warning that is an implicit part of being one of today's new Web
chiefs: ``Her board and shareholders are going to lynch her if she
doesn't execute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
