<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      05-09 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Warm and increasingly humid air will be drawn north through the
eastern Plains and Mississippi Valley as southerly winds increase
ahead of developing low pressure in the western Plains. Scattered
thundershowers will be common in the sultry air from the western
Gulf of Mexico coast to the central Missouri River Valley. Some
potent thunderstorms will erupt Monday afternoon as a jet stream
disturbance crosses over eastern Nebraska, Iowa and northern
Missouri. During the late afternoon and evening, a new area of
thunderstorms will gain strength over central parts of Kansas and
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   A pool of chilly air will spread gradually east from the
northern Rockies. As the cool air encounters the warmer air mass
over the Plains, areas of locally heavy rain will occur from
southern Manitoba to the western Dakotas. A mixture of valley rain
showers, intermittent mountain snow and gusty winds from the north
will cover a large part of Montana, Wyoming and the western slopes
of northern Colorado. Elsewhere in the Western states dry weather
will prevail; however, clouds will begin to increase near the
Northwest coast as a warm front approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive high pressure will promote plentiful sunshine in most
of the Northeast. Breezes from the northwest will be gusty at times
over New England where some mountain clouds and sprinkles will
develop.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be warm with ample sunshine in most areas. A
weak disturbance will increase the risk of a few thundershowers
near the coasts of Georgia and southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Shifting Gears
</P>
<P>
   During spring, the atmosphere shifts gears. For most of the
winter, storms move steadily at 30 to 40 mph. The pace is set by
jet stream winds which draw energy from the temperature differences
across the globe. During summer, when thermal contrast is minimal,
weather systems move half as fast. In spring, the jet stream
undergoes an unsteady northward retreat. Often, the jet stream is
as strong as it is in the winter. However, during the week ahead,
the jet stream over much of the East will weaken considerably,
resulting in slow weather changes typical of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Thursday: Moist winds from the south will combine
with a jet stream disturbance to produce some strong thunderstorms
in the western Mississippi Valley. Breezy and cool conditions will
develop over New England while most of the Eastern states are dry
and mild. Cool and showery conditions will follow a cold front as
it move through the Northwest states. The Southwest will be hot
with plenty of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Saturday: Warm air will spread over most of the Eastern
states, although sea breezes will keep parts of the Atlantic
seaboard cool. The Southeast will be very warm and humid with
scattered afternoon thunder. A few thunderstorms will also form in
the warm air over the Ohio Valley and Great Lakes. Most of the
Northwest will be quite cool with scattered showers. The Southwest
will stay dry and very warm.
</P>
</TEXT>
