<HEADLINE>
SKIP THE `HOWDY' AND SAY YES TO HEARTY EUROPEAN FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As long as we were in the neighborhood, we decided to drop in on
Dick.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, historians identify him as Richard the Lion-Hearted
and he no longer lives in Durnstein Castle overlooking the Danube.
But he was imprisoned there in 1192.
</P>
<P>
   The climb to the ruins of Dunstein was straight up and when we
rested for breath, another hiker asked my wife Alice whether we
were Americans. He was German but had once ridden a motorcycle
around America including, he said, Montana. Told that we were both
raised in Montana, he waved and uttered a greeting: ``Howdy!''
</P>
<P>
   We could not spot a McDonald's franchise from the castle ruins.
But that seemed to be one of the few viewpoints in Europe where you
would not glimpse a golden arch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like McDonald's?'' a young lady in Nancy, France, asked
us.
</P>
<P>
   Before we could answer, she said, ``I love McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   Her province was surrounded by vineyards yet she showed no
interest in wine. ``I drink only Coca-Cola,'' she informed us.
</P>
<P>
   At one intersection in Budapest, it was possible to spot signs
identifying Burger King, Wendy's, KFC and McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we headed for Gerbeaud, established in 1858, where fine
pastries are served in a ballroom setting.
</P>
<P>
   We ordered Black Forest Cake and coffee. A Hungarian couple at
the next table daintily picked at a symmetrical pile of tiny cream
puffs that they consumed between slurps of Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we reached the historic community of Bratislava in
Slovakia, we suspected we might finally have outdistanced the
spreading Americanization of Europe. Then we spotted a sign posted
in front of an ancient stone gateway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening soon,'' it promised. ``Montana Grizzly Bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if I stumble across a package of ground beef, I'd much
rather create some European-style meatballs than a row of
quarter-pounders.
</P>
<P>
   Lion-Hearted Meatballs
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef or ground turkey
</P>
<P>
   half-cup cup fresh rye bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 and three-fourths cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 lightly beaten egg
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter teaspoon rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-quarter teaspoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can small onions
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons canola oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup beef stock
</P>
<P>
   3 carrots, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sage
</P>
<P>
   After you have sprinted up to the castle and back, moosh
together in an authentic 14th-century Tupperware bowl the beef or
turkey, bread crumbs, Parmesan cheese, parsley, garlic, egg,
rosemary, one-quarter teaspoon pepper, 1 teaspoon salt and
one-quarter cup red wine. Knead with your hands for 2 minutes, then
form into meatballs, about an inch and a half in diameter. Place on
a plate, cover with plastic wrap and chill at least an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of oil or butter in a large skillet. Stir in
the brown sugar. Toss in the mushrooms and stir-cook over high
heat, until they have released their juices and are turning brown.
Remove to bowl and add the onions, drained.
</P>
<P>
   Brown the meatballs on all sides in the same skillet. Add them
to the mushrooms and onions in the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining 2 tablespoons of butter or oil to the pan.
Stir in one-quarter cup flour and stir-cook 3 minutes. Add the beef
broth and one and one-half cups red wine. Stir until the sauce is
smooth and has begun to thicken. Dump into the pan the carrots,
thyme, sage and 1 teaspoon black pepper. Plunk into the skillet the
meatballs, mushrooms and onions and stir.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the skillet and simmer for an hour. If the sauce isn't as
thick as you would like, remove the lid after 45 minutes of
cooking. Richard the Lion-Hearted preferred his meatballs in a
fairly thin sauce. Duke Leopold V liked his fairly thick. Oops,
there they go again.
</P>
<P>
   This should serve four, with buttered noodles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
