<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-VETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN WORLD WAR II VETERANS NOW ANGRY AT AN OLD ALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Aleksei Vasilenko is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On the 54th anniversary of the Allied victory over the
Nazis, Viktor Chumakov, 73, a fighter-pilot-turned-sniper in what
Russians call the Great Patriotic War, recalled the morning his
division of infantrymen reached the Elbe River in Germany and saw
their American allies on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the Americans, waving and crossing the river on rafts,''
he said. ``We met. We had lots of fun _ singing, dancing, drinking
together. I even remember someone had a Russian accordion. That was
a great time. Everyone was so glad that the war was finally over.''
</P>
<P>
   Chumakov, who transferred to the infantry when the country's
supply of planes ran short, stood grizzled but erect Sunday, one
row of medals across his breast, a second running down the lapel of
his blue uniform. ``The Americans who fought in the war must be
ashamed today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking of the NATO air campaign in Yugoslavia, of
course. So were most of the other veterans interviewed on a
crystalline day at the vast, overwhelming plaza and memorial built
for them a few miles southwest of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia seemed almost a subtext of Sunday's celebration,
popping up in sermons, speeches and demonstrations in Moscow and
elsewhere in the old Soviet empire.
</P>
<P>
   Russia lost as many as 27 million people in World War II, and
even a half-century later the nation honors its war veterans to a
degree unimaginable in the United States. The veterans are rapidly
dying off _ there are an estimated two million in Russia today,
half as many as five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's celebration, like that of every Victory Day, drew
tens of thousands to Moscow's Victory Park memorial and thousands
more to rallies, marches and ceremonies downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The streets were festooned with billboards and banners, most
bearing slogans like ``Glory to the City of Heroes of the War!''
Every veteran clutched a handful of tulips and daffodils given him
_ or her _ by children walking through the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of veterans were dancing in front of the Bolshoi Theater,
and old units had reunions in Culture Park, along the Moscow River.
A parade of 5,000 servicemen in Red Square was dampened somewhat by
the absence _ for lack of money, it appeared _ of the usual
artillery and other military hardware.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslavia and emnity toward the West were almost
unavoidable. At a Communist Party rally near downtown, a large
crowd _ 450,000 by the party's reckoning, 11,000 by that of a local
news radio station _ waved placards bearing the face of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and cheered the slogan
``Solidarity With Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Orthodox Patriarch, Aleksy II, told worshipers that
the flames of war had risen again in southern Europe and must be
smothered before a third world war erupts.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin, swathed in a black overcoat against the
cold, gave a short speech in which he made no mention of
Yugoslavia. ``We must support each other and reliably defend
Russia's security and integrity,'' he said. ``We must do everything
possible to strengthen our army. This is our common duty.''
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, according to Russian press reports, Yeltsin said
the searing experience of World War II should give modern leaders
pause. ``All countries should not forget the main lesson of war,''
he said. ``The rule of power may spark a big fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's remarks were muted compared with those of many
veterans. None saw any parallel between Hitler's massacre of six
million Jews and the killings or expulsions of Kosovo Albanians.
Nor did any draw a distinction between the NATO alliance and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they denounced America in general, and especially
President Clinton, as outlaws and bullies bent on imposing their
will on other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Chumakov, the onetime fighter pilot, angrily asserted that he
now believed old stories that the CIA had orchestrated the breakup
of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   A portly 74-year-old who would identify himself only as Anatoly
refused to talk about his service as an artillery gunner. ``I'm
more interested in Yugoslavia,'' he said. ``Milosevic and the other
things _ that's an internal problem. It doesn't give anyone the
right to bomb a country. A lot of people have died there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame Clinton most of all. The man's an idiot. First he has
a war in Iraq, now one in Europe, all without U.N. permission.
They're outlaws. They don't obey international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly later said he had spent six months in Washington, D.C.,
recently visiting his daughter and her American husband and had
come away unimpressed. He left believing that Americans by nature
``want to command everything _ they're rough and crude.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Vasilenko, 72, a former infantryman, said he had entered
the war as a 16-year-old Cossack cavalryman, fighting Romanians.
The situation was so desperate during the first winter, he said,
that the soldiers were reduced to amputating the frozen legs of
dead Romanians, then warming them over a fire to remove their
boots.
</P>
<P>
   The unit was starving and freezing until shipments of clothing
and food arrived from the United States, under President Franklin
D. &UR;  &LR; Roosevelt's Lend-Lease program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans were good friends,'' he said. ``Roosevelt was a
good man. Now America wants to be the leader of the world. Well,
Russia is a big country as well, and it is developing new missiles.
The military industry is working again. Russia is stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russians don't trust Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
