<HEADLINE>
AS MOM WOULD SAY, `BE NICE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Mother's Day, we say nice things about people. Because that's
what Mom taught.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind ...
</P>
<P>
   - It hasn't taken the Kansas City Council long to figure out
that it's lucky to have Bonnie Sue Cooper on board.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, a mother of three who came to the council after 17 years
as a Republican member of the Missouri House, brings a wealth of
legislative know-how.
</P>
<P>
   That will come in valuable as Kansas City, Mo., continues its
annual battle to get as much out of the General Assembly as St.
Louis does.
</P>
<P>
   She has federal connections, too, through her leadership of the
5,000-member American Legislative Exchange Council in 1987 and
National Order of Women Legislators in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   New Mayor Kay Barnes quickly saw that she had a bird in hand.
She appointed Cooper to head the Legislative Rules and Ethics
Committee, which works to build ties with state and federal
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she was a member of the minority party, Cooper had a
reputation for working well with Democrats to bring home the bacon
for Kansas City. She knows how to cut deals and make compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper already is working with city department heads to get more
grant money flowing to the city. During her time in Jefferson City,
Mo., she noticed that Kansas City often wasn't getting its fair
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is because we weren't asking for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians don't often aspire to move from bigger to smaller
offices, as Cooper did with her move from a state post to a local
one. But with term limits, Cooper had to move out by 2002, and she
liked the idea of overseeing some of the laws she had helped
implement at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   That, and she wanted to spend more time with her four
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   - Doris Haddock is 89 and is walking across America to protest,
of all things, Congress' failure to pass campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite arthritis in her hands and aches in her legs, Haddock, a
great-grandmother of 11, journeys on. Known as Granny D, she began
her journey in Pasadena, Calif., more than three months ago and
hopes to reach Washington by January. She tries to cover 10 miles a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her about the influence of money in the nation's politics
and Haddock uncoils a righteous anger and pounds the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just infuriates me!'' she told The New York Times. ``I feel
we are losing our democracy. The corporations are taking over and
deciding who gets elected.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-April, Haddock logged her 1,000th mile. She has fewer
than 2,000 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Godspeed, Granny D.
</P>
<P>
   - Jim Garner is not a mother. Nor does he have grandchildren.
But in his first year on the job, the minority leader of the Kansas
House made his presence felt in a powerful way.
</P>
<P>
   By wielding his party's 48 votes as a club, Garner was able to
wring significant concessions from Republicans eager to pass a
highway program and other bills.
</P>
<P>
   Among his achievements: creation of a children's trust fund that
will hold money from the settlement of the tobacco lawsuit. Without
the fund, the Legislature might have been tempted to fritter the
money away on other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, concluded Martin Hawver, publisher of Hawver's Capitol
Report, became the most powerful lawmaker in the statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   - U.S. Rep. Roy Blunt, a Republican from southwest Missouri, has
become a power player in just his second term in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Voted the chief deputy whip in January, Blunt is at the table
when the House leadership makes key decisions. He also is one of 10
members of George W. Bush's presidential exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say ``rising star''?
</P>
</TEXT>
