<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN CONTINUE TO COMPETE WITH MOUNTAINS, AND THE ROCKS PREVAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For one month short of 75 years, the mountaineer's body had lain
unmarked, unmolested and remarkably preserved through the eternal
winter on a ledge near the roof of the world.
</P>
<P>
   George Mallory and his young climbing companion, Andrew Irvine,
perished in early June 1924 somewhere below the summit of Mount
Everest. A team member, witnessing their final assault on the peak,
saw them vanish into a mist above their last camp at nearly 27,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would be seen again until, in recent days, an expedition
of American climbers found and identified Mallory's remains.
Irvine's body was not found.
</P>
<P>
   Reports indicated that a fall had cost Mallory a broken leg and
injured shoulder -- fatal injuries in an environment so unforgiving
that even a small setback can spell doom.
</P>
<P>
   The lore of Everest is rich with accounts of ascents that
reached their goal and others that ended in tragedy. So it is
possible to picture Mallory's last hours.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced in that altitude mountaineers call the ``death
zone'' -- an otherworldly region of thin air, brutal cold and
spectral beauty -- he would have understood immediately the meaning
of his hurts. No doubt he would have been concerned for his
climbing colleague, 28 years old and still a student. He would have
been sorry for the grief his own wife and family would soon have to
bear.
</P>
<P>
   Then, being powerless over these matters, he surely must have
composed himself.
</P>
<P>
   As evening deepened and shadow claimed the mountain's face, the
terrible cold would have come on with a force to defeat whatever
protection the outerwear of that day afforded. And sometime in the
frozen darkness of that June night, Mallory would have drifted into
the sleep from which there was no waking.
</P>
<P>
   This is how, from reading and imagining, this flatlander
supposes the last hours would have gone. Knowing is, of course,
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Unknowable, also, is the answer to an enduring historical
question. Might Mallory and Irvine in fact have been the first two
men to surmount Everest, rather than Edmund Hillary and Tenzing
Norgay, who climbed the mountain 29 Junes later, in 1953?
</P>
<P>
   Did calamity overtake them before they reached the summit, only
some 2,200 feet above that last camp? Or is it possible they
completed their ascent, then perished on the way back down?
</P>
<P>
   And if the latter is true, wouldn't it mean that Hillary and his
Sherpa partner received the credit for an achievement that two
other brave men had earlier paid for with their lives?
</P>
<P>
   Fertile area for speculation, no doubt, but leading only to a
further question.
</P>
<P>
   What conceivable difference could it make?
</P>
<P>
   If one can believe what mountaineers say about their life's
passion, it isn't competition that draws them to the dangerous
heights, in calculated acceptance of mortal risk. At least not
competition with other climbers.
</P>
<P>
   No, they say, it's the chance for measuring the strength of
their sinews, their mastery of fear, the largeness of their hearts
against an adversary so much grander than themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory wouldn't have thought it very important who got the
credit for being first, his grandson said. ``He climbed for the joy
of climbing.''
</P>
<P>
   And so must all the best of them. They have their time, then
pass in their turn. And after everything, there remain the
mountains -- beautiful and wicked and unchanged -- caring nothing
for records, and never really conquered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
