<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIAT-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-09 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIAT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: AN AD MAN IN SEARCH OF AN AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., N.J.)  (jw) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A co-founder of one of America's best-known agencies now wants
to hire an agency. And it's not likely to be the agency he once
headed.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Chiat, who had been chairman and chief executive at
Chiat/Day, the agency known for campaigns for advertisers like
Apple Computer, Energizer and Nissan, is seeking a shop to handle
the account of Screaming Media (www.screamingmedia.net), a New York
company in which he holds a minority stake and is temporarily
acting as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Screaming Media, formerly named Interactive Connection, is in a
business known as content streaming, collecting and distributing to
Web sites news articles on topics such as technology, health and
business. The content is meant as an incentive for computer users
to visit the sites more frequently and spend more time once they
are there.
</P>
<P>
   Chiat is not automatically awarding the assignment, with
billings estimated at $3 million to $5 million, to his former
agency, now named TBWA/Chiat/Day, without a review. Rather, he
plans to hold what could be called an online audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do our agency search on the Internet,'' Chiat,
67, said last week in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies can go to our Web site and send us e-mail on why they
think they should be our agency,'' he added. ``And they can put the
pitch up on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they present a compelling story,'' he added, ``we'll hire
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if TBWA/Chiat/Day would participate in the ``Chiathon'' _
the nickname for the review coined by Jim Pavoldi, a salesman at
Screaming Media _ Chiat replied, ``They're certainly invited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have total respect for the agency,'' he said. ``They're a
great agency. But I want to see if agencies out there understand
what we're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiat said that he would ``probably be a minor part of the
decision-making'' because of his former ties to TBWA/Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Chiat is involved or not, TBWA/Chiat/Day is bowing out
of the review gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay and I had dinner the other night,'' said Bob Kuperman,
president and chief executive for the Americas at TBWA Worldwide in
New York. ``And I told him he'd be the worst client in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived with the guy for 10 years,'' Kuperman said, laughing.
``I have to have him as a client now?''
</P>
<P>
   Chiat founded Chiat/Day in 1968 with Guy Day, as they merged
Faust/Day with Jay Chiat &AMP; Associates in Los Angeles. Chiat/Day's
bold risk-taking for accounts like Apple (the ``1984'' commercial)
and Energizer (E.B. the battery bunny) earned the agency a
reputation for creative prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Chiat left Chiat/Day after it was sold to Omnicom Group in 1995
and merged with domestic operations of TBWA International to form
the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of TBWA Worldwide. Chiat has been serving
as a consultant to Omnicom as he is paid out his share of the
purchase price for Chiat/Day over several years.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign for Screaming Media would have two purposes, said
Alan Ellman, 36, president, who joined Chiat for the interview.
</P>
<P>
   One would be to attract additional Web sites as clients as well
as additional sources of news articles for the content the company
provides.
</P>
<P>
   The other would be to promote a feature now being tested that
Ellman termed ``contextual commerce,'' which ``utilizes interest in
editorial to sell product.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiat explained: ``We have software programs that allow us to
embed applets in editorial. So you can click on a word and a window
comes up with an on-site link.'' For instance, a computer user
reading a book review could click on the title or the author's
name, bringing up a Web site like Barnesandnoble.com where the book
could be ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web sites split the revenue with us,'' Chiat said, ``and
the content provider.''
</P>
<P>
   These programs are now being tested.
</P>
<P>
   Chiat and Ellman acknowledged that contextual commerce could
elicit objections from those perceiving it as another way the
Internet blurs the lines between editorial and commercial content.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to do it with some kind of sensitivity,'' Chiat
said. ``We don't want to turn the editorial into a throwaway
shopping paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to searching for an agency, Screaming Media is also
seeking a chief executive to replace Chiat, who has been handling
those duties temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the Steve Jobs interim CEO school of management,''
Chiat said, smiling, referring to the interim chief executive at
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Chiat and Ellman listed other investors in Screaming Media as
Regis McKenna, president of McKenna Group, a management consulting
firm in Palo Alto, Calif.; Kevin O'Connor, chairman and chief
executive at Double Click in New York, and James Robinson III,
former chairman and chief executive of the American Express Co.
</P>
<P>
   Chiat also has other Internet interests. He is a member of the
board of Cybergold Inc. in Berkeley, Calif., and an investor in
Passlogix Inc. in New York and Softcom Video in Iselin, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing his experiences on Madison Avenue and in cyberspace,
Chiat declared that the online realm ``moves at a factor at least
10 times faster than an agency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a short attention span like I do,'' he added,
``it's perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 1849EDT &QL; 
