A0110 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     05-09 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 16)  
(lb) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EVERYBODY WAS SO YOUNG: GERALD AND SARA MURPHY. A LOST
GENERATION LOVE STORY. &LR;  By Amanda Vaill. Broadway, $15. The Murphys
were a dazzling, rich American couple who knew and entertained just
about everybody who was anybody in Paris and on the French Riviera
in the 1920's, from Fitzgerald to Picasso. In 1998 our reviewer,
Brooke Allen, called this ``a marvelously readable biography'' by
``a skillful and compassionate writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABOUT A BOY. &LR;  By Nick Hornby. Riverhead, $12.95. Will Freeman
is a smug but aimless London bachelor in his 30s who devises a
dating scheme to tap the market in sexy divorced women by
pretending to be a single dad and joining a support group full of
single mothers. Before long, though, he runs into a troubled
12-year-old boy who sees right through him, and the two become
unlikely soul mates. ``Hornby ... combines a skilled, intuitive
appreciation for the rigors of comic structure with highly original
insights about the way the enchantments of popular culture
insinuate themselves into middle-class notions of romance,'' Hal
Espen wrote here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A WALK IN THE WOODS: REDISCOVERING AMERICA ON THE APPALACHIAN
TRAIL. &LR;  By Bill Bryson. Broadway, $13. The author chronicles in
breezy, good-humored fashion his five-month struggle to hike the
2,100-mile Appalachian Trail from Georgia to Maine. Bryson is ``a
satirist of the first rank, one who writes (and walks) with
Chaucerian brio,'' Dwight Garner wrote here last year.  &UR; SEARCHING
FOR YELLOWSTONE: ECOLOGY AND WONDER IN THE LAST WILDERNESS &LR; , by
Paul Schullery (Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $14), is an environmental
and human history of Yellowstone National Park by a longtime park
ranger and administrator. ``Schullery ... has given us a
refreshingly unhyperbolic look at the place he loves,'' Michael
Parfit wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREEDOMLAND. &LR;  By Richard Price. Island/Dell, $7.99. This novel
tracks the racial turmoil that erupts after a white woman turns up
in a New Jersey city and claims her 4-year-old son was abducted by
a black carjacker. ```Freedomland' is infinitely more than a
detective story,'' Francine Prose said here last year. ``It aspires
to the heft and weight of a 19th-century Russian classic.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORMHOLES: ESSAYS AND OCCASIONAL WRITINGS. &LR;  By John Fowles.
Owl/Holt, $16.
</P>
<P>
   This grab bag of musings by the 73-year-old English novelist
covers a lot of territory _ from autobiographical pieces to
cantankerous forays into politics and culture. ``The book is as
various, quirkily learned, beguiling, opinionated and, in parts, as
sumptuously written as Fowles' fiction,'' Roger Kimball wrote here
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE IRON TRACKS. &LR;  By Aharon Appelfeld. Schocken, $12. This
Israeli novel is about a concentration camp survivor who wanders
through Austria buying sacred books and other remnants of the
Jewish culture that once flourished there while searching for the
Nazi officer who murdered his parents. ``Appelfeld's controlled
fiction compresses large themes into small spaces,'' Jonathan Rosen
said here in 1998.  &UR; BRONSTEIN'S CHILDREN &LR; , by Jurek Becker
(University of Chicago, $15), is another novel about the psychic
aftershocks of the Holocaust, in which an 18-year-old German Jew in
1973 stumbles onto his father and two other camp survivors as they
torture a former Nazi guard. ``Becker, writing simply and clearly
in an unstrained narrative, speaks with the voice of knowledge,''
Eva Figes said here in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COLLECTED POEMS OF AMY CLAMPITT. &LR;  Knopf, $19.95. Clampitt's
poetry is full of restless motion and energy as she evokes places
like the Quaker village in Iowa where she was born and Greenwich
Village, where she cultivated a resolute bohemianism. In 1997 in
the New York Times Book Review, Christopher Benfey called this
posthumously published collection a testament to an ``extraordinary
life's work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BEAUTIFUL MIND. &LR;  By Sylvia Nasar. Touchstone/Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $16. This biography of John Nash, the Nobel Prize-winning
developer of game theory, follows him from his early career through
his crippling bouts of schizophrenia to his recovery years later.
The author, who writes about economics for The New York Times,
``offers a remarkable look into the arcane world of mathematics and
the tragedy of madness,'' Simon Singh wrote here in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREEN FIRES: ASSAULT ON EDEN. A NOVEL OF THE ECUADORIAN
RAINFOREST. &LR;  By Marnie Mueller. Curbstone, $13.95. A former Peace
Corps volunteer revisits the jungles of coastal Ecuador on her
honeymoon in 1969 and becomes involved in a battle between the
native people and American oil companies. ``The characters are well
drawn, and the novel has adventure, intrigue and romance as well as
politics,'' one critic said in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAVANA DREAMS: A STORY OF A CUBAN FAMILY. &LR;  By Wendy Gimbel.
Vintage, $13. The lives of three unhappy women _ a wealthy
bourgeoise, her daughter and the daughter's child by Fidel Castro _
provide a striking perspective on Cuba and its odd destiny. ``The
result is a shimmering book,'' Alma Guillermoprieto said here last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 1917EDT &QL; 
