<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: HARDCOVER BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, May 16)  
(Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for hardcover
books. See BESTSELLERS-HARD-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales for the week ending May 1, at almost
4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 50,000 other retailers
(gift shops, department stores, newsstands, supermarkets),
statistically weighted to represent all such outlets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) indicates that a book's sales are barely distinguishable
from those of the book above. A (b) indicates that some bookstores
report receiving bulk orders for a book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. WE'LL MEET AGAIN, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $25.) A woman struggles to free herself of the
</P>
<P>
   suspicion that she murdered her husband.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE GIRL WHO LOVED TOM GORDON, by Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   (Scribner, $16.95.) When a young girl gets lost in the
</P>
<P>
   woods, she is saved by her spiritual association with a
</P>
<P>
   relief pitcher for the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   3. A NEW SONG, by Jan Karon. (Viking, $24.95.) A clergyman
</P>
<P>
   and his wife move 600 miles from home, creating new friendships
</P>
<P>
   and maintaining old ones.
</P>
<P>
   4. EAST OF THE MOUNTAINS, by David Guterson. (Harcourt
</P>
<P>
   Brace, $25.) A man with cancer returns to the eastern
</P>
<P>
   Washington of his youth to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   5. BITTERSWEET, by Danielle Steel. (Delacorte, $26.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman copes with a midlife crisis: Should she continue
</P>
<P>
   to raise a family or should she pursue her old career?
</P>
<P>
   6. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Doubleday, $27.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and a
</P>
<P>
   young woman who works as a missionary in the jungles
</P>
<P>
   of Brazil are brought together by a startling secret.
</P>
<P>
   7. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Levine/Scholastic, $16.95.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school of witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   8. TARA ROAD, by Maeve Binchy. (Delacorte, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Two women _ one from Ireland, one from New England _
</P>
<P>
   learn a lot about each other as well as about themselves
</P>
<P>
   when they exchange houses for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   9. WHAT'S HEAVEN? by Maria Shriver. Illustrated
</P>
<P>
   by Sandra Speidel. (Golden Books/St. Martin's, $15.) When little
</P>
<P>
   Kate's great-grandmother dies, her mother consoles her.
</P>
<P>
   10. EYE OF THE BEHOLDER, by Jayne Ann Krentz. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $24.) An Art Deco expert becomes involved with a rich
</P>
<P>
   businessman who detests her stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) VITTORIO, THE VAMPIRE, by Anne Rice. (Knopf,
</P>
<P>
   $19.95.) A supernatural siren exercises her wiles
</P>
<P>
   in Renaissance Italy and seduces a teen-age boy.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE HOURS, by Michael Cunningham. (Farrar, Straus
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; Giroux, $22.) The lives of two modern American women,
</P>
<P>
   coping with demands of family and friends, converge with
</P>
<P>
   the life and work of Virginia Woolf.
</P>
<P>
   13. ABIDE WITH ME, by E. Lynn Harris. (Doubleday,
</P>
<P>
   $24.95.) The friendships and sexual relationships of
</P>
<P>
   young people whose careers are beginning to blossom.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Flamingo, $26.) Five female characters,
</P>
<P>
   a missionary's family, narrate this novel set in
</P>
<P>
   the Belgian Congo during that country's fight for
</P>
<P>
   independence.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) THE BEST AMERICAN SHORT STORIES OF THE CENTURY,
</P>
<P>
   edited by John Updike and Katrina Kenison. (Houghton
</P>
<P>
   Mifflin, $28.) Fifty-five stories.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE GREATEST GENERATION, by Tom Brokaw. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) The lives of men and women who came
</P>
<P>
   of age during the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   2. TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death.
</P>
<P>
   3. BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   An American writer recalls a spring and summer spent
</P>
<P>
   in the romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   4. ALL TOO HUMAN, by George Stephanopoulos. (Little,
</P>
<P>
   Brown, $27.95.) The former adviser to President Clinton
</P>
<P>
   recalls his years in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   5. YESTERDAY, I CRIED, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $22.) A counselor recalls how she turned
</P>
<P>
   painful experiences into feelings of hope.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27.50.) A journalist explains
</P>
<P>
   the instant electronic global economy.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) BLACK HAWK DOWN, by Mark Bowden. (Atlantic Monthly,
</P>
<P>
   $24.) The bloody battle between American forces and Somalia
</P>
<P>
   street fighters in Mogadishu in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE CENTURY, by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $60.) An account of the 20th century,
</P>
<P>
   complete with photographs and first-person narratives.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE ART OF HAPPINESS, by the Dalai Lama and Howard
</P>
<P>
   C. Cutler. (Riverhead, $22.95.) What Buddhist doctrines
</P>
<P>
   and common sense tell us about dealing with everyday
</P>
<P>
   problems.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE MAJORS, by John Feinstein. (Little, Brown, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist's account of the 1998 Masters, U.S. Open,
</P>
<P>
   British Open and PGA golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   11. BUSINESS (AT) THE SPEED OF THOUGHT, by Bill Gates with
</P>
<P>
   Collins Hemingway. (Warner, $30.) The chairman of
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft discusses how new technology is changing the
</P>
<P>
   ways business is done. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12. TRAVELING MERCIES, by Anne Lamott. (Pantheon,
</P>
<P>
   $23.) A chronicle of the author's journey toward faith.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) UNCOVERING CLINTON, by Michael Isikoff. (Crown, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist's account of scandals in the Clinton White
</P>
<P>
   House and his role in reporting them.
</P>
<P>
   14. RAISING CAIN, by Dan Kindlon and Michael Thompson
</P>
<P>
   with Teresa Barker. (Ballantine, $24.95.) Two child
</P>
<P>
   psychologists consider the emotional life of boys and
</P>
<P>
   what can be done to benefit it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   15. COMFORT FROM A COUNTRY QUILT, by Reba McEntire.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $19.95.) The country music star tells how she
</P>
<P>
   balances the demands of her career and her family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. LIFE STRATEGIES, by Philip C. McGraw. (Hyperion,
</P>
<P>
   $21.95.) How to find what matters in your life and
</P>
<P>
   what to do about it. (b).
</P>
<P>
   2. LABELLE CUISINE, by Patti LaBelle with Laura B.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, (Broadway, $25.) The singer offers recipes
</P>
<P>
   and advice about cooking Southern style.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE COURAGE TO BE RICH, by Suze Orman. (Riverhead,
</P>
<P>
   $24.95.) How to create a life of material and spiritual
</P>
<P>
   abundance. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4.(x) SUGAR BUSTERS! by H. Leighton Steward et al.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $22.) A diet designed for losing
</P>
<P>
   weight, increasing energy and combating disease.(b)
