<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELEMENTALS &LR; - &UR; BOOK-REV     05-09 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEMENTALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` ELEMENTALS:' FANTASY AND PARABLE BRINGING SOLACE 
</HEADLINE>
 - BOOK-REVIEW-NYT  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review) 
(DW) 
 Hilma Wolitzer's novels include ``Tunnel of Love'' and
``Silver.''  
 By HILMA WOLITZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How do you decide when to stop looking at something?'' This is
the riddle that haunts the protagonist of ``Crocodile Tears,'' the
fine opening story of A.S. Byatt's kaleidoscopic new collection.
Patricia Nimmo is suddenly widowed after a petty argument with her
husband, Tony, at one of the small London art galleries they
frequent. She flees this tragic event like a criminal, traveling
aimlessly through France until she finally settles, almost
randomly, in Nimes.
</P>
<P>
   There she continues her zealous habit of observation, noting
everything from the ``small silver square of fish crisscrossed with
golden lines'' that she eats for dinner to the abstract geometry of
the local architecture. Even her self-assigned project _ to read
Proust, in French _ is ``like a jigsaw seen through thick, uneven
glassware, the colors and shapes hopelessly distorted.''
</P>
<P>
   But tender thoughts of Tony, whom she first met in student
theater (``He had called her Patra, and she had called him
Antony''), pierce Patricia's willed concentration on the visual
world, and she begins to grieve in public places. Another fugitive,
a remote Norwegian named Nils Isaksen, witnesses her misery and
cautiously offers his assistance, which she refuses at first with
corresponding British reserve. But Nils persists, driven by his own
secret sorrow and guilt to help her assuage hers.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia's solace begins with a dream of Tony, warmly alive
beside her. She feels ``dreadfully happy,'' an oxymoronic phrase
that perfectly captures the opposing yet twinned experiences of
memory and loss. Gradually, through conversations about history and
mythology, she and Nils allow each other access to their private
histories and their emotions, and he accompanies her back to London
to face the reality of what she sought so desperately to escape. In
a lovely, understated denouement, they begin their slow, mutual
progression toward recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Byatt, whose elegant literary mystery, ``Possession,'' won
the Booker Prize in 1990, always has been concerned with the ways
in which art and literature inform and transform our lives. In ``A
Lamia in the Cevennes,'' a painter named Bernard Lycett-Kean leaves
Thatcher's Britain for a house in Southern France. He installs a
swimming pool, has it filled with river water and spends his days
contentedly swimming and battling problems of color and line.
</P>
<P>
   One day what appears at first to be a black water snake swims
past him. Soon he realizes that the creature is brilliantly
patterned and has lustrous human eyes. It announces itself as a
lamia, an enchanted spirit that requires a mere kiss from him to
turn into a beautiful woman. If he doesn't comply, the lamia hints,
there will be Faustian consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But Bernard, who likes snakes more than women, demurs. All he
wants is for this hybrid being to remain in his pool in its current
state, so he can solve the problems of its colors. It's a standoff,
as the lamia pleads for the chance to gain an immortal soul, and
Bernard opts for a few more days of painting. But their conflict is
finally, wittily resolved, and Bernard is able to return to his
studies, ``one of the ways in which human beings are happy.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Byatt demonstrated in her previous collection, ``A Djinn
in the Nightingale's Eye,'' the fairy tale is the ideal form for
her gifts. ``Cold,'' the story of a beautiful princess, descended
from an icewoman and seemingly doomed by her metabolism, is steeped
in imagery and sensation. Fiammarosa, like all fairy tale
princesses, is offered in marriage to whoever best meets the
challenge set by her father, although she will make the final
choice herself.
</P>
<P>
   The passionate but cold-blooded Fiammarosa's needs demand
exceptional invention and perseverance on the part of her legion of
suitors. They all send emissaries to woo her with lavish gifts,
while at home her brilliant, lovesick tutor plots his own
courtship.
</P>
<P>
   When her hand is finally won by Sasan, a master glass blower and
the ruler of a desert nation, she returns his ardor, but languishes
in the sultry climate of his kingdom. After visiting her new
husband at his work, she almost succumbs to the fiery heat. ``She
was melting, she thought in confusion, as she fell, slowly, slowly,
bending and crumpling in the blast, becoming hot and liquid, a
white scrap, moaning in a sea of red blood, lit by flames.'' How
Sasan saves her is a testament to both the heroism of love and the
power of art.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter stories in ``Elementals'' offer their own, smaller
pleasures. ``Christ in the House of Martha and Mary'' is a charming
parable about the glory inherent in every kind of work. As an
artist explains to a young cook dissatisfied with her lot in life,
``the divide is not between the servants and the served, between
the leisured and the workers, but between those who are interested
in the world and its multiplicity of forms and forces, and those
who merely subsist.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jael,'' a woman who has ``the opposite of Alzheimer's'' _
the ability to remember things she's not sure ever happened _
reflects back on her girlhood and makes amusingly irreverent
connections between her early studies of the Scriptures and the
television commercials she now creates. When blood turns into fruit
juice, the miracle is merely technological, not divine.
</P>
<P>
   The only disappointment in the collection is the brief
``Baglady,'' about the metamorphosis of a gentlewoman in a
supermall, which seems merely clever and doesn't develop beyond its
original concept. But the longer stories, fired by a fierce
intelligence and related in shimmering prose, evolve from idea to
execution in unexpected and thrillingly persuasive leaps. This
eclectic little volume should delight A.S. Byatt's devoted readers
and attract many new ones.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ELEMENTALS: STORIES OF FIRE AND ICE'
</P>
<P>
   By A.S. Byatt
</P>
<P>
   230 pages. Random House. $21.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
