<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-NYT &LR;      05-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE ON CHINESE EMBASSY MUST NOT DETER NATO, BLAIR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair, the most outspoken of the
allied leaders in championing NATO since the start of the war over
Kosovo, said Sunday that the attack on the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade should not and would not deter the alliance from
intensifying its bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Conscious of the effect such episodes are having on British
public opinion, he wrote a front page article in the mass tabloid
Sunday Mirror saying: ``NATO will prevail. The butchers of Belgrade
will be defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Britons who believe that NATO should suspend the bombing ``could
not be more wrong,'' Blair said, adding that ``it would send
exactly the wrong message'' to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In the personal and evocative language that has characterized
his repeated calls to arms, Blair gave a graphic account of his
visit last week to refugee camps in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is worth remembering these people when you hear stories
about incidents like the mistaken attack on the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade,'' he wrote. ``No matter how many times you see these
scenes on TV, nothing prepares you for the stench, the
all-pervading air of fear or the awful stories that pour out. They
come from women who have been raped. From old men who have seen
their daughters violated. From children who have seen their fathers
dragged away and shot. From sisters who've lost brothers, and
brothers who have lost sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   British newspapers and television had shown Blair moving in
shirtsleeves through the Stenkovec camp and the Blace border post,
and his wife, Cherie, was photographed weeping at the sight of the
hordes of displaced people. Blair told readers that every person to
whom he spoke urged NATO to stick to its bombing. Blair, who
addressed the Romanian Parliament in Bucharest on his trip to the
Balkans last week, will take his message this week to Albania and
Bulgaria, where meetings are planned with refugees as well as heads
of state. In his stepped-up campaign to bolster support, he
exhorted people to rally around NATO in an op-ed article in
Friday's Times of London, and he will do so in other British papers
this week.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Blair has cast the war in terms meant to
resonate with Europeans, noting that the scenes of people being
forced from their homes and packed onto cattle trains bear awful
similarities to those of 50 years ago. ``It is time for my
generation to reflect on the fight of our parents' generation
against Hitler's evil regime,'' he said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Blair's voice has been the most insistent in Europe,
there is also some resentment of Britain in the rest of Europe
because of Britain's reluctance to take in the refugees whose
plight Blair cites so passionately. Only 330 Kosovo refugees have
arrived in the United Kingdom while nearly 10,000 have been
airlifted to Germany, more than 6,000 to Turkey and 2,600 to
Norway.
</P>
<P>
   At the commemoration of NATO's 50th anniversary in Washington
last month, Blair broadened his audience to embrace Americans. He
was the most visible of the assembled national leaders, arriving a
day ahead of time to see President Clinton, lobbying congressmen,
traveling to Chicago and appearing on television news shows.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators in Britain saw the prime minister providing
spine-stiffening leadership to a president weakened by scandal,
shoring him up the way Margaret Thatcher counseled President Bush
over Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation that Blair is anxious about White House
perseverance in the face of public and congressional opposition,
and worried that the United States will accept a diplomatic
settlement too generous to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Blair chose an American network, CNN, to state his
position that the Yugoslav leader was a war criminal and not
someone with whom NATO ought to be thinking about negotiating. ``I
will not be sitting down and dealing with Milosevic,'' he said. ``I
don't think anyone is in a position to be dealing with Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment contrasted with remarks by Clinton in Germany a day
earlier, outlining the possibility of a settlement that would leave
Milosevic in power and stressing that removal of the dictator was
not a stated policy goal. Blair said bluntly, ``The corrupt
dictatorship of Milosevic must be cast out.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has formally ruled out the introduction of ground
troops, Blair is known to feel that they will be needed in whatever
mopping up actions in Kosovo follow the end of the bombing. This
scenario, in which the troops would enter without formal permission
and little chance of major resistance, is being called a
``semi-permissive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   There is far less opposition to the use of ground troops in
Britain and elsewhere in Europe than there is in the United States,
and Blair is understood to have no clear idea of whether the
Europeans can count on the Americans to commit significant numbers
of soldiers if they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports of British unease at possible American
vacillation, a spokesman for 10 Downing Street said, ``The prime
minister has no question about the president's resolve. At the
summit and since then, we have watched everything the president has
said, and we have not seen his resolve waver, and we didn't expect
it to.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman also disputed reports of British unhappiness over
the sudden switch to the diplomatic track in Bonn, Germany, last
week, when foreign ministers of eight nations, including Russia,
settled on a proposal aimed at ending the war and guaranteeing the
safe return of the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the proposal included all the threshold points that
NATO requires as a condition for ending the bombing, he said, ``We
welcomed the effort the president and the Russians and the others
have made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
