<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAMSEY-COX     05-09 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As mixed signals continue, JonBenet Ramsey murder investigation
may be winding down
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For eight months, a public hungry for justice in the
JonBenet Ramsey case has held its collective ear to the closed door
of a grand jury room.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, the slightest sign of an impending decision set
off a flurry of rumor and media attention.
</P>
<P>
   Still, eight months is an uncommonly long time for a grand jury
to work, say legal experts, and these days the buzz is growing that
the proceedings are winding down. The pool of reporters that hover
in the court hallways has doubled to a dozen. And for the past two
weeks the grand jury of eight women and four men has gone from
meeting twice a week to once, according to the media closely
watching the scene in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But, with no official word coming down, mixed signals persist.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, the judge overseeing the Ramsey grand jury
struck down a request for television cameras in the courtroom.
Boulder District Court Judge Roxanne Bailin said in her ruling that
``there is no current indication that an indictment of anyone is
imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   The request pertained to only a first court appearance, bond
hearing and filing of charges following any indictment. It did not
address cameras at a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the grand jury, which would have concluded its term in
late April, has received an extension of up to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Conjecture that the grand jury was nearly done heated up in
March when Denver 's Rocky Mountain News, quoting the jury
commissioner, reported that five people serving as alternates had
been discharged.
</P>
<P>
   In April, rumors were fueled by an unconfirmed Fox News report
that the Ramseys were making arrangements for ``a plan of
cooperation'' with prosecutors, should one or both parents be
indicted.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Bob Grant, a district attorney from a neighboring
county who had lent a prosecutor to the grand jury, has said he has
reason to believe he'll be getting his employee back soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to getting my prosecutor back by the
middle or end of May,'' said the Adams County district attorney.
But he tossed in some words of caution, saying, ``That estimation
doesn't have a whole lot of reality-base to it.''
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet's body was found Dec. 26, 1996, in the basement of the
family's home in Boulder. About seven hours earlier, her mother
Patsy Ramsey had reported to police in a 5:52 a.m. phone call that
she had found a ransom note demanding $118,000 for the girl's safe
return.
</P>
<P>
   John and Patsy Ramsey have been a focus of the investigation,
but they have maintained their innocence. They currently live in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the scuttlebutt, the evidence and testimony
presented to the grand jury has pretty much remained a secret over
the past eight months. The secrecy marks a change in a murder
mystery that for many months had been riddled with media leaks that
detailed trouble with the investigation and dissent between cops
and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Hunter, the district attorney handling the case, has
repeatedly declined comment on the closed-door grand jury probe
into the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   When the grand jury does announce its decision, it has three
likely scenarios to chose from, said Grant:
</P>
<P>
   _ They could recommend an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   _ They could decide they do not have sufficient evidence to
recommend an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   _ They could decide not to even deliberate for lack of evidence.
That could include calling for more investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it indicts anyone, the grand jury could also
issue a report on the investigation, though anyone named in the
report has the right to see it and add their own comments before
its released. The judge and the prosecutor must agree that the
report will not compromise any ongoing investigation. A grand
jury's recommendation for an indictment must also be signed by the
judge and prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The elevation of what commonly would be considered a local
murder story into an international news event has fascinated people
for over two years. Whether the grand jury indicts someone or not,
it will hardly mark the end of the story, said media expert Alan
Caruba.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, the dimensions of the story are far in excess of
its real news value,'' said Caruba, a former editor of a directory
of media contacts and writer whose work has appeared in the New
York Times. ``It's become symbolic of all child murders.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the grand jury chose to indict someone, especially one or
both of the parents, the story would create a media frenzy equal to
the O.J. Simpson trial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if no indictment comes down, interest will continue, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it passes into the annals of the classic unsolved
mysteries,'' he said. ``And it goes on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Schneider writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
