u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-09 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: 400 YEARS AFTER VAN DYCK TRIBUTE; JOAN OF ARC'S BIG
MONTH; A CINCINNATI CHORAL FESTIVAL; 100 YEARS AFTER FRED ASTAIRE'S
BIRTH 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Belgium, Ohio)   By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 14 he painted his first self-portrait. By 18 he was a master
in the Antwerp Guild of St. Luke. Peter Paul Rubens called him ``my
best pupil.'' He was Anthony Van Dyck. Commemorating the 400th
anniversary of this artist's birth, his native Antwerp, Belgium, is
assembling a major tribute from Saturday into October, including
exhibitions sprawling across three museums and related displays and
a music festival. Hundreds of paintings from museums and private
collections around the world, including those of Queen Elizabeth II
of Britain, will be shown. More than 80 van Dyck portraits will be
displayed through Aug. 15 at the Royal Museum of Fine Arts; his
splendid, influential English landscape drawings will be at the
Rubens House through Aug. 20, and his engravings at the
Plantin-Moretus Museum through Aug. 20. Information:
011-32-70-233-799.
</P>
<P>
   Events Honoring Joan of Arc
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For better and worse May has always been a big month
for Joan of Arc. She was burned at the stake on May 30, 1431, and
she was canonized on May 16, 1920. Monday begins another busy
series of events pivoting around her. At 8 Monday night at Avery
Fisher, the Concordia Orchestra will present Richard Einhorn's
oratorio ``Voices of Light'' (1993), performed with the movie it
was written to accompany: Carl Dreyer's silent film ``The Passion
of Joan of Arc'' (1928). Information: (212) 721-6500. At 8 p.m. on
Thursday, the Collegiate Chorale will offer a concert version of
Verdi's opera ``Giovanna d'Arco'' at Carnegie Hall. Information:
(212) 247-7800. On Sunday and the following Tuesday, CBS will
present ``Joan of Arc,'' a four-hour mini-series starring Leelee
Sobieski.
</P>
<P>
   Choral Conclave in Cincinnati
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the oldest continual choral festival in the Western
Hemisphere, the Cincinnati May Festival opens on Thursday for a run
through May 22. The festival's music director, James Conlon, will
present the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra, the 150-voice May
Festival volunteer chorus and other performers in a survey of
20th-century choral music. The festival begins with Kurt Weill's
``Propheten.'' Information: (513) 381-3000.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Astaire's Birthday
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The witty singer Mary Cleere Haran will preside over
the Fred Astaire 100th Birthday Celebration at 8:30 Monday night in
the Diva Series at Joe's Pub at the Joseph Papp Public Theater.
Though Monday is the actual anniversary, Ms. Haran's tribute will
continue Tuesday. Information: (212) 239-6200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
