<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-LUCAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER LUCAS NOT IMPRESSED BY POLE POSITION IN BOX OFFICE DERBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``e'' entertainment   and ``n'' California
news files.) 
(EDITORS: Daily News Film Critic Bob Strauss attended the first
press screening   of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace''
on Friday night in New York.) 
BY BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Lucas told reporters in New York on Sunday
that he's not one of the many who expect ``Star Wars: Episode I _
The Phantom Menace,'' his universally anticipated prequel to the
most popular movie series of all time, to be the biggest box office
hit in history.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he doesn't care whether it is or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The billion dollars or so that people are saying the film will
make, I'm dubious about,'' said Lucas, who hasn't directed a
feature film since the first ``Star Wars'' 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That 1977 classic currently stands as the second-highest
grossing feature ever at a figure of $461 &UR;  &LR; million, including
reissues.
</P>
<P>
   James Cameron's ``Titanic'' is the leader in North American box
office take at more than $600 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where that `Let's beat Titanic' stuff came
from,'' Lucas added. ``Anybody who knows the film business knows
that the chances of this film beating the original (Star Wars) are
slim to none. I don't even think it'll really beat `E.T.' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   (``E.T.'' led the all-time box office rankings from 1982 until
1997, when the ``Star Wars Special Edition'' was reissued.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I expect it to be one of the top 10 grossers of all
time,'' Lucas said of ``Phantom Menace,'' ``and if it wasn't, I
would probably be very disappointed. But it's not the end of the
world, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Though certainly the most personally successful of filmmakers _
Lucas owns all rights to ``Star Wars'' sequels and merchandising _
he disdains both the industry's and the media's focus on films'
financial performance.
</P>
<P>
