<HEADER>
A0138 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-YESTERDAY-LADN     05-09 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTERDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE MADE MAGIC IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   May 11, 1963: Dodgers' Sandy Koufax throws his second no-hitter,
a near-perfect 8-0 win against San Francisco and Juan Marichal. The
only runner for the Giants is Ed Bailey, who drew an eighth-inning
walk with one out.
</P>
<P>
   May 14, 1981: Dodgers' Fernando Valenzuela beats Montreal 3-2 to
extend his record to 8-0 with an ERA of 0.50.
</P>
<P>
   May 14, 1996: Magic Johnson announces his second retirement from
the Lakers. He rejoined the team in January and played 32 games to
help get the team into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 1973: Angels' Nolan Ryan throws his first career
no-hitter, at Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 1984: Lakers' Magic Johnson sets an NBA playoff record
with 24 assists in a 118-102 victory over Phoenix in the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   May 15, 1998: The Dodgers send Mike Piazza and Todd Zeile to the
Florida Marlins for Gary Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Jim Eisenreich
and Charles Johnson. Of the four, only Sheffield remains with L.A.
</P>
<P>
   May 16, 1979: The Lakers, who acquired the right to draft No.1
when Gail Goodrich signed as a free agent with New Orleans before
the 1976-77 season, announce they have an agreement with Magic
Johnson, who announced five days earlier he was leaving Michigan
State after his junior year. The pick becomes official on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   May 16, 1980: Starting at center in place of the injured Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar in Game 6 of the NBA Finals, Magic Johnson scores 42
points, grabs 15 rebounds and has seven assists in 47 minutes at
Philadelphia to lead the Lakers to a 123-107 win and clinch the
title. For that, Johnson becomes the first rookie named MVP of the
Finals. (6)
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Wednesday: The original coach of the Mighty Ducks and
ex-husband of former Laker girl Paula Abdul, actor Emilio Estevez
(37). Thursday: former Lakers forward Dennis Rodman (38) and former
Dodgers catcher John Roseboro (66). Friday: Former UCLA basketball
star Pooh Richardson (33). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
