<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINERS LINING UP TO TAKE A SHOT AT CHARISMATIC IN PREAKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trainers and their horses seemed slower than usual in making
the move, but the Triple Crown scene was relentlessly shifting last
week from Louisville to Baltimore while racing skeptics wondered
how in the world the 31-1 long-shot winner of the Kentucky Derby
could repeat in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   At Pimlico Race Course, where the Preakness will be run
Saturday, the track is narrower, the turns tighter and the distance
shorter than it was for the Derby at Churchill Downs. But
Charismatic will try to make it two straight over 10 or 11 of the
horses he outran with an untroubled trip in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   As Preakness week began, it appeared that a full field of 14
horses would be entered for the second classic for 3-year-olds,
most of them graduates of the Derby. They include Charismatic, the
winner; Menifee, who missed catching him by a neck and was ranked
as the probable favorite to defeat him this time, and Cat Thief,
who missed by less than a length and finished third.
</P>
<P>
   It also seemed likely that Worldly Manner, the horse from Dubai,
who ran seventh in the Derby, would give it another try in the
Preakness. And Bob Baffert, who lost the Derby when all three of
his horses ran out of the money, indicated over the weekend that he
might try to enter his two star fillies: Excellent Meeting, who
finished fifth in the Derby, and Silverbulletday, who won the
Kentucky Oaks the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert apparently intended to excuse General Challenge from
further punishment following the colt's arduous trip to an
11th-place finish in the Derby. And he still was considering
whether to enter Prime Timber, who ran a solid fourth in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert is holding a pair of aces: Silverbulletday, winner
of 10 of her 11 starts, including the Kentucky Oaks, and Excellent
Meeting, winner of six races in a row before the Derby. They are
expected to be shipped to Baltimore on Wednesday. But the trainer,
who played the same guessing game before the Derby, suggested that
he might change the agenda for both fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert returned to Pimlico over the weekend with Real Quiet,
winner of the Derby and Preakness last year. Baffert revived his
exuberance when Real Quiet outran Free House in the homestretch and
won the Pimlico Special by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer also won the Derby and Preakness in 1997 with Silver
Charm. Now, although his Derby streak was broken, he could win the
Black-Eyed Susan one day with one filly and the Preakness the next
day with another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I still plan to enter Silverbulletday in both the
Black-Eyed Susan and the Preakness,'' he said. ``It pretty much
depends on where she draws whether she goes in the Preakness. If I
don't like the post, she'll go in the other race.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, Charismatic's trainer, won his third Kentucky
Derby in five years and his fourth overall, restoring luster to a
career that was being overshadowed by Baffert. But for Lukas, his
chief mission was to build some credibility into Charismatic, who
has won only four of his 15 starts and who ran in a $62,500
claiming race as recently as Feb 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get the credit that he deserves,'' Lukas said.
``But it would be dangerous to overlook him in the Preakness. Very
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charismatic clearly was not a dominant horse who might sweep
the Triple Crown, which probably explains why a full field of 14 is
likely to start the Preakness for the first time since 1992. That
was the year A.P. Indy came up with a foot injury on the morning of
the Derby, which was won by the undistinguished Lil E. Tee. Two
weeks later, Pine Bluff won the Preakness. Three weeks after that,
a repaired A.P. Indy came back to win the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Charismatic was trying to find respect, Menifee has won
five of his seven starts and ran second in the two others. And Cat
Thief, who is the more highly regarded of the Lukas horses, should
be close to him in the odds.
</P>
<P>
   If Menifee wins the race, it will be the sixth victory for his
jockey, Pat Day, tying him with Eddie Arcaro for the Preakness
record. Day also is the only rider to win the Preakness three years
in a row: aboard Tabasco Cat in 1994, Timber Country in 1995 and
Louis Quatorze in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One other question mark was removed late last week when Carl
Nafzger decided to run Vicar, who won the Fountain of Youth Stakes
and the Florida Derby before finishing 18th in the Kentucky Derby.
He said that he would ship Vicar from Churchill Downs to Pimlico on
Wednesday, but added that an outside post position would change his
mind about starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get our rhythm out of the gate,'' Nafzger said.
``We didn't get that in the last race, and a horse with that much
speed, that's his game. Get him out, get in the pace and then have
a little kick at the end. If I get out there in the 14 hole, then I
doubt I will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Nafzger said Vicar would have a new jockey because he released
Shane Sellers last week when he was not sure that they would make
the Preakness. ``Shane was getting calls from other trainers,''
Nafzger said, ``so I told him if he found something definite, he
probably should go.''
</P>
<P>
   The horses will run 1 3/16 miles in the Preakness, which is
one-sixteenth shorter than the Derby. For the strong of heart and
wind, the Triple Crown series closes with the Belmont on June 5 at
a 1 1/2 miles .  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
