<HEADLINE>
BC-FINBUDGET-SFCHRON 
</HEADLINE>
 SF CHRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, May 10, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TALKSIGN _  &LR; Damien Pickering stands on the edge of the curb,
listening intently for the red light to change. Blind since
childhood, Pickering relies on a small plastic box he holds in his
hand like a TV remote control. The box repeats a scratchy,
computerized voice that says, ``Wait, Polk Street. Wait, Polk
Street.'' Since 1995, San Francisco has become a real-life
laboratory for Talking Signs, which uses microprocessors and
infrared beams to give vision-impaired people a voice description
of signs and landmarks in their vicinity. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEBACCESS &LR;  _ The blazing 3-D graphics, video and sound that
enliven multimedia Web sites also can create barriers for people
with disabilities. ``Web design is primarily driven by retinal
chauvinists,'' said Jerry Kuns, a visually impaired sales
representative who uses computer speech and Braille synthesizers to
read information on the Internet. ``Pictures are great, but they
are stumbling blocks to me.'' By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NET FILES &LR;  _ Art Coombes and customers of his small
Internet service company recently learned some hard lessons about
sharing an online account with a spammer. They stopped receiving
e-mail. Coombes, owner of Internet Frontier in Walnut Creek, became
the latest unwitting ISP to make the Realtime Blackhole List, which
is generated by the self-proclaimed e-mail police of the Internet.
By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIOSCOPE &LR;  _ A company's desire to protect a secret formula
collided with a judge's interest in proving guilt beyond a shadow
of a doubt last week. San Francisco Superior Court Judge Robert
Dondero decided that he would not accept a certain type of DNA test
as evidence in five criminal trials before him because the company
that sells the test _ Perkin-Elmer Biosystems in Foster City _
refused to show him the secret formula that supposedly makes the
test foolproof. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUCWATCH &LR;  _ Mark Dodd and Rodrigo Sales are the self-styled
consumer advocates of the online auction world. When bidders and
sellers have gripes, Dodd and Sales listen. The pair run
AuctionWatch.com, a forum where auction participants can chat,
complain and get more information about who's buying, who's selling
and who's cheating. That's made AuctionWatch a frequent thorn in
the side of eBay and other major online auction sites, both in a
watchdog role and as a gathering spot where disgruntled customers
freely air gripes. By Jamie Beckett
</P>
</TEXT>
