<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO MOTIVATE THE HEAT, RILEY GOES TO THE VIDEOTAPE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Normal, for Pat Riley, would have been to hold a
marathon practice Sunday. He would have run his players until they
either dropped or realized how awful it was to lose their first
home playoff game by 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   But renowned as he is for motivating underachieving teams with
work and more work, the Miami Heat coach let the camera speak for
him.
</P>
<P>
   A day after they were run out of Miami Arena in Game 1 of the
three-of-five-game series, Heat players were forced to sit through
a videotape at their Coconut Grove practice facility of their 95-75
debacle against the New York Knicks. No wind sprints. No endless
scrimmage. Just Knick highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all the truth,'' said P.J. Brown, who was ejected from
the game after arguing a technical foul. ``They say the eye doesn't
lie. With that camera, there's nothing you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   With Game 2 looming Monday night, Riley is one loss from
returning to Madison Square Garden in a disastrous 0-2 hole. Rather
than resort to the usual bunker mentality, he tried a more
practical approach. Basically telling his players, ``That's not
you,'' he urged them to watch the videotape before speaking of
their seasonlong resilience.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat began the season 1-3 and weathered a midseason streak
in which they lost six of seven games before righting themselves to
take control of the Atlantic Division and eventually the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the perception and what people think based
on the first game,'' Riley said. ``I know what our team is and how
we've showed in the past. We are a team that has great heart and
great character _ and it will surface.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``What really counts is who we are, what we've done
and how we've played in the past. We simply have to get back to
that. The reality, like any team that loses the first game of the
playoffs, is that we simply have to go back to work mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to Game 2, Riley cautioned his players about reading
too many South Florida newspapers _ most of which painted a
dreadful picture for the first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, beneath the steely veneers of Alonzo Mourning and Tim
Hardaway, there is genuine concern.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning had an effective offensive game, but Miami was once
again unmasked as a team with few offensive options beyond its
franchise center and trigger-happy point guard. Dan Majerle and
Jamal Mashburn missed layups. Voshon Lenard could not make a
3-pointer until the game was out of reach. The reserve forward
Clarence Weatherspoon looked intimidated each time he caught the
ball in the post.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway is clearly ailing. Bothered by a sore right knee, he
made only 4 of 19 shots. Stubbornly proud, he did not stick around
to be interviewed by reporters. But his defenders were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the odds are poor that that will happen,'' Riley said
of Hardaway having another meltdown from the perimeter. ``But
they're doing a good job on him. Tim's got to find a way to do
other things, and I've got to find a way to help him get better
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning said: ``I know Timmy. He's going to go out and play a
lot better game. We don't play that way on a regular basis. If we
played that way on a regular basis, we wouldn't be the No. 1 seed
in the East.''
</P>
<P>
   The general perception among Heat players is that Saturday was
an aberration. They even played down the 44 points put up by
Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play as hard as they did,'' Majerle said. ``We
didn't do the things we needed to do to win. Sprewell and Houston
are both great players, but we have to go out and play our type of
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley criticized his team's transition defense and went on and
on about discipline and detail. But the challenge he was issuing to
his players seemed simple: lock those Game 1 impostors in the
closet and assume their rightful identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed as anybody,'' Majerle said. ``He was mad,
but we've seen him a lot worse. He knows what we have to do. He let
the film pretty much speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said: ``Everybody who stepped on the court yesterday for
the Knicks contributed nicely to the team. We only had one guy that
stepped up for us. If they're going to play like that, we have to
have more guys on our team play better to match them. Because if
they continue to play like they played and we continue to play like
we played, we're going to be swept.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
