<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-NET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 FILES _ SF CHRON   Anti-Spam Service or McCarthyism?  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
Art Coombes and customers of his small Internet service company
recently learned some hard lessons about sharing an online account
with a spammer. They stopped receiving e-mail.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coombes, owner of Internet Frontier in Walnut Creek, became the
latest unwitting ISP to make the Realtime Blackhole List, which is
generated by the self-proclaimed e-mail police of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Coombes and a long list of RBL offenders, call the
Redwood City organization behind the list a gang of vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
   RBL publishes an electronic enemies list of ISPs and Web-hosting
companies that it accuses of trafficking in spam or unsolicited
bulk e-mail. Billions of junk e-mail messages are delivered
annually, according to e-mail experts. RBL's list is circulated to
hundreds of ISPs, universities and online organizations, who,
following RBL's advice, automatically can refuse to deliver
messages from an ISP that has been ``blackholed.''
</P>
<P>
   At various times, America Online, Microsoft Network, Real
Networks and Earthlink Network have been listed by RBL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a solution to spam,'' said John Mozena, co-founder of
Coalition Against Unsolicited Commercial Email, of which RBL is a
member. ``But it is a valuable tool _ both in technical and public
relations terms _ for domains that want to protect themselves
against spam. No one wants to be stigmatized by being on the RBL
list.''
</P>
<P>
   But the electronic blockade often extends too far. When an ISP
is ``blackholed,'' other ISPs and corporations block all e-mail
from that ISP _ cutting off the ISP's nonspamming customers in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than be surgically precise, they are like the Sherman
Army marching to the sea,'' said Coombes, whose company has 2,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being penalized for simply being a customer of Internet
Frontier,'' said one East Bay resident, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a month, e-mail service for dozens of Internet
Frontier customers was spotty _ until Coombes booted the offending
spammer from his online service, RBL dropped his company from its
list and other ISPs lifted their ban. Full e-mail service was
restored to Internet Frontier several days ago. Nick Nicholas,
executive director of the Mail Abuse Prevention System LLC, which
operates the Realtime Blackhole List, admitted that consumers
``unfortunately are caught in the middle.'' But he said RBL's
pressure tactics forced Internet Frontier to clean up its act.
</P>
<P>
   Counters the still-fuming Coombes: ``We are off their list not
because we dropped a customer, but because we threatened a lawsuit.
They can dress this up anyway they want, but what they are doing is
arrogant and philosophically repugnant.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Others agree that RBL is taking a radical approach _ albeit
with less vitriol than Coombes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes spam, and there is no easy way to stop it,'' said
Paul Hoffman, director of Internet Mail Consortium in Santa Cruz.
``So we have a situation where people are taking extreme measures
that upset a lot of individuals yet cut spam by only 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EUROSPAM: The European Parliament, meanwhile, improbably voted last
week to legalize spam over the objections of ISPs and anti-spamming
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The bill _ part of larger legislation on legal aspects of
electronic commerce _ requires that unsolicited commercial e-mail
be labeled as such in e-mail headers. &UR;  &LR; European ISPs, who rightly
accused Parliament members of being misinformed, fear that weak
laws will encourage spammers to bombard consumers with junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   Could you imagine a similar scenario in the United States? Not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; There are several bills floating in Congress to curb spam
nationwide, and state laws in California, Nevada, Washington and
Virginia. Another 14 states are considering anti-spam bills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WWW.FORCEBEWITHYOU.COM: Can't get enough tidbits, gossip and
digital images from the ``Star Wars'' prequel? There are
constellations of intergalactic Web sites devoted to ``Episode I:
The Phantom Menace,'' debuting May 19. For starters, try out
 &LR; www.theprequels.com &LR; ,  &LR; www.phantomcast.com &LR; ,
 &LR; www.hollywood.com/starwars &LR;  and &LR;  www.asylum.com/cgi-bin &LR; 
 &LR; /aggregate?aggregatorswtpm &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Each site is crammed with enough behind-the-scenes features,
factoids and trivia to overload both R2-D2 and C-3PO.
</P>
<P>
   Still not satisfied? Then view  &LR; www.countingdown.com &LR;  for live
Web casts of the happenings at Mann's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood
as this year's movie mega-event nears lift-off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEIMAN IMACS: Speaking of pop culture icons, the iMac _ Apple's
futuristic computer for first-time Internet users _ now is
available from the catalog of tony retailer Neiman Marcus. A
special version of the candy-colored Macs, with printer and
scanner, costs $1,699.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE BOOK ON E-MAIL: File this under Netiquette. A new book,
``Simple Steps to E-mail Success,'' offers a crash course in the
do's and don'ts of using e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Before you scoff at a 62-page business book on how to write
e-mail, consider this: Online correspondence is slowly supplanting
the phone and face-to-face conversations. More than 200 million
e-mail messages travel through cyberspace every day, according to
Fortune magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Author Joy Van Skiver advises e-mailers to craft short, concise
messages that include punchy headings &UR;  &LR; and make good use of white
space. She also recommends that consumers carefully check spelling
and grammar of their e-mails to make a better impression. Van
Skiver stresses that electronic letter writers avoid long-winded
messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't read all of their mail,'' she said. ``They
get about 50 messages a day, so make your message brief and
visually pleasing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VAN SMAK IS HUGE: Props from one NoCal clone to Jim ``Romey'' Rome,
the sports talk-show host who is blowing up on a national level.
His Web site is tremendous, with huge faxes, annual smak-off
winners, photos from the Rat family album and tour stops, and the
neck glossary. It is outstanding. I'm out. If you don't understand
any of this, go to  &LR; www.jimrome.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  If you love ``MTV Celebrity Deathmatch,'' then take a gander at &LR; 
www.hotpopcorn.com &LR;   &LR; /celebconnection/hangceleb &LR; . Along the same
vein, you also might consider  &LR; www.goddessofgarbage.com &LR; . In both
instances, trash is good.
</P>
