<SLUG> BC-AUCWATCH-AUCTION </SLUG>
 WATCH _ SF CHRON  
 Watchdog Site Keeps Its Eye on Web Auctions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Jamie Beckett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Mark Dodd and Rodrigo Sales are the self-styled consumer advocates
of the online auction world. When bidders and sellers have gripes,
Dodd and Sales listen.
</P>
<P>
   The pair run AuctionWatch.com, a forum where auction
participants can chat, complain and get more information about
who's buying, who's selling and who's cheating. That's made
AuctionWatch a frequent thorn in the side of eBay and other major
online auction sites, both in a watchdog role and as a gathering
spot where disgruntled customers freely air gripes.
</P>
<P>
   Its founders have plans to make the site a great deal more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to become the trusted, unbiased portal to the online
auction community,'' said Sales, the Mountain View company's
25-year-old co-founder and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides free ``image hosting'' for auctions on both
eBay and Amazon, allowing sellers to post pictures to help push
their products. AuctionWatch provides the server space to store
these images.
</P>
<P>
   AuctionWatch recently added a postcard service that auction
participants can use as ``feedback.'' This rating of other users
and how they handle transactions is a key element of online auction
protocol.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers information on hundreds of online auction
sites, and it is moving to provide advice for auction participants
on such subjects as bidding strategies.
</P>
<P>
   AuctionWatch keeps the online auction houses on their toes. A
few months ago, Dodd spotted (and made his observation public) a
bazooka for sale on eBay, after the Web site had banned sales of
guns and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Auction newcomer Amazon.com has had its share of complaints on
AuctionWatch, as well, ranging from gripes about a lack of bidders
to complaints that the site is too hard to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd is the driving force behind AuctionWatch. He'd been doing
some buying and selling himself _ mostly toys and ``Star Wars''
paraphernalia _ and he noticed that there was no unbiased source of
information on the auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the business-to-individual sites didn't even allow
bidders to interact and that they used the auction format only to
increase excitement about a product and drive up prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was bad for consumers,'' said Dodd. ``I wasn't going to
stand for that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was last spring. Dodd, a 29-year-old, self-taught
programmer and inveterate tinkerer _ as a child, he tore apart his
parents microwave and TV and put them back together _ spent a month
setting up the site. It went live in June 1998, spreading the word
via users' forums on eBay and other auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   In August, needing resources for expansion, Dodd called in his
friend Sales. The two met in 1991 through a classified ad _ Sales
was selling automobile tires. Sales then was a year away from
finishing his MBA at Stanford. The lessons about raising capital
were fresh in his mind. They raised money from angel investors,
waiting to build the company before they approached venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Sales and Dodd say the site is getting ``millions''
of page views a month and is growing by 190 percent monthly. They
won't discuss revenue, except to say it's now based primarily on
advertising, which isn't plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   The company, formerly headquartered in the apartments of its
founders, just moved to its first offices, in Mountain View.
</P>
<P>
   But investors say there's plenty of potential because of the
booming growth of the online auction business and because of the
need for the services AuctionWatch offers by monitoring auctions
and providing services for users.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a gigantic market, and you're going to
need somebody to do what AuctionWatch does,'' said Palo Alto money
manager Kurt Feshbach. ``These guys (AuctionWatch) are the first on
the block.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
