<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM TENSE AS NETANYAHU THREATENS TO CLOSE PLO OFFICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Vowing to block entry by the Israeli police, scores
of Palestinians gathered Sunday at the Palestine Liberation
Organization's headquarters in East Jerusalem as Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu threatened to close three offices in the
building forcibly.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to boost a flagging campaign little more than a week
before the Israeli elections, Netanyahu revived a longstanding
demand of the political right to move against the PLO building,
Orient House, plunging Israeli and Palestinian officials into
crisis talks to avert violence.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials have warned that closing the offices would
set off serious unrest, and the move has caused a rift between
Netanyahu and the public security minister, Avigdor Kahalani, whose
police officers would have to enforce the closure.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Netanyahu made his threat Sunday, Kahalani met with
Faisal Husseini, the top Palestinian official in Jerusalem, to try
to negotiate a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Cabinet officials who approved the closing last
month debated their next steps at a late-night meeting as American
diplomats tried to mediate the crisis. Israeli security officials
reportedly told the ministers that forcibly closing the offices
could set off riots in East Jerusalem, the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has made Jerusalem a rallying cry of his election
campaign, and he is pressing to close the offices on the grounds
that they are linked to the Palestinian Authority, thus violating
the Israeli-Palestinian accords and Israeli sovereignty over
Jerusalem. The Palestinians deny such links, saying the offices
belong to the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Orient House is considered a national symbol by many
Palestinians. Netanyahu has repeatedly pressed to close it, calling
political activities there, especially meetings with foreign
diplomats, a challenge to Israeli rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians view East Jerusalem, captured by Israel from
Jordan in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, as the capital of their
hoped-for state. Israel asserts that the area will forever remain
part of its indivisible capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will shut these offices,'' Netanyahu said Sunday. ``We will
shut them down with agreement, or we will have to do it without
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahalani said he was seeking a peaceful solution. ``We are
trying to find a solution without having to go in by force, which
would create violence there,'' he said. Scores of Palestinians have
gathered at Orient House in recent days to block a forced entry by
the Israeli police, and many slept in the compound overnight.
</P>
<P>
   After signing orders that set a 7 p.m. deadline for the closing,
Kahalani played for more time. ``Why should we put a gun to the
head when it is still possible to find a way to continue living
together and continue the peace process?'' he said after meeting
with Husseini.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline came and went, officials on both sides continued
their consultations. Husseini met with Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, and with the U.S. consul general in Jerusalem,
John Herbst, urging his intervention. Dennis Ross, the State
Department's special envoy to the Middle East, spoke by phone with
Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that if there is a closure order there will be riots
everywhere,'' Husseini said. ``We want to arrive at something that
will prevent a deterioration.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel Radio reported Sunday night that the Palestinians had
rejected an Israeli proposal that two of the offices be moved to
Abu Dis, a village just outside the Jerusalem city limits, and that
Husseini stop meeting foreign ambassadors in Orient House.
</P>
<P>
   The three offices ordered closed are a department that monitors
Israeli settlement activity; the office of international relations,
which handles contacts with foreign diplomats; and the personal
office of Husseini, who is the official responsible for Jerusalem
affairs in the PLO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
