<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Monday, May 10,
and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHCHITECTS-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ Seattle may be about to shed
its reputation for cheap, tacky and dull civic buildings _ or at
least the cheap part. Noted architects are bringing their pencils
to Seattle this week to compete for the job of designing Seattle's
$156 million Central Library, to be followed by a similar contest
next month for a $66 million City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   By Steven Goldsmith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PREMIER-BRITISH COLUMBIA (VICTORIA, British Columbia) _ Somehow,
British Columbia Premier Glen Clark is still on his feet. The Royal
Canadian Mounted Police has downgraded charges against the
premier's neighbor. The recall campaign has collapsed. Bad economic
news was recently broken when Louisiana-Pacific announced it would
invest $283 million (Canadian) in four new mills. As Clark's
opponents tried to stage a mass rally in Nanaimo last Thursday, 250
supporters of his government paraded in under a banner reading:
``Give Us News, Not Right-Wing Propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-FUNDS (Seattle) _ Environmentalists working to purchase
and preserve a wilderness area in north central Washington will on
Monday announce a multimillion-dollar gift in stock that, along
with grassroots fund-raising, puts them halfway to their goal. The
Loomis Forest Fund, launched to protect 25,000 acres of rugged and
pristine state-owned land near the Canadian border, aims to raise
$13 million by July 1 to purchase the forest and protect it from
planned logging.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LUCAS (New York) _ It was only fitting that on the day to
celebrate the contributions of mothers everywhere, one of pop
culture's biggest Mr. Moms celebrated his latest child _ the most
anticipated movie in years. Director George Lucas, a single father
of three and the force behind ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' gushed the morning after his latest opus was seen at a
special screening for journalists.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert L. Jamieson Jr. (Story will move in the ``e''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-OUR GUYS (Undated) _ The story behind Monday night's ABC
movie, ``Our Guys'' is a disturbing one. It's the story of a
17-year-old girl who was sexually assaulted by a group of high
school football players in 1989 in the comfortable, suburban
enclave of Glen Ridge, N.J. After the story leaked, the town
circled the wagons and rallied. Not around the victim, who had the
mental capacity of an 8-year-old, but around the boys who had been
accused.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ We could not spot a McDonald's
franchise from the castle ruins. But that seemed to be one of the
few viewpoints in Europe where you would not glimpse a golden arch.
``You like McDonald's?'' a young lady in Nancy, France, asked us.
Before we could answer, she said, ``I love McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Owen. (Story has moved in the ``d'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (New York) _ The Seattle Mariners and Jeff Fassero
lost 6-1 to the Yankees, as the Mariners were able to manage only
three hits off assorted New York relief pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Column on Rick Welts, the former
Seattle SuperSonics ballboy, who is leaving the NBA to take an
important job in Rupert Murdoch's burgeoning sports empire.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
