<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADOES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMANS' SPIRIT UNSHAKEN AFTER LATEST TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Their building was destroyed by last week's
killer tornado, but the spirit and faith of members of Beth Haven
Independent Baptist Church is unshaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been completely positive, nothing negative,''
said Ivan Casteel, the pastor of the small church that had stood on
Western Avenue near 119th Street, an area that sustained some of
the heaviest damage in south Oklahoma City on May 3. ``This is a
slight setback. It may be awhile, but we will rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, about 130 members of his congregation gathered at
Southwest Baptist Church, which had opened its doors so that Beth
Haven members could pray together for those who lost lives and
property.
</P>
<P>
   Two members' homes were destroyed and two were heavily damaged,
Casteel said.
</P>
<P>
   In Moore on Sunday, hundreds of people _ including Oklahoma Gov.
Frank Keating, U.S. Rep. J.C. Watts and the mayors of Oklahoma City
and Moore _ gathered at First Baptist Church to celebrate Mother's
Day and the resilience of Oklahomans.
</P>
<P>
   The large brick church is about the only building left standing
in that part of town.
</P>
<P>
   The storms that struck a week ago today spawned 76 verified
tornadoes, killed 41 people and injured more than 700. Damage was
put at about $1 billion, and 11 counties were declared federal
disaster areas. Weather officials calculated winds in excess of 300
mph, including one tornado with winds of 318 mph, the fastest ever
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Only two people remained unaccounted for Sunday, a man and a
woman. Earlier two British tourists who had been counted as
missing, John and Barbara Potten, called their son in England, who
notified the Oklahoma Medical Examiner's Office that they were all
right. The couple are traveling through the United States in a
recreational vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   At First Baptist Church, Keating told those in attendance that
once again the people of Oklahoma have been tested and are showing
that despite the loss of life and property, their spirit remains
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge here today is to be here together as a feeling
family,'' Keating said. ``To rebuild we have to stay together. We
will be here together as an Oklahoma family.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was the same for the displaced Beth Haven
congregation. The church will go on, Casteel said, urging
worshipers to remember others who have been affected by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the only fish in the pond,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ester Fellin, 36, a church member whose mobile home in Bridge
Creek was destroyed by the tornado, said she and her husband and
their two children were not at home when the twister moved through
their area.
</P>
<P>
   Since it hit, the family has drawn strength from their
congregation. ``I don't know what we would have done without our
church family,'' she said before Sunday's service.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, several dozen Beth Haven members worked to clear
debris from a field next to the 5-year-old metal church building.
They raked insulation from the grass and dumped small pieces of
rubble into garbage cans. A line of large trees was to have become
a picnic area for parishioners. The trees now lay mangled, the bark
and leaves sucked from their trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Kitelinger walked toward the church, seeing the damage
for the first time. She and her husband, Frank, came to join the
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news didn't do it justice,'' she said, wiping tears from
her cheeks. ``On TV, you can't see how bad it is. I'm a little
shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   The day the storm hit, about 40 church members were signed up
for a money management class that was scheduled for 7 p.m. at the
church, which is across the street from Westmoore High School and
near the Emerald Springs Apartment complex where four people died.
</P>
<P>
   About 6:30 p.m., when newscasts announced that the powerful
storm was snaking toward the church, the class was canceled and
those who hadn't yet arrived were called and told to seek shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Some were en route and were told to leave as soon as they
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes after the last person left the church, the twister
hit.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the tornado, Casteel has heard from nearly 100
preachers from around the country who have offered support,
including one church in Richmond, Va., that is sending two
truckloads of donated items to Beth Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Casteel said what members don't need will be passed on to others
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   And he got a call from Choctaw, a town about 30 miles northeast
of Oklahoma City, where paperwork from the church was recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Kitelinger said she and her husband visited many churches before
deciding on Beth Haven. The tornado, its victims and the rebuilding
of the church will fortify the congregation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a family,'' Kitelinger said. ``I think it will pull us
together moreso. The spirit of the Lord is here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
