<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ITALIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS WINS ITALIAN OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Last week, Venus Williams became that rare American
visitor who will leave Rome wealthier than when she arrived. Now,
the next challenge for Williams, clay-court neophyte turned
clay-court master, will be to win her first Grand Slam singles
title on the same slippery surface in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of dreams, and most of them come true these
days,'' Williams told the crowd after winning the Italian Open
Sunday with a 6-4, 6-2 victory over Mary Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Williams lost in the Italian final to Martina
Hingis. This year, Hingis had to settle for winning the doubles
after Williams got the best of her in Saturday's semifinals and
then did a short but satisfied victory dance on center court.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's celebration was more subdued: two long arms thrust into
the air. But the satisfaction was there for all in the Foro Italico
to see, when Williams _ braces recently removed from her teeth _
stood grinning with her trophy at the victory ceremony, saving her
first and most enthusiastic pose for her sister Serena, who was on
the court with a camera.
</P>
<P>
   Serena has had a remarkable spring, but Venus is, for now, the
young woman to beat, even on clay, a surface she had never played a
tournament on until last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I understand it a little more,'' she said. ``I
think I've learned how to attack when I need to: to step up
sometimes and to keep the ball in play sometimes. In the past, I
didn't always know how to find the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Pierce was nursing a strained groin muscle before
Sunday's match and strained a hamstring during the match, there is
no reason to qualify what Williams has accomplished so far this
year. Since losing a quarterfinal and her composure against Lindsay
Davenport at the Australian Open, her play and results have
improved considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something is going wrong, you go out and fix it, and I went
and fixed everything that was going wrong,'' she said. ``Basically
I was making a lot of errors off the forehand, and I decided that I
would have to no longer be able to participate in that activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has won four tournaments in 1999, more than anyone
including Hingis, who is still ranked No. 1 to Williams' No. 5, but
who did not perform like it down the stretch on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That three-set victory was Williams' first over Hingis on clay,
but what happened against Pierce was no novelty. Only last week,
Williams defeated Pierce, 6-0, 6-3, in the final of the WTA event
in Hamburg to win her first clay-court event. Pierce was treated
for a back injury during that lopsided match, and Sunday, the
hard-slugging French woman whose imposing physique is paradoxically
fragile was treated again on court.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce had strained her groin during the semifinals, and she had
a small bandage on her upper-left thigh Sunday. That did not keep
her from matching Williams' power from the baseline in the early
going, but in the third game, Pierce said that she felt a sharp
pain in her left hamstring. After repeated visits from the trainer
on changeovers, she finished the match with the entire thigh
wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was bothering me for most of my shots and
running,'' said Pierce, who won the Italian Open in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Williams served 12 aces SUnday, rushed the net intelligently and
kept her power consistently under control from the baseline,
hitting 19 winners and making only 11 unforced errors. Though
Pierce broke her serve twice, the only time Williams truly lost her
concentration came at 3-2, 0-30 in the first set when a swarm of
bees sent fans in the upper bleachers shouting and scurrying for
cover as she prepared to hit a second serve. The result was a
double-fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``When her game is on, she's tough to beat,'' Pierce said.
``She's just powerful. The way to beat her is to take it to her and
keep her running. If you give her short balls, you tend to put
yourself in a difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   While Serena travels to Germany this week with mother Oracene to
play in Berlin, Venus will fly home to Florida and resume
practicing on green clay before returning to the red at the French
Open, which begins in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of confidence in my tennis, even before I won
these two tournaments,'' Venus said. ``It's just going to be up to
me the next two weeks to train hard and maintain the same level and
come back playing even better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
