<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-550&AMP;ADD-N     05-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE IS SPARED BOMBING FOR A NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO spared Belgrade from bombing overnight
Sunday, but said military targets there had not been taken off the
bombing list despite Friday's mistaken attack against the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military and civilian spokesmen blamed a failure by U.S.
and allied intelligence to determine the correct location of a
Yugoslav military supply headquarters that an American plane was
assigned to bomb for the error. The location the pilot was given
was in fact the spot where the embassy was built several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The error started in the intelligence gathering process,''
Jamie P. Shea, NATO's spokesman, said. ``It obviously went through
the system and was not identified.'' But he continued: ``We are not
going to be intimidated into stopping the bombing. The air campaign
is going to go on until Serb forces leave Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that a joint statement issued late Saturday in
Washington by Defense Secretary Bill Cohen and the director of
central intelligence, George J. Tenet, represented all that the
allies were likely to say in public about the reason for the
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   NATO apologized Saturday to the Chinese authorities for the
error and for the three deaths and 20 injuries it caused.
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany plans to express regrets in
person when he visits Beijing later this week, according to
diplomats here.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO planes struck no targets in Belgrade in the 24 hours
up to 9 a.m. Sunday, the 47th day in the allied bombing campaign to
stop attacks by the forces of President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia on the ethnic Albanian civilian population of Kosovo, a
senior diplomat said the allies had not ordered military commanders
to halt strikes on the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general sentiment was that we have to stay the course,''
the diplomat said, though allied ambassadors told military
commanders to exercise extra care in the target-selection process
to guard against any repetition of the error in hitting the Chinese
Embassy. The allied representatives here also asked Gen. Wesley K.
Clark, the military commander, to report to them personally this
week on the incident and on the progress of the bombing operations.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said its planes had flown more than 500 missions and bombed
targets throughout Serbia on Sunday despite poor weather, hitting
airfields at Nis, Pristina and Sjnenica, three bridges, and radio
and television transmitter sites at nine locations as well as
military barracks at Kragujevac and Valjevo and oil storage sites
at Lopatnica and Nis.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, the command said, pilots had bombed Yugoslav
artillery positions near the Albanian border west of Djakovica, and
11 artillery and mortar positions near the Macedonian border.
Allied bombers also hit Yugoslav troop positions and, elsewhere in
the province, they bombed reinforced military shelters, armored
vehicles, trucks and a command post.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the bombing in Kosovo this month, an allied
military spokesman, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz of Germany, said Sunday
that Yugoslav forces in the province had been pinned down and were
now increasingly unable to conduct the sweeps that have driven
hundreds of thousands of civilians from the province over the last
month and a half.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the bombing drove Yugoslav military units into hiding, Jertz
said, there had been a resurgence of activity by the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that our operations may be allowing them to provide
some protection for their kinfolk,'' Jertz said, although he added,
using the Albanian initials for the KLA: ``We are not the air force
of the UCK We are not supporting the UCK, either directly or
indirectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the allies' assertion that the bombing had slowed down
Yugoslav attacks, Shea said that 5,000 more refugees, most of them
from the city of Pec in western Kosovo, had poured across the
border into Albania Saturday and that 4,000 were expected there
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy Friday, the
allies had reached general agreement with Russia on the outlines of
a possible diplomatic solution that would end the fighting and
allow all the refugees to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A senior diplomat said that the allies hoped to keep up momentum
this week when Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott flies to
Moscow on Tuesday for two days of talks with Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The allies hope that Russia will eventually agree to a U.N.
Security Council resolution authorizing an international military
force to move into Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
