<DOCNO> NYT19990509.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAYER-COX     05-09 2066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Ohio churches high on Rocky Mountain prayer, worldwide
spirituality
</P>
<P>
   By Charlise Lyles
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS. Colo. _ This parched mountain valley at the
foot of Pikes Peak is the new epicenter of American power
evangelism.
</P>
<P>
   At its core is an unprecedented urgency about prayer.
</P>
<P>
   It radiates from dozens of Christian ministries such as the
conservative Focus on the Family, major promoters of the National
Day of Prayer, as well as the newly opened World Prayer Center,
Intercessors International and the Promise Keepers, farther north
in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium comes to a close, their message has penetrated
sanctuaries throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   These so-called ``parachurch ministries'' have taken prayer high
tech so that local churches can log on to the Prayer Room Network
and receive prayer request from people they may never talk to or
see.
</P>
<P>
   They've compelled Terri Sebree, a member of Dayton, Ohio's New
Covenant Church, to promote $10 Adopt-a-Leader kits to faithful who
wish to pray for city commissioners, state legislators or
congressional representatives.
</P>
<P>
   They've convinced Centerville, Ohio teen-agers Jennifer Knoll
and Lindsay Swift that they have ``a talent for prayer'' and should
fill out applications to become intercessors, praying for people
they do not know.
</P>
<P>
   And they have declared Dayton one of several ``strategic
cities'' ripe for millennial revival.
</P>
<P>
   The ministries have migrated to these mountains from across the
country, many from California, lured by the Lord, most of their
spokespeople will tell you. But beauty, quality of life, lower cost
of living and state tax incentives for nonprofit agencies are also
part of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, scores of Dayton churches have tuned in to
the Rocky Mountain prayer high and global evangelical movement.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Forrest Schwalm of Fairhaven Church in Centerville stays
tuned in to Colorado Springs ministries that sponsor programs such
as Prayer Track AD 2000, which aims to evangelize ``unreached
people'' by the century's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Prayer Center is going to have a growing influence
on prayer all over the United States,'' said Schwalm. ``It's going
to provide up-to-the-minute prayer requests and needs all over the
world. As a result of their hookups, you'll be able to pray for
people all over the world in seconds. ``There's an awareness that
the whole communications technology explosion has affected
Christians and Christian prayer life. People are aware of more info
and all of that contributes toward a prayer movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, says Schwalm and other evangelicals, is a sense of
millennial urgency and mission about prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer Central
</P>
<P>
   The steep curves of Highway 83 here could easily be dubbed the
highway to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   In between sleek Ford Aerospace buildings and a U.S. Olympic
Committee facility rise brand-new structures that will house
offices for expanding ministries. Just as you reach a summit, a
stucco semicircular fortress seems to rise out of the mountainside
like a mirage. Flags of 54 countries snap in the breeze above it.
This is the World Prayer Center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Pastor Ted Haggard was a 27-year-old up-and-coming
minister from York, Ind., praying and fasting on a Colorado
mountainside when he had a few visions. One revealed to him a place
where people could pray for global evangelism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just to pray.'' he said. ``This is where we connect
a global network of intercessors; we would link prayer
organizations all around the globe. And I saw a person standing
inside a globe praying. That's why the building is inside a circle
of flags. I saw a person go up to a kiosk and punch in how long he
had prayed and what he wanted to pray about.''
</P>
<P>
   Haggard's New Life Church donated $3 million and 2.2 acres for
the center. Evangelist C. Peter Wagner of Global Harvest
Ministries, which is located in the center, raised another $2.5
million to cover the total price tag, $5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   It opened in September 1998. Fourteen-foot floor-to-ceiling
windows reveal a panorama of Pikes Peak. Suspended from the
auditorium ceiling is a 2,200-pound transparent globe, 15 feet in
diameter, that rotates every hour. Underneath the building are six
miles of wiring and conduits. There's also a conference center; its
65-plus rooms include 10 ``extended prayer suites'' for overnight
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   A global network
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry about that, but we have very sensitive security
information in here,'' Faith, the receptionist, apologizes as a
door clicks locked behind a visitor entering the World Prayer
Center's inner sanctum.
</P>
<P>
   Inside is the computerized nerve center of world evangelism,
where prayer requests are categorized, coded, and in some cases,
secretly disseminated to intercessors.
</P>
<P>
   Using e-mail, faxes and a burgeoning Christian church computer
network, the center plans to link prayer requests from around the
world with millions of volunteers willing to pray for them. Derrick
Trimble staffs ``The Observatory,'' headquarters of the Prayer Room
Network and a cyber-cafe, a low-light, mauve-colored room with bar
stools and a bank of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who feel called to pray for others can log on to a server
here that will provide them prayer concerns on any topic from
personal to public. They can talk to missionaries or intercessors
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an international connecting point. We connect prayer
points,'' explains Trimble, a soft-spoken man of 39 in horn-rimmed
glasses seated behind a laptop computer. ``There are strategic
prayer concerns. We categorize them based on urgency and
sensitivity. In many ways, it's like a news service. But it's
focusing on items for prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the World Prayer Center's communication infrastructure
is designed to mobilize prayer instantly in churches across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does the customer want?'' is scribbled on the wipe board
across from Trimble's desk.
</P>
<P>
   He is also the marketing man. It's his job to sell the Prayer
Room Network (PRN) to 5,000 churches across the country for an
annual $300 subscription fee.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, churches can send prayer requests and ``receive
prayer information of state, national and global importance.'' And
they can connect with other prayer rooms for online discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Annual operating costs are estimated at $600,000 with a
round-the-clock staff seven days a week. The prayer software is
being developed in-house for three servers at a cost of up to
$40,000 each. ``When we get 5,000 PRNs, that'll cover our costs and
a little more for expansion,'' he says. ``We don't make any money
on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Prayer and commerce
</P>
<P>
   Just south of the World Prayer Center is Focus on the Family,
another prayer nerve center.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1977 in California by child psychologist James
Dobson, today Focus is a compound of new brick buildings, including
an amusement park-style visitors center. Its annual operating
budget for its 75 outreach ministries is $116 million, coming from
private donations about whom employees remain tight-lipped.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners hear Dobson's Christian values radio broadcasts on
2,500 stations in 95 countries. And his attempts to influence
Congress are infamous. In February 1988, he scolded the GOP,
calling the party a traitor to the evangelical constituency for
failure to approve ``pro-family'' and ``pro-moral'' legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Dobson's wife, Shirley, the National Day
of Prayer has taken hold across the country. Dobson's appearance at
the 1998 Dayton Mayor's Prayer Breakfast drew more than 3,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   On the third floor at Focus, thick carpets soften the bustle as
Jim Weidmann and the nine-member staff of the National Day of
Prayer Task Force worked to coordinate 5,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Shelves are lined with National Day of Prayer products: $10
Adopt-a-Leader kits to equip those who wish to pray for a city
commissioner, state legislator or congressional representative. Or
a $100 painting of George Washington praying in the woods of Valley
Forge by moonlight. There are prayer calendars, prayer coloring
books, a CD titled Let Us Pray and another book, The Myth of
Separation: A Revealing Look at What the Founders and the Courts
Really Say.
</P>
<P>
   And snug on Weidmann's wrist is one of the newest products, a
canvas bracelet whose woven threads spell ``Pray.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the money situation, people look at the catalog and
say, 'You're just selling stuff,''' said Weidmann. ``But we're
really just doing things to help people. A church can observe
National Day of Prayer with our resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Weidmann and his assistant, Robert Velarde, want to infuse
secular holidays such as the Fourth of July and Thanksgiving with
an awareness of Christian prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Dobsons' stances against homosexuality and in favor
of school prayer, Weidmann and Velarde maintain that their mission
is apolitical. ``Our only agenda is that we want to lift our nation
up,'' said Weidmann. ``We're not a political organization. We can't
endorse candidates. We do come from a certain perspective and
people may interpret that.''
</P>
<P>
   Worship with `no strings'
</P>
<P>
   When the National Day Task Force needed someone to train its
team of nationwide coordinators to pray, it called on the Rev. Ted
Haggard, the visionary.
</P>
<P>
   A slender, blond, laid-back guy who pads about the World Prayer
Center in his socks, Haggard wraps a sweet, almost prepubescent
voice around a listener as he cozies up in a big leather chair in
the atrium.
</P>
<P>
   He is a self-described political conservative and charismatic
Christian, a believer in the gifts of prophecy and intercession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a church where people could worship with no strings
attached _ endless boards, bickering, bureaucracy, formality,
jealously. But prayer would be the focal point ''
</P>
<P>
   His vision for a hassle-free church has come true. The North
American Church Growth Association has called his 8,000-member
charismatic New Life Church one of the fastest-growing in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   New Life stands just across the parking lot from the World
Prayer Center. Outside, the mountain air is thin. Inside, people
seem breathless for God. Completed in 1992, it is a cavernous _
70,000 square feet _ two-story concrete slab structure. There are
no angels in the architecture, no stained-glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   Worship is just as simple. Rather than preaching, Sunday
services center on informal worship and prayer. Members stand,
reach their hands to heavens or sit quietly, praying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This church teaches you to have a love relationship with God
through prayer,'' said Dale Pitts, 41, a construction worker who
attends church in overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Living Word Church in Vandalia, Ohio closely resembles New Life.
The building is a simple, mall-like structure. Its roof, painted
royal blue, rises above a subdivision. And inside, members are
eager to pray as intercessors for others.
</P>
<P>
   Tommi Femrite, a member of New Life and vice president of
Intercessors International, recently brought her campaign to
recruit intercessors for global prayer to Living Word. Femrite says
Dayton is ``a key city militarily and spiritually'' and ripe for
revival because of growing prayer activity.
</P>
<P>
   Two Centerville High School students who could have been out
partying on a recent Friday night enrolled to be intercessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in a panicky situation, God answered before I could
get the words out,'' said Jennifer Knoll, 17. ``I want to be able
to pray for others like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Intercessors International will provide her ``code names'' of
three pastors and their problems. She will pray 15 minutes daily.
In turn, she will receive a progress report on the pastors.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Clark, a saleswoman who attends Living Word, gives thanks
to the intercessory prayer movement emanating from Colorado
Springs. It's in the marrow of her church now, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started smoking MarIboros when I was 12 years old and I've
never been able to quit, '' said Clark, 41. ``I haven't had a
cigarette since the second week in December. People here prayed and
fasted for me to quit smoking. And I believe their prayers set me
free to feel the spirit of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlise Lyles writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
