<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGHED-UP ANGELS SWEPT IN BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Angels manager Terry Collins sat in his office Sunday
afternoon after his club's 4-2 loss to the Boston Red Sox, and
didn't have the scowl he usually has after a loss.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any reason for a scowl, it was Sunday. The loss
before 23,710 at Fenway Park ended a three-game sweep at the hands
of the Red Sox. It was the Angels' fourth loss in a row and sixth
in seven games. They fell six games under .500 (13-19) for the
first time this season and remain alone in last place.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins was relatively calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had other options, we'd look at it,'' Collins said of a
lineup that is missing four starters because of injury. ``But we
don't. We've got to get it done with this bunch. As guys get
healthy, we'll have more options.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the Angels lineup Sunday included Dave Silvestri at
shortstop, Jeff Huson at second base, Orlando Palmeiro in right
field and Charlie O'Brien at catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are fortunate to be part of a division (AL West) in
which no team is playing much better than .500 ball. But it doesn't
get any easier for Anaheim, which will begin a three-game series
against the defending World Series champion Yankees on Tuesday
night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking a lot of guys to do a lot of things they
shouldn't have to do,'' Collins said. ``We have young players that
hopefully will learn by it and down the road be better for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reach inside ourselves. They're down, no question.
But I'll tell you one thing, they're trying. You see it on their
faces all game long. They're trying, they're into it. They'll break
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, they don't seem close to breaking out of their
team-wide batting slump. Although they had 10 hits Sunday _ the
most they've had in seven games _ they still couldn't come up with
the big hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' only runs against Red Sox starter Mark Portugal
(3-1) scored on an RBI single by Palmeiro in the second inning and
an RBI double by Silvestri in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The one Angel slumping more than any other is third baseman Troy
Glaus, who is 2 for 27 with 11 strikeouts in his past seven games.
Glaus, off to a sizzling start, has seen his batting average fall
to .282.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be fine; he's handled it good,'' Collins said. ``He's
taking extra batting practice, trying to correct things. His swing
right now is a little long and he might be tired, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Ken Hill (1-2) had lasted at least seven innings
in his previous four starts but couldn't make it out of the fourth
inning Sunday. He gave up four runs and seven hits in 32/3 innings.
And when Collins came to the mound with two out in the fourth, Hill
initially refused to give Collins the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to give him the ball,'' Hill said. ``I wanted to
keep battling. I'm not a quitter. No matter what the situation, if
you're up or down, I want to keep fighting. I take pride in what I
do. Nobody wants to be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a perfect first inning, but after that he lost a little
bit of rhythm, which is what he uses for command,'' Collins
explained. ``He struggled after that. I didn't want to leave him in
and have him start searching for things and changing his
mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill gave up a solo home run to Nomar Garciaparra in the second
inning, and, in the third, gave up a two-out RBI single to Troy
O'Leary despite being ahead in the count 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a fastball inside and I didn't get it in
there,'' Hill said. ``I was too fine with it instead of burying it
in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating because we're not playing well. It's
frustrating because you want to give good, quality innings and keep
the game close because we're not scoring many runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox added two runs in the fourth on an RBI triple by
Damon Buford and a sacrifice fly by Jose Offerman.
</P>
</TEXT>
