<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANTON COMES THROUGH FOR YANKS IN PITCHING EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Stanton grinned like a pig farmer who had been
asked to play golf at a private club, after he was informed he
would start against the Seattle Mariners Sunday. Truth be told, the
Yankees' coaching staff wished it had never had to submit the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, would have greatly
preferred that Ramiro Mendoza had shaken off his viral infection
and pitched, as scheduled, rather than turn to Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   But Mendoza's temperature soared and his throat swelled, and
Stanton stepped in and prepared in his own weird left-handed
reliever way and shut out the Mariners for the first four innings.
In his first start in the major leagues after 552 relief
appearances _ a record for calls as a reliever before getting a
first start _ Stanton established a beachhead for the Yankees in
their 6-1 victory against Seattle before 49,622 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley followed Stanton and threw four strong innings _
prompting complaints from Mariners manager Lou Piniella that
Grimsley was illegally scuffing the ball _ and earned the victory,
improving his record to 4-0. Derek Jeter slugged his seventh home
run, a 430-foot blast that landed at the base of the monuments in
left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Yankees optioned outfielder Ricky Ledee to Class
AAA Columbus and called up Shane Spencer, who will be given a
chance to become the everyday left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer's angst over demoting the likable Ledee was diminished by
the performances of Stanton and Grimsley, for the circumstances
were ominous. The Yankees had no fully rested starters available,
and their bullpen had been depleted by the recent workload. Mendoza
began feeling ill on Saturday, but Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching
coach, figured Mendoza would get better overnight. When Brian
Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, offered to call up a pitcher
from Class AAA, perhaps a starter, Zimmer and Stottlemyre insisted
that no, they would get by.
</P>
<P>
   Except that Mendoza felt worse Sunday, leaving Stanton and
Grimsley as the only viable options to start in his place. Zimmer
picked Stanton _ the fact that the left-handed-hitting Ken Griffey
Jr. was to bat in the first inning might have been a deciding
factor _ and hoped Stanton would pitch two or three good innings
and Grimsley two or three innings before the Yankees somehow turned
over a lead to Mariano Rivera in the eighth. David Cone, slated to
work out in the bullpen Sunday, volunteered to throw an inning in
relief, and Zimmer and Stottlemyre did not say no immediately.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the Mariners had pounded Stanton? A pitching
disaster, with Zimmer possibly turning to position players to throw
the late innings. ``We could've been a little bit embarrassed
today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton felt no pressure, in a sense. This was something
different, something fresh. ``This was fun,'' said Stanton, who was
switched from a starter to a reliever in the minor leagues in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton trades his share of one-liners with starting pitchers
over the supposed ease of the starters' professional lifestyle, and
after Stottlemyre informed Stanton of his emergency start Sunday,
at about 11 a.m., Stanton mostly stayed with the normal routine of
a reliever. He shagged fly balls during batting practice, a
practice unheard of by starting pitchers. Stottlemyre expected
Stanton to begin warming up at 1:20 p.m. at the latest, about 15
minutes before game time.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton _ who sometimes warms up in the bullpen with as few as
10 pitches _ did not start throwing until 1:27 p.m. Even then, he
threw just 20 pitches or so; most starters require 50 to 60 to warm
up.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton did not return to the dugout after his pregame warmups,
going to the mound directly from the bullpen, just before the game
was to begin. The strangest part of the day, he said, was standing
on the mound for the national anthem; he had never done that in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   As enjoyable as it was, however, Stanton understood the great
need for him to pitch at least adequately, and that pressure, he
said, forced him to concentrate. ``I hate to say there are times
that my concentration is not what it should be,'' Stanton said,
``but that definitely happens. But when the adrenaline gets going,
those are the easy times to concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrying a 12.86 earned run average into the game, Stanton,
working from the stretch as always, threw far better than he had at
any time this season, getting strikes with all four of his pitches.
Zimmer said he felt good about Stanton right away, seeing him get
ahead in the count early and repeatedly. The Mariners did not get
their first hit until Dan Wilson plunked an opposite-field double
in the third inning, and by then the Yankees led, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton threw 42 pitches in the first three innings _ ``It was
the most strikes I've seen him throw in two years,'' Cone cracked _
and Stanton opened the fourth by walking David Bell. Grimsley
popped up in the bullpen and Stottlemyre walked slowly to the
mound. Stanton knew he was just trying to kill time for Grimsley to
warm up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You OK?'' Stottlemyre asked. Yes, Stanton replied, and
Stottlemyre asked again and Stanton answered the same way, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know why I'm out here,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton retired the next three batters, however, and lobbied to
pitch the fifth inning. But Stottlemyre explained that if Stanton
did that, he would not be available to relieve in Tuesday's game,
and Stanton departed, returning to his life as a reliever with his
perfect 0.00 ERA as a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cakewalk,'' Stanton said, laughing, like a pig farmer
who hit a hole-in-one at the club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
