<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL ALTERS THE KNICK-HEAT, GRIND-IT-OUT EQUATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Latrell Sprewell was standing for the cameras after
practice, decked with yellow-tinted, black-rimmed sunglasses to
accessorize his hip braids and complete a look fit for the South
Beach scene.
</P>
<P>
   It seems he could have easily found his niche here, in the
sunshine, on a team that needed a shooting guard, playing for Pat
Riley. He knows how close he was to that reality when the Heat and
Knicks were jockeying to acquire him in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here, so yeah, I'm happy I ended up with New York, I
guess,'' Sprewell said after the Knicks practiced in preparation
for Game 2 of their first-round series against Miami set for Monday
at Miami Arena. ``But if I was in Miami, I'd probably be saying the
same thing about being with them.''
</P>
<P>
   His transition from league outcast to reinstated star might have
been easier in Miami: less pressure, less chance of playing off the
bench, less unhappiness. But Riley pulled out of the running for
Sprewell at the 11th hour. The Knicks' management took the risk
with the belief that the slashing three-time All-Star could nudge
them ahead of the Heat and Pacers in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sprewell began to raise eyebrows with his reckless
style and grumble about his sixth-man role, and when the Knicks
were on the verge of missing the playoffs, the Heat was sticking
its flag into the top of the division.
</P>
<P>
   Who needed Sprewell? The Heat earned the top seeding in the
East, while the Knicks picked up the pieces of their season in time
to grab the eighth and final spot. But after finally finding
harmony with Sprewell, the Knicks reversed their underdog status
and shocked the Heat in Game 1 with their 95-75 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome defied expectation. This was supposed to be a
grind-it-out, halfcourt kind of meeting between two teams that
mirror each other. But the addition of Sprewell distorts that
reflection to an extent. He is not like any Knick that Riley has
prepared for in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they'll play me next,'' Sprewell said. ``You
just have to adjust to what happens. I know they'll come out fired
up, though.''
</P>
<P>
   This matchup may yet revert to its buttoned-down personality of
the past if Miami makes some of the open shots it missed on
Saturday and puts the Knicks in a tighter, more pressured
situation. With that in mind, the Knicks restrained themselves from
gloating Sunday. They were cautiously optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can come back to New York with two games, we can close
the series out, hopefully,'' Kurt Thomas said. ``We just have to
keep working together. We all knew we had a great player in
Latrell. It was just a matter of jelling.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Sprewell's contorted shots continue to fall, that
cohesiveness stands a better chance of sustaining itself. He gives
the Knicks a look the Heat doesn't have. Sprewell is the Knick
alternative to the predictable halfcourt world lorded over by
Patrick Ewing. The Heat may not be able to win if Alonzo Mourning
doesn't dominate. But the Knicks have consistently shown they can
thrive even when Ewing has to gingerly step back from his go-to
role because of a sore Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way of knowing how mobile Ewing will be in Game 2.
Typically, he has needed more than a day's rest before feeling good
enough to spin for layups and slide laterally to defend. If Ewing
becomes more of a rebounder and shot blocker _ just as he was in
Game 1 _ the Knicks have other methods of scoring. Such as
Sprewell, for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big guy knows that there are other players here
who can take the load off his shoulders, somewhat,'' said Sprewell,
who complemented Allan Houston's 22 points with 22 of his own in
Game 1. ``But we want Patrick in there. He was excellent in
rebounding and blocking shots on Saturday. That was great for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to know that he doesn't have to do it all. But we
haven't always played that way. He has had to be the dominant guy.
We want him to feel less of the burden. Hopefully, we can do our
part to have a team effort. That's when we're playing our best
basketball, when everyone is doing something on the floor to help
each other, and it's not just one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the theme for the Knicks in their last eight games of
the regular season. During that 6-2 span, five different Knicks
were the team's top scorer: Ewing twice, Sprewell three times, then
Houston, Larry Johnson and Marcus Camby. The pattern extended to
Game 1 when Houston and Sprewell led the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this is the best we've played this year, as far as
playing together on both ends of the floor and the confidence of
the team,'' Sprewell said. ``Right now, we're at a level that we
really haven't been at this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Sprewell is living with his sixth-man role, albeit
begrudgingly. Maybe he would have found a more comfortable niche as
a Heat star. He'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just flattered that both teams wanted me,'' Sprewell
said. ``Two first-class organizations. You couldn't go wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
