<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS2-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PRETTY BOYS LEADING WAY FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mike Keane, Grant Marshall, Brian Skrudland and Dave
Reid are not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   That's an observation that has nothing to do with the scraggly
beards and long hair of Keane and Marshall, Skrudland's receding
hairline or Reid's circa-1950 crew cut.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is it a commentary on the assorted scars, cuts and
missing teeth common to men who make their living playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   No, this has nothing to do with physical appearance. This is
about style of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have their share of pretty players. Mike Modano, Joe
Nieuwendyk Jere Lehtinen and Sergei Zubov are fancy skaters and
puck handlers. Brett Hull has a gorgeous slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing attractive about the play of Keane and Co.,
however.
</P>
<P>
   They bump, they grind, they push, they shove, they hit, they
hold. They annoy, they pester.
</P>
<P>
   They win.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars take a 2-0 lead into St. Louis today for Game 3 of the
best-of-seven, Western Conference semifinal series, thanks largely
to the play of the grinders.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk deservedly grabbed the headlines after his
game-winning goal in overtime of Game 2 on Saturday night, but the
Stars wouldn't have been in position to win without the
contributions of the blue-collar, lunch-pail guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game really started to turn in our favor when some of the
grinders really started getting a bigger bite in the game,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``grinders'' primarily are Marshall, Keane, Skrudland, Reid,
Guy Carbonneau _ who's out with a knee injury but is expected back
for Game 4 on Wednesday _ Blake Sloan and Benoit Hogue. They spend
most of their time on the third and fourth lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're out there, they do good things,'' said Stars
defenseman and captain Derian Hatcher. ``That's what we expect from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't score much, although Keane got the Stars' third goal
_ and his second of the postseason _ after a feed from Marshall in
the 5-4 victory on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not their job. Their job is to keep the other team
from scoring, to do the dirty work, to play hard, to provide energy
on every shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to score; that's the name of the game,'' Sloan
said. ``But the third- and fourth-line guys like Marshall and Keane
and myself, it's our job to keep it down in their zone. If we keep
the pressure on, it really wears them down. That's our job. To
create more opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan is playing that role so well he's creating playing
opportunities for himself. Even though he's listed at a charitable
5-foot-10, he leads the Stars in hits in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hits come in the opponents' end, as Sloan and his
fellow grinders battle to keep the other team from getting the puck
up the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep it down low and keep the other team from
getting scoring opportunities, that's how we gauge a good shift,''
said Sloan, whose playing time comes at the expense of Tony Hrkac,
who's a better scorer. ``It's a tough role, but a fun role.''
</P>
<P>
   The grinders are so important that they play at the expense of
Hull's best game.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Hull is most effective in a three-line rotation.
But the benefits of playing four lines outweigh having the former
86-goal scorer at his absolute best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a four-line team,'' Hitchcock said after Saturday's
game. ``We're a 12-forward team. We needed everybody to win the
hockey game.''
</P>
<P>
   The grinders weren't at their best in the first two periods of
Game 2. The pretty players on both players controlled the game,
racing up and down the ice and creating scoring chance after
scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues led, 4-3, after two periods against a team that hadn't
given up more than two goals in its first five games in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the blue-collar guys took over after that.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues had 24 shots in the first 40 minutes. They got off
only seven in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a huge third period from Mike Keane and his line,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``They did a tremendous job controlling the puck
down low. They give the kind of effort you have to have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the overtime, the fourth line almost scored the game winner.
Skrudland kept poking at a puck that Blues goalie Grant Fuhr might
or might not have covered and finally slid it across the line, but
the play was blown dead.
</P>
<P>
   However, while that was going on, Marshall was on the ice
tussling with the Blues' Terry Yake. Both players drew roughing
penalties, creating a four-on-four game for two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough time, and gave enough space, for the
pretty-skating Nieuwendyk to score the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of will,'' Hitchcock said. ``Maybe it wasn't the
strongest positional game, but we played hard for 60 minutes.
That's our team, and that's the way we've played all playoffs.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
