<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BLUES WINGER IS GOAL-ORIENTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A pack of media members surrounded St. Louis
winger Pavol Demitra's locker after practice several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty popular, eh?'' Blues winger Blair Atcheynum joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants same thing,'' Demitra said, forlornly.
``Everyone wants to ask why I'm not scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Well now that you mention it Pavol, why aren't you?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Demitra said. ``I really don't know. Maybe in
Game 2, I score.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring hadn't been a question in the regular season. Demitra,
24, led St. Louis in goals (37) and assists (52). He had 52 points
in all of 1997-98, his first full NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's maybe not producing at the rate he did over the course of
the year, but he's one of those guys who all of a sudden: `Boom' is
going to snap out of it and have a big night,'' Blues coach Joel
Quenneville said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Quenneville a psychic; Demitra went ``boom'' in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   He scored twice in Saturday's 5-4 loss, tallying St. Louis'
first and last goals. The Blues probably will need more of the same
from Demitra if they are going to get back in this best-of-seven
series with a victory in Game 3 tonight in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I have to do. I have to score goals,'' Demitra
said. ``I score a couple of goals \Rin Game 2\S, but not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Blues brass gambled in the off-season that Demitra and others
could fill a scoring role left when Brett Hull signed with the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he would be able to remained a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already heard that question probably 1,000 times,'' Demitra
said.
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't been asked, though, Demitra said he wouldn't have
thought about it. He said nobody in the Blues organization had
talked to him about replacing Hull.
</P>
<P>
   The two are about as different as Dallas and Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Hull loved the spotlight. He liked talking about the big goal
almost as much as he liked scoring it. Demitra, well, he would just
as soon leave that kind of stuff to guys like Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adulation and exposure he gets from being a top scorer,''
Quenneville said, ``he probably wishes he never had it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain pressure that comes with being the man. It
was a pressure that Quenneville said Demitra took very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started the year, we figured we should get more
balanced scoring from a number of people, Jimmy Campbell, Pavol,
Geoff Courtnall, Scotty Young,'' Quenneville said. ``Pavol emerged
as a key guy as far as producing for us. I think he surprised a
number of people including ourselves with his offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the top 10 scorers in the league, which he was
one of them, the other nine are superstars.''
</P>
<P>
   Try Demitra in a group with Jaromir Jagr, Peter Forsberg, Eric
Lindros and Theo Fleury?
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't supposed to be there, but he was.
</P>
<P>
   So when the goals stopped coming _ Demitra didn't score in the
last four games of the Blues' seven-game, first-round series
against Phoenix _ the questions started coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My response is scoring goals. That is what I want to do,''
Demitra said. ``I'm just starting. ... I'm still learning, just
learning. I think I can do much better.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
