<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL UNFAZED BY ST. LOUIS BOOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Brett Hull said he doesn't expect to be
welcomed back to St. Louis today _ not with the Stars leading the
best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals series 2-0 and Blues
fans looking to find a villain.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he has no problem with the fans of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if they boo me. They booed me in the preseason
game I played there. They booed me in the regular-season game I
played there,'' Hull said. ``They pay their money for the tickets.
They have the right to boo.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who played 11 seasons in a Blues uniform and scored the
majority of his 586 career regular-season goals (13th all-time in
the NHL), said he still loves the city of St. Louis, still has
plenty of friends in St. Louis and still respects the fans and
their love of the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been over this a lot,'' said Hull, who was allowed to
walk as a free agent last summer when the Blues refused to give him
a no-trade clause in his contract. The Stars signed him to a
three-year deal for $17 million. ``Management there made a decision
that they wanted to go a new direction, that they wanted to go with
youth, and that's just business. But what I had there and what I
gained playing and living there, that hasn't gone away. It's a
great city and they have great fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Blues fans now see Hull as an opponent, if not a
traitor. And Hull said after training camp he would no longer sign
St. Louis Blues sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Dallas Star now,'' Hull said. ``We've gone through all
that stuff, and now I'm just another guy they like to hate.''
VERBEEK TO RETURN Stars winger Pat Verbeek is expected back in the
lineup tonight after sitting out a one-game NHL suspension for
slashing Pierre Turgeon in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek said he didn't expect retribution from the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just go in there and play,'' he said. ``As far as I'm
concerned, it's over.'' STREAKING Just as the Stars have a chance
to set a franchise record tonight by winning their seventh
consecutive playoff game, three Stars players also have the chance
to extend playoff streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner had a goal and an assist Friday in Game 2
and now has scored a point in five consecutive playoff games _ a
career best for the 23-year-old winger. Langenbrunner has three
goals and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano also is on a career-best streak as he
has points in six consecutive games. Modano assisted on Jere
Lehtinen's game-tying goal in Game 2. Modano has two goals and four
assists in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Zubov assisted on a goal for the fourth consecutive game.
He has six assists in the playoffs. CONGRATULATORY CALL Stars
center Guy Carbonneau, who was in Quebec after the death of his
father Thursday, called the Stars' locker room to congratulate Joe
Nieuwendyk on his overtime goal after Game 2. Carbonneau will
attend the funeral of his father today and is expected to join the
Stars tomorrow in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau, who has missed the past four games with a knee
injury, is expected to need only one skate to be ready and is
listed as likely to play in Game 4 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
