<HEADLINE>
BLUES' CHASE SCOFFS AT REPORT OF FINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Blues winger Kelly Chase said reports that
he had been fined $1,000 for throwing a water bottle at Stars
winger Pat Verbeek in the tunnel following Game 1 are false.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even throw a water bottle,'' Chase said. ``Some knob
head reported that without talking to me or talking to Verbeek.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek was called for slashing Blues center Pierre Turgeon with
2:18 remaining in Game 1. The Blues were upset, saying Verbeek
intended to injure Turgeon. Chase said he wasn't upset enough to
throw a water bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Would Turgeon have helped if he had been fined $1,000?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' Chase said. GOING HOME Home hasn't exactly
been helpful for the Blues in the playoffs. They were 1-2 at Kiel
Center in the first round against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Blues center Pierre Turgeon said he thinks part of the problem
is they are always coming home trailing in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to go back home 1-1, but we've got to move on
and think about the third game,'' Turgeon said. ``It's not like
we've never been in that situation before.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis came back from down 3-1 in the series to defeat
Phoenix and advance to the second round. MORAL VICTORIES The Blues
had been saying all along that they thought they could defeat the
Stars. They sounded convinced following Game 2 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues played well enough to win and had a 4-3 lead in the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look at that game like we could beat them,'' St.
Louis defenseman Chris Pronger said. ``With a couple of bounces
here and there and scoring, I guess we could finish them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blues coach Joel Quenneville: ``Certainly, we proved we've
got a chance against these guys. It's not a hopeless situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
