<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FOURSOME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FOUR COURSEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ All right, so they're not exactly The Four
Horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   How about The Four Coursemen?
</P>
<P>
   When Mark Brooks, Clark Dennis, Alan Bratton and Lindy Miller
stride the fairways of the TPC course at Las Colinas in this week's
GTE Byron Nelson Classic, they surely will be making some kind of
local golf history.
</P>
<P>
   Four players, three of them PGA Tour pros, from the same club _
Fort Worth's Mira Vista Golf Club _ teeing it up in a Tour event on
the same weekend, near their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Come Sunday, could there be an all Mira Vista leader board at
the Nelson?
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice,'' said Brooks, who won the 1996 PGA
Championship. ``We've got quite a few guys in the field, so that
helps your chances. Hopefully, everybody plays good.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an occurrence would catch the attention of Mira Vista's 500
members, said Miller, the club professional who will compete in the
Nelson for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mark or Clark or Alan are in contention on the weekend,
there's a real buzz in the locker room,'' said Miller.
``Everybody's talking about it. When the telecast is ready to come
on, everybody gets ready to watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the three touring pros spend much of their time on
the road, they play frequently at Mira Vista, and Brooks, 38, even
owns a home there. As a result, Miller said, members of the private
club have adopted the three pros as their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have something in common with our members,'' Miller
explained. ``There's a bond between them because they are out there
among them playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hardin, a Mira Vista member who has played with Dennis,
Brooks and Bratton, says members follow their progress on the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we do when we get the sports pages is check to
see what those guys shot,'' Hardin said. ``We know to look for the
dark \Rboldfaced\S names in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the chat when we're out on the range: what Alan or Mark
or Clark shot. We keep up with them. It adds something when someone
you've played with at home is out there competing with the best in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the three pros spend varying amounts of time at the
club ``because they're at different stages of their lives. They've
got families and those sorts of responsibilities. Alan spends more
time than the others because he and his wife don't have any kids.
When he's in town, he gets out and plays with the members.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, Miller said, plays about six days a week at Mira Vista
when he's home and even comes out to chip on Mondays. Brooks and
Dennis, he added, play two or three times a week when they are in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis said he, Brooks and Bratton are aware of how the other
members of their Mira Vista contingent are faring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always check,'' said Dennis, the 33-year-old Fort Worth
native who had his best year on Tour last season, earning more than
$400,000 and posting a third-place finish at the Kemper Open. ``I'd
like to see us all play good the same week. I'd love it if we could
get three top 10s this week.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, at the Nissan Open at Riviera Country Club in
Pacific Palisades, Calif., Dennis glanced up and saw the leader
board, which showed that, like himself, Brooks had shot a
3-under-par 68, and that Bratton had fired a 4-under 67.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' Dennis remarked. ``Mira Vista shot 10-under
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis plays regularly with Hardin and Mira Vista members Vance
Minter, Dan Dunkelberg and Mark Wolf, he said. Dennis might even
have a home at Mira Vista in his future; he has purchased a lot
behind the 13th green.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Dennis nor Bratton nor Brooks are carrying their playing
partners at the club, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get some good games going out there,'' Dennis said. ``I've
really got to play. I can't lay down. I don't have to give those
guys strokes. I'm the one who needs strokes sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Minter, who has known Dennis since he was 15 years old, said the
friendly games on the course aren't altered by the fact that a PGA
Tour pro is among the foursomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all such good friends,'' Minter said. ``And I know the
members enjoy having them around. There's no intimidation at all.
Each one is such a really good guy that we pull for all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, 27, credits his Mira Vista games with helping prepare
him for his successful performance in November at PGA Tour
Qualifying School in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with them got me through Tour school. They got me
ready,'' said Bratton. ``There aren't many country clubs where I
can go and have a good game with members. If I don't play good, a
couple of those guys can whip me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going through the learning stages right now,'' Hardin
said of Bratton. ``He's going to be a heck of a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect a lot of Nelson spectators from Fort Worth to be watching
Miller, too, this week. A top player at Oklahoma State, he was a
regular at the event through the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And, Bratton advises, don't underestimate Miller's chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a great player,'' Bratton said. ``He could be out
here \Ron the Tour\S if he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Mira Vista members said they'll head over to Irving to
watch their club's representatives at the Nelson; others said
they'll wait to catch them next week at the Mastercard Colonial in
Fort Worth. The only issue for members is which golfer to root for.
</P>
<P>
   Minter has the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe, I could pull against anyone of them,'' he
said. ``Everybody out here is pulling for every one of them.''
Staff writer Jimmy Burch contributed to this report. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
