<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-EXPOS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      05-09 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Perhaps Tim Bogar has the solution for whatever ails Chris Holt
during the first inning of almost every ballgame.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bogey told me he was going to pitch the first inning and I
could take over after that,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a worth a try. Bogey would be better than quadruple
bogey, which is what Holt carded in the first inning Sunday for the
second start in a row. And just like before, the deficit proved too
great to overcome for the Astros, who fell 4-2 to the Montreal
Expos before a Mother's Day crowd of 24,804 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Mama may have said there'd be days like this for Holt, but it's
doubtful she was suggesting it would happen with such regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the 24 earned runs Holt has allowed this year have
come in the first inning, including 11 first-inning runs over his
last three starts. After the first inning of his last three
outings, Holt has allowed only one earned run in 15 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' said Holt, who hasn't had a
1-2-3 first inning in six starts this year. ``For some reason, I'm
just not finding a groove in the first inning. I can't put my
finger on it. I give up a hit here, a hit there, and the next thing
I know we're down 4-0. I'm going to have to get it figured out.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt tried to remedy the problem Sunday by simulating an inning
in the bullpen before he took the mound. So much for that idea; the
Expos piled up five hits and enough runs to win the game before the
Astros stepped into the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just in a funk,'' Holt said. ``It's more of a mental
thing. I can't be anticipating bad things happening. I've got to
shake this. I know I'm 0-5, but I can easily rattle off five wins
and get back to .500.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' record at the Astrodome dropped to .500 after the
bottom-rung Expos took two of three in the series. Prior to
arriving in Houston, the Expos had lost four of their previous six
games.
</P>
<P>
   But they managed to have a big inning against Shane Reynolds on
Saturday and one against Holt on Sunday, while their pitching staff
stifled the Astros, who hit a tepid .248 in the series and left 26
runners on base, including 13 in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, they were held in check by righthander Carl Pavano
(2-4), who spaced seven hits over seven innings while lowering his
ERA to 5.54.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would have done much more against Pavano,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``He left a lot of pitches up
(in the strike zone), and he wasn't throwing extremely hard. But we
never really got to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos had trouble getting to Holt after the first inning. He
retired eight of the next 13 batters he faced, but by then it was
too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's typically the way it happens when a pitcher falls
behind,'' Dierker said. ``You start to relax, and you pitch
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The continuation of Holt's first-inning curse began with a
one-out walk to Jose Vidro, who scored on Brad Fullmer's single to
left. Third baseman Shane Andrews, who drove in five of the Expos'
12 runs in the series, followed with a two-run single, and Orlando
Cabrera also had an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holt's problem is that he hasn't had good command,'' Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's clearly a different pitcher once he gets out of the
first inning. In the first inning, Holt has a 19.50 ERA and
opponents are hitting a whopping .548 against him. After the first,
he is holding opponents to a .269 batting average and has a 3.49
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my ability is, and I know I've got good enough
stuff,'' Holt said. ``It's just a matter of concentrating and
getting three quick outs in the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett's bases-loaded sacrifice fly to center scored Craig
Biggio to slice the Expos' lead to three runs in the bottom of the
first. It was the first time Everett had been at the plate with the
bases loaded this season.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, who walked three times Sunday despite entering the
game with just six walks on the season, drew a leadoff walk in the
third and scored on Bill Spiers' single to left.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros collected only one hit over the next three innings
and five for the remainder of the game. Expos closer Ugueth Urbina
struck out two batters in the ninth and stranded runners at second
and third for his second save in as many days and his sixth of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urbina's tough,'' said Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell, who
was 0-for-5 with two strikeouts. ``The way I was playing, it
wouldn't have mattered who was out there, but he's tough. Those
kids (the Expos) may be young, but they're tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Expos' 10-19 record, it sure seemed that way over
the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
