<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO' ILLS FOR VAUGHN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Just when it didn't look like things could get any
worse for the Angels, Mo Vaughn seems to have suffered a setback
with his sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   According to Vaughn's father, Leroy, Vaughn's ankle has
considerable swelling and is hurting. Vaughn might have to return
to the designated-hitter spot Tuesday when the Angels begin a
three-game series in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is gimpy,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``You can
tell his ankle is bothering him. But I asked him how it was and he
said it feels OK. We'll talk about it in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn wouldn't use his ankle as an excuse for going 1 for 11
with six strikeouts in the three games against the Red Sox. In
fact, Vaughn wasn't talking at all to the media after Sunday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fried,'' Angels spokesman Tim Mead said. ``He's done more
(for the media during the weekend in Boston) than he should have
been expected to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was not on the team flight to New York, instead taking a
later flight so he could spend more time at his North Easton,
Mass., home with his parents and sister.
</P>
<P>
   Hurts getting better: Both right fielder Tim Salmon and second
baseman Randy Velarde made progress with their respective injuries
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon (sprained left wrist) hit off a tee and said while there
is still some pain he was able to swing the bat ``pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to do this,'' Salmon said, ``to see where we're at
and how it responds (today). Tuesday maybe I'll take some early
hitting and go from there. It's encouraging, it's a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, who will have therapy on the wrist today, is hoping to
return during the series against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde (stiff lower back) also plans to take batting practice
Tuesday in New York and possibly play in the series.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell thrown out, again: For the second season in a row,
pitcher Jack McDowell was ejected from a game despite not being on
the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, on the disabled list recovering from shoulder surgery,
was thrown out of Sunday's game by third-base umpire John Shulock.
It happened in the fourth inning after Damon Buford tagged and
scored from third on a sacrifice fly by Jose Offerman. It appeared
that Buford might have left early, and the Angels appealed.
</P>
<P>
   After Shulock gave the safe sign, he stormed toward the Angels
dugout, pointing his finger. McDowell got off the bench and yelled
back and was tossed.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, who refused comment after the game, was thrown out of
a game last season in June when the Angels and Royals fought in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Mound time: It had been four days since closer Troy Percival had
gotten any work, so Collins put him in the game in the eighth
inning Sunday despite not being in a save situation.
</P>
<P>
   Percival came in with a runner on first and two out, and needed
only one pitch to retire John Valentin and end the inning. The Red
Sox didn't bat in the ninth because they had the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``One pitch is about as little work as you can get in a game,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, the Yankees: Last season, the Angels arrived in New
York in August in a pennant race and won three in a five-game
series. Starting Tuesday, the Angels play three at Yankee Stadium
before returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went in last year when everybody thought the (stuff) was
going to hit the fan and we played great,'' Collins said. ``So
maybe it's the extra challenge that we need. One thing about the
Yankees, they face challenges every day because everybody wants to
beat them. It's something to get up for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have today off. on Tuesday, Steve Sparks (1-3, 4.29
ERA) will start for Anaheim against New York's Andy Pettitte (1-1,
4.88).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
