</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS SHOOT DOWN METS AS REED FALTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Only once over their first 31 games has a New York
Mets starter lasted more than seven innings. And Sunday, Rick Reed
did not even make it out of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who has been the Mets' most consistent starter over the
last three years, lasted just 1 2/3 innings in an 11-6 loss to the
Arizona Diamondbacks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed a career-high eight earned runs on seven hits. And
even though the Mets (18-13) pounded out a season-high 16 hits,
they were no match for the Diamondbacks, who took a 9-0 lead after
two innings en route to capturing two of three games in this
weekend series.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be successful, you have to be consistent,'' said
Reed (2-1), whose earned run average more than doubled from 3.60
before the game to 7.56. ``It's not a matter of taking pride in it.
If you're consistent, you'll stick around a long time. That's why I
want to forget about today _ as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won only one of their last five games. In just
three games here, the pitching staff's earned run average rose from
3.69 to 4.24 as the Diamondbacks, in their second season, tied a
franchise record by scoring 27 runs over a three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Mets off to Denver for three games at Coors Field,
the most hitter-friendly park in the National League, there is no
respite in sight for the pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Only Al Leiter, who will start against the Rockies on Monday
night, has lasted more than seven innings, having gone 7 2/3
innings in a 6-4 loss to Montreal on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Reed had left a game this early without being hurt
was on Aug. 16, 1989, when he was with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was probably the best I felt all year, believe it or
not,'' said Reed, who seemed to still be having trouble believing
it after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stunk. I just got my pitches up,'' he said. ``When I warmed
up in the bullpen, I felt fine. I was good. But just when I got
between the lines, where it counted, I just didn't get it done.
That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   It took only nine pitches for Reed to fall behind, 3-0. Tony
Womack led off by singling off the mound on a 1--2-pitch. Jay Bell
lashed a 2-1 offering over the fence in left center on a hop for a
ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   And then Luis Gonzalez jumped all over a first-pitch cut
fastball _ one that Mike Piazza said had no bite on it _ for a
413-foot home run inside the right-field foul pole. That extended
his major league best hitting streak to 22 games and gave the
Diamondbacks the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Reed retired the next three batters in succession, but his
troubles started up again in the second. By the time manager Bobby
Valentine sent pitching coach Bob Apodaca out to get Reed, the
Diamondbacks had added on three more runs. And after Steve Finley
greeted the reliever Josias Manzanillo with a three-run homer to
right, the book was closed on Reed, and the Mets were trailing by
nine runs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Valentine fielded a lineup with just four starters
in their regular positions, the Mets hammered away at Arizona's
suspect pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Allensworth had three hits, including his first homer
of the season. Piazza went 3 for 4, with his fourth home run, in
his first multiple-hit game since coming off the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo, Todd Pratt and Rey Ordonez each had two hits.
And Mike Kinkade belted his second home run.
</P>
<P>
   But the offense was in too big a hole, and hitting into four
double plays and going 1 for 9 with runners in scoring position did
not help.
</P>
<P>
   The only intriguing element after the second inning came when
the Mets scored three times in the ninth inning and Valentine sent
John Olerud to bat as a pinch-hitter with no one on and two out.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud had a streak of reaching base by either a hit or a walk
in the team's first 30 games _ 47 games dating back to last season.
But Valentine didn't have any pinch-hitters left and Olerud ended
the streak by striking out out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you want me to do, send up the pitcher and the white
flag?'' said Valentine. ``I don't do that. No one knows what the
record is? Then I guess it doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud said he felt the same way. ``I think a hitting streak
would be a little different than this thing,'' he said. Valentine
concurred, saying he would not have sent Olerud up had it been a
hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Watson, a relief pitcher whom Olerud hit for, had been 3
for 8 this season. His career batting average: .260. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
