<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-09 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES MISSED THE CHANCE FOR ANOTHER POSITIVE
DEED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the inside, where Joe Torre recovers gallantly
and another game comes daily, it seems perfectly natural for Don
Zimmer to be limping along as an interim, martyred manager. He
promised Torre he would be a good soldier, a G.I. Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any question,'' Chris Chambliss said. ``Given
Zim's experience, and being that he's close to Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, there is another view of how the Yankees have
managed Torre's forced absence. The choice of Zimmer to be the
temporary replacement in his crimped and cranky condition should
raise a question that is disturbingly decades old: to what lengths
will a professional sports team go before it turns to a minority
aspirant, if only to fill in? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this particular case, George Steinbrenner responded to
Torre's spring training diagnosis of prostate cancer by calling his
68-year-old bench coach out of his imminent retirement.
Steinbrenner needlessly played on Zimmer's admirable loyalties to
Torre when he might have appointed one of two African-American
coaches with deep organizational roots and high managerial hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss, who has managing experience, and Willie Randolph, who
does not, would have leaped at the chance. Out of loyalty to the
team and personal pride, they knew better than to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't asked to do it and it wasn't my place to stand up and
say, `I want to manage,''' said Chambliss, the batting coach, a
30-year veteran of professional baseball, a minor league manager on
three levels and manager of the year on two of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sports owners often contend that minority candidates do not
promote themselves, or network enough. Though few owners hire
proactively, many speak sympathetically. Some are less enlightened,
even crude. John McMullen, the Devils' owner, recently contended in
a published report that, based on his experience owning the Houston
Astros, minorities didn't want jobs that would pay less than
``these people'' made as players.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the attitude and agenda, the ladder somehow keeps
growing when a minority candidate reaches the next-to-last rung.
When the Mets sidelined their general manager, Steve Phillips, over
sexual allegations last winter, it was as if his assistant, Omar
Minaya, did not exist. Rather than have a man with working
knowledge of Phillips' blueprint take over, they dusted off an
organizational dinosaur, Frank Cashen. They explained this as a
common corporate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure if you took a survey of major league teams asking why
this happens, you would get all kinds of different answers,''
Chambliss said.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much for a member of a minority to start sliding
back down the managerial ladder, his team's or others' who might
have considered him. Chambliss, in the winter previous to last,
interviewed for several major league jobs. He still wishes to
manage, and wants this known. But what does it say to other teams
about Chambliss the prospect that the Yankees picked as Torre's
temp a man with a bum right knee, who is wincing through the
early-season schedule as bone meets bone the way ball meets bat?
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, supposedly the sensible choice for a smooth transition,
has himself been a distraction. Even Torre told him to go home from
Texas last weekend, when Zimmer suddenly announced he was suffering
too much and was going to quit. Why didn't Steinbrenner just thank
Zimmer for his effort, and tell Chambliss or Randolph, his
third-base coach, to start pressing the buttons for his 125-victory
defending champs until Torre returns later this month?
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers pride themselves on being contrary, but the Zimmer
Chronicles have somehow played out without a second guess. Have we
all become so anesthetized by old-school inequity that logical
alternatives don't cross our minds?
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Steinbrenner, with Torre, ignored Zimmer's
disability and cited his 13 years as a major league manager.
Similar experience didn't seem to be a prerequisite when he hired
Buck Showalter, or Bucky Dent. It is the same old story everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years, until Dave Cowens walked out on the Charlotte
Hornets this season, Paul Silas sat around as an assistant coach
and watched former players like Paul Westphal and Danny Ainge and
career assistants like Jeff Van Gundy climb right on by. Minorities
lack experience and therefore leadership credentials. On the other
hand, Tim Johnson, a white manager who wrote creative fiction on
his personal resume, wasn't canned by Toronto until this spring
when he became an international joke.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Chambliss and Randolph are not complaining about
anything, not even baseball's minority record. ``You have to be
patient,'' Randolph said. ``If you keep asking, `When am I going to
get a shot,' you start to sound a little bitter, like Davey Lopes.
I love the game too much for that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are worse things, Chambliss said, than working with the
best team in baseball, for a class act like Torre. There is no
point in dwelling on issues beyond your control, and no time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you feel Zim's not even hurt,'' Randolph said. ``But
once in a while, he gets up and goes, `Yaaah!'''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer shrugs off the pain the way the players deal with
distraction. Steinbrenner. Strawberry. Irabu. Clemens. Torre.
Zimmer. The Yankees, after beating Seattle, 6-1, Sunday roll along,
in first place. They would have been there under another interim
manager, who would have spared Zimmer this ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same, same,'' he said, fiddling with his brace, when asked the
other night how his chronic knee felt.
</P>
<P>
   Some old wounds just don't heal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
