<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR LEDEE, ANOTHER LOW MOMENT IN A CAREER FULL OF
HIGH PROMISE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the way out to batting practice Sunday morning,
Ricky Ledee, two bats under his arm and and a glove in his hand,
stopped at the Yankees' clubhouse door to look at the lineup card
that had been posted shortly before. The lineup, for the game that
afternoon against Seattle, began: ``Curtis 7, Jeter 6, O'Neill 9,''
meaning, using scorekeeping shorthand, Chad Curtis leading off and
playing left field _ Ledee's position _ followed by Derek Jeter,
shortstop, and Paul O'Neill, right field.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth straight game, Ledee, the slender rookie who the
interim manager Don Zimmer had said was ``one of the hottest
prospects in our organization,'' was not in the starting lineup.
Ledee did not linger. One imagined that his heart sank a little
bit, again.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, who is batting just .200 in his 16 games played this
season, knew he was facing a possible demotion to the Columbus farm
team. While Ledee has suffered numerous disappointments in his
young baseball life _ at 25 he has spent nine seasons in the minor
leagues _ it was dispiriting to face the possibility of another.
Especially after the World Series he enjoyed last October.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not spreading the blame. ``I've been given a big
opportunity to play this season,'' Ledee said before the game,
``and I haven't produced.'' He has struck out 15 times in 45
at-bats. After he did get a 10th-inning pinch-hit single that won
the game against Kansas City last Thursday, he was asked how he
felt at the plate when the count went to no balls and two strikes.
``I thought to myself, `Here we go again,' '' he admitted. It was
hardly the confession of a confident hitter.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way from his extraordinary play in the World Series
last October, when he batted .600, with 6 hits in 10 at-bats. He
had come up from Class AAA Columbus the month before and played
well enough to start Game 1 of the Series against San Diego.
Ledee's first at-bat came with the bases loaded. He faced Kevin
Brown, perhaps the best pitcher in baseball last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of situation,'' Ledee said, ``that you dream
about as a kid, as a minor leaguer _ World Series, bases loaded.''
He ripped a double, scoring two runs. How did he feel standing on
second base? ``I wanted to scream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had been signed by the Yankees out of Puerto Rico when he was
16 years old. He had hoped finally that ``the bus rides'' _ his
metaphor for the entire minor league experience _ were just a dusty
memory. It appeared to be one of those wonderful sports stories, a
Cinderella-in-spiked-shoes kind of tale.
</P>
<P>
   But then opposing teams began to study the young man. He was a
good fastball hitter, so let's try breaking stuff, off-speed stuff.
Soon he ran into problems. In spring training, he hit just .167.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been patient enough at the plate,'' Ledee said.
``I've been going after pitches out of the strike zone big time.
Too anxious. That's been killing me. And I'm hard on myself. Yeah,
my confidence level is way down.'' Zimmer, who has spent a
half-century in baseball, had spoken to him gently, telling him to
relax. The concept is easier than the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first time a young ballplayer has run into
difficulty,'' said Paul O'Neill, who was up and down to the minor
leagues three times before sticking as a major leaguer with
Cincinnati. ``And then it becomes a head game. You begin putting
pressure on yourself. It beats you down. Ricky will come out of it.
He's too good a ballplayer not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee said that sometimes he ``thinks too much'' at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to guess what the pitcher is going to throw, and I wind
up striking out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hitting problems may have affected Ledee's play in left
field as well. He has appeared tentative, even to the extent of
playing a single down the line by Kansas City's plodding catcher,
Chad Kreuter, into a two-base blow.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's 6-1 Yankee victory, Ledee was told that Zim
wanted to see him in his office. Zimmer knows how hard Ledee has
tried, regularly coming early to the ball park to work on the parts
of his game. Zimmer knows Ledee's long struggle to get to the major
leagues. Like the rest of the team, Zimmer has a fondness for
Ledee. He broke the news to Ricky Ledee that he was sending him
back to Columbus. I'm sorry, Zimmer told Ledee, but he'd get a
chance to play more there, to get his game together again, he
hoped, to make it back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you send someone down,'' Zimmer said later, ``you're
always half sick to your stomach. Especially a great kid like
Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee offered no argument. He left and quietly began to clear
out his locker. Outfielder Shane Spencer, recalled from Columbus
and with hopes bright, will move into Ledee's vacated premises.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Ledee recalled a dream he had when he was 16 and
having problems in the Rookie League in Tampa, Fla. It had to do
with his father, Antonio, who was killed in an automobile accident
when Ricky was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the dream I was running the bases,'' he said, ``and I was
feeling so tired rounding second that I didn't think I could make
it to third. But I heard the third-base coach yelling: `Don't give
up! Don't give up!' I looked and saw that the third-base coach was
my father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always remember that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
