<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-09 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS ARE WINNING DESPITE VAN GUNDY, OR BECAUSE OF
HIM?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Reporters swarmed around Patrick Ewing Sunday as the
Knicks ended their practice at the Miami Arena. Did he think the
Heat had an answer for the new look the Knicks had shown on
Saturday, with its emphasis on speed and quickness? Ewing didn't
have much to add to what everyone saw in the 20-point rout that
gave the Knicks a 1-0 lead in their first-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only time will tell,'' Ewing said. ``They're a good team,
also. We mirror each other. They're going to come out with a lot of
intensity. We just have to match it and come with a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing ended his impromptu news conference when a reporter asked
if he felt more inclined to play defense now that the Knicks had
increased their offensive arsenal. Ewing eyed the questioner and
smiled. ``You sound like you're from New York with that comment,''
he said, and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Now the reporters swarmed around Coach Jeff Van Gundy, peppering
him with questions about the fluid, more open offense the Knicks
have shown since the last few weeks of the regular season. Van
Gundy played down the 95-75 victory on Saturday, and especially
brushed away inferences that the team had become more
offense-minded, more transition-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't run,'' he said. ``I mean, it's a misnomer that we
were in transition a lot yesterday. I think they had 14 fast breaks
and we had 16.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won, in Van Gundy's view, because the Heat missed a
lot of open shots, not because New York was better in transition.
``They were wide open, and they just had the misfortune to miss,''
he said. ``I wish we had something more to do with that, but we
didn't have as much to do with that as I thought we did during the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone observed that when Ewing was on the bench, the offense
seemed to be more successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``More successful?'' Van Gundy asked incredulously. ``I
disagree, but again, that's a perception.'' The questioner
persisted: when Ewing is not in the game, the Knicks seem to run up
and down the court more.
</P>
<P>
   ``False,'' Van Gundy said. ``False. Absolutely false. He's our
best rebounder. On the 16 fast breaks we got, he ignited over half
of them with his rebounding and shot blocking. So when he's on the
court, we have a better chance to run.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just another day in the life of the intriguing Knicks, a
team left for dead a month ago but now established as a team to
chase. In the midst of a satisfying transformation that has seen
the Knicks jell, Van Gundy faces a juggling act.
</P>
<P>
   He is trying to keep his job as head coach, while playing out a
political drama that resulted in his rival, Ernie Grunfeld, losing
his job as the team's president last month. Grunfeld _ with the
blessing of Dave Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden
_ acquired Marcus Camby and Latrell Sprewell in trades that sent
the core of Van Gundy's team elsewhere. Van Gundy initially had to
be coaxed to play the newcomers; he disparaged Camby's work ethic
and made Sprewell a sixth man. Now the Knicks are winning precisely
because of the two new players, the related new-found
aggressiveness of Allan Houston and the adaptation of Ewing to a
role as a rebounder, shot blocker and scorer when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy still sees the Knicks as a halfcourt team, and they
can certainly play that way in spots. But a bruising halfcourt game
no longer presents the Knicks with their best chance of winning.
``I think we can play both styles,'' Camby said Sunday. ``We're
versatile. We can post up; we can also get out on the break and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   This Knick team, with all the chaos of the last month, has
become a lot like the city it represents, a melange of attitudes
and agendas with politics always being played out, sometimes
harshly, at a number of levels. Yet on the court the attitudes and
agendas have somehow begun to coalesce in a winning unit. The
question Knicks executives have to answer is: Are the Knicks
winning because of Van Gundy's willingness to adjust, or despite
his resistance to change?
</P>
<P>
   With Grunfeld out of view, Knicks fans are getting their first
clear view of Jeff Van Gundy. No longer the sympathetic underdog,
as he was portrayed during his first two seasons as head coach, Van
Gundy has shown himself to be smart, politically savvy,
manipulative and even combative. Last year he grabbed Alonzo
Mourning's leg during a playoff brawl; he sniped at Michael Jordan
and Phil Jackson. This year he criticized Camby to justify
minimizing his playing time. Last week, in a bizarre small-town
move, Van Gundy ordered the Garden's out-of-town scoreboard turned
off so that players and fans wouldn't be distracted by the
Pistons-76ers score.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Van Gundy has taken the Knicks to the playoffs
and a rousing opening victory.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely the only way he can insure his return as the Knicks'
head coach is to take the team to the Eastern Conference finals.
The only way to do that is to give Camby, Sprewell and Houston
greater latitude as the playoffs progress. The team is looking good
and sounding happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing together more,'' Camby said. ``The ball's being
swung around; we don't have any egos; everyone wants to share the
spotlight. When different guys are scoring and passing like that,
it makes the game fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
