u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      05-09 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA REPORTS PROGRESS ON DIPLOMATIC FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO claimed military successes and Russia heralded
a diplomatic advance Sunday, as efforts to end the conflict in
Kosovo continued, shaken but not scuttled by the NATO bombing
Friday night of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Still apologizing for the bombing, which they called a ``tragic
error,'' NATO officials said the alliance flew 500 sorties Saturday
night, with an airfield and military assembly area in Kosovo among
the targets.
</P>
<P>
   However, news reports said that NATO warplanes generally avoided
Yugoslavia's larger cities. In addition to killing at least three
journalists in the Chinese Embassy, NATO warplanes reportedly
killed 15 with errant bombs in Nis, Yugoslavia's third-largest
city.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said their operations had been hampered by
weather and did not say they were intentionally avoiding cities.
</P>
<P>
   In Bonn, Russia's Balkans envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, emerged
from meetings with German leaders Sunday and declared that hopeful
``new circumstances'' had arisen regarding a peace plan backed by
Russia and the seven major industrialized nations. That plan calls
broadly for an international peacekeeping force in Kosovo, but
diplomats are still negotiating the details.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin would not describe the ``new circumstances'' but
told reporters that he had presented them by phone to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, who reacted positively. ``Well, he
took them very well,'' the former Russian prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Mike Hammer, a spokesman for the National
Security Council, said the ``new circumstances'' may involve
Russia's position on some elements of the peace plan, such as the
composition of the international military force that would take
positions in Kosovo to keep the peace when refugees return, or the
timetable for the withdrawl of Milosevic's troops.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin had been expected to fly to Yugoslavia from
Germany, but he returned to Moscow to discuss events with Russian
leaders and possibly later this week with US Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott, who will make his second trip to Moscow in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent a letter of regret to Chinese President
Jiang Zemin, saying that the embassy in Belgrade was not struck
intentionally. He also asked the Chinese leader to continue to
provide security for US diplomats in China, who have been besieged
by angry crowds rallying at US embassies, smashing windows and
damaging cars.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has said that it targeted the embassy, thinking that the
building housed a Serb weapons depot. Sunday, US officials told
reporters that the Central Intelligence Agency initially picked the
building as a target, thinking it was the Yugoslav Federal
Directorate of Supply and Procurement. But subsequent reviews by
other military bodies did not discover that the building actually
housed the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ws no pilot or crew error,'' General Wesley Clark,
NATO's supreme allied commander, said on the ABC program ``This
Week.'' ``It was a case of the selection of the target and the
process that was involved there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at that process, we've got confidence in it, we
think this was an anomaly and we're going to continue to intensify
this air campaign. We're not going to let an incident like this
deter us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is the southern province of Yugoslavia, but an armed
independence movement of ethnic Albanians is pushing to redraw the
political map. Western leaders say Milosevic, a Serb, has used the
independence movement as an excuse to slaughter ethnic Albanians
and to drive more than 700,000 from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   -- Chinese officials arrived in Belgrade to arrange for the
return of the bodies of victims from the embassy bombing. The
Chinese Foreign Ministry said that the dead included a recently
married couple. More than 20 people were said to be injured.
</P>
<P>
   -- President Clinton spoke with French President Jacques Chirac
for about 40 minutes about Kosovo and the embassy bombing. ``Chirac
shares our view that things like this will occur,'' said Hammer,
the National Security Council spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   -- Two of Milosevic's political opponents asked the
international community not to sign any deal that would leave him
in power. The president of the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro,
Milo Djukanovic, joined with Zoran Djindjic, leader of the Serbian
opposition Democratic Party, to issue the appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
