<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEFTY-RELIEVERS-2     05-09 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEFTY-RELIEVERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP WANTED: LEFTY RELIEVERS, PREVIOUS EXPERIENCE UNIMPORTANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was after midnight after a game two weeks ago, and
Tony Fossas was munching on a TV dinner and watching sports
highlight shows in his hotel room in Columbus, Ohio, when a
reporter called. Even though the scene sounded drab, Fossas spoke
excitedly about pitching for the Yankees' Class AAA affiliate and
spoke hopefully about resuming his major league career.
</P>
<P>
   Ten hours after Fossas hung up the telephone, he was called up
by the Yankees. No one was surprised. No one should be. Fossas is a
left-handed relief pitcher and, although he is 41 years old, rarely
throws a pitch that exceeds 86 mph, and has been with seven major
and minor league teams in the last two years, is a precious
commodity in a game where lefty relievers are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do understand that if I wasn't left-handed, I wouldn't be
here,'' Fossas said. ``I understand that fully. There's no doubt
about it. There's not that many of us.''
</P>
<P>
   One day after Fossas was summoned, he gave up four runs in
one-third of an inning. There was immediate speculation that he
might be demoted or released. Once again, no one would have been
surprised. The job of a lefty reliever can be unpredictable and, if
he does not retire left-handed batters consistently, it can end
abruptly. That is, until the next team with a void in the bullpen
takes a chance. And someone will.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get the opportunity to extend their baseball life more
than anyone else,'' said John Schuerholz, the general manager of
the Atlanta Braves. ``They're hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossas and his brethren have heard all of the hackneyed jokes
about how easy it is for left-handers to make it to the major
leagues. If you are left-handed and can stand up straight, breathe
and throw strikes, someone will eventually give you a chance to
pitch in the major leagues. While that is obviously an
exaggeration, it is true that lefties get many more opportunities
than righties.
</P>
<P>
   Fossas has been released by three organizations in the last
year, and his name has become synonymous with nomadic reliever: Has
left arm, has held lefties to a .240 average over the last five
years and will travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a left-hander does get released, someone like Fossas, you
know he's going to get picked up,'' said the Mets' John Franco, who
has saved more games than any lefty in history. ``Before you know
it, he's released and then you're watching some game on TV and here
comes Tony Fossas. You say, `How the heck did he get there?'''
</P>
<P>
   Why are lefties so precious? Mostly because they are so
difficult to find. Studies have shown that while 5 to 30 percent of
the world's population has some left-handed skills, roughly 13
percent can be considered lefties. Yet 30 percent of the pitchers
on opening day rosters this season were lefty, and general managers
work overtime to raise that percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard stories from my grandparents and my parents that
picking up a fork left-handed was the wrong way of doing it,'' said
Doug Melvin, the general manager of the Texas Rangers. ``Now, if
you pick up a baseball left-handed, that's the right way to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What else makes lefties so precious? Batters swear that their
pitches break differently than those of right-handers, and come
from different arm angles, making it tougher for left-handed
batters to even pick up the ball. In addition, lefty relievers are
more of a mystery because they usually have a trick pitch or a
deceptive motion, and hitters are more accustomed to righties.
Finally, some hitters even mentioned that the lack of quality
left-handed batting practice pitchers can be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams, the Yankees and the Toronto Blue Jays, take
their lefty batting-practice pitcher on every road trip. For the
roughly $20,000 that it costs, it seems like a terrific investment.
Still, Charlie Wonsowicz, who has been the lefty for the Yankees
for seven years, doubted that every team could find a lefty to toss
strikes daily, keep quiet and blend in with a team. Indeed, the
Yankees once dismissed a nuisance of a lefty because he kept
plunking Don Mattingly in batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was an abundance out there, more guys would be doing
it,'' Wonsowicz said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, like most general managers, is familiar with the
problem. As he sat in his office at Yankee Stadium, staring at
boards that listed all of the players in the organization, he
lamented that the Yankees have only 21 lefties among their 128
pitchers. After the Yankees grudgingly included Graeme Lloyd in the
Roger Clemens-David Wells trade with Toronto, Cashman was so eager
to fill the left-handed void that he signed Trevor Wilson, a
32-year-old who missed all of 1996 and 1997 with injuries and who
tossed seven and two-thirds innings in the majors in 1998. Then he
nabbed Fossas the day after the Rangers released him in March.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said the Yankees had been scrambling to replace him, and
Cashman acknowledged that the team will spend 162 games, if needed,
looking for a second lefty reliever to complement Mike Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lefties are very valuable,'' Cashman said. ``If you can get
your hands on a lefty, you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefties know that, so they plod along, and general managers
toil, sometimes obsessively, to obtain them. Melvin so coveted a
left-hander once that he signed Scott Bailes, who had not pitched
in the majors for two years; he also signed Ed Vosberg, who had
pitched in Italy two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets happily gave Dennis Cook, a left-hander in his 12th
season who was released by the White Sox in 1994, a three-year,
$6.6 million contract because he had become one of the most
versatile pitchers in baseball. Cook, 36, who has 15-month-old
triplets, said he might even play for the minimum after his
contract expired if someone still wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Orosco, who is 42 and could eclipse the record for career
appearances this season, is signed through 2000. His agent and wife
have told him he should pitch until he is 50. Lloyd, 32, thinks he
could easily last another decade while the Indians hope 38-year-old
Paul Assenmacher does not retire. And Fossas? The pitcher who spent
11 years in the minors before emerging as a specialist and who has
never made more than $750,000 in a season is determined to keep
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how many coaches told me I'd never make it?'' Fossas
asked. ``Every one.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Teams usually try to cling to the dependable lefty relievers,
specialists like Orosco, Assenmacher, Cook and Milwaukee's Mike
Myers. There are only two lefties who are full-time closers, Franco
and Houston's Billy Wagner, and few lefties are long relievers.
Eddie Guardado pitches so frequently for Minnesota that his
nickname is Every Day. Many lefty relievers are asked to get a few
outs, usually against lefties, and get out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad job,'' Melvin said. ``You might pitch 40
innings and face 40 batters. It's not a bad job if you can get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lloyd, who pitched precisely 39 innings in the regular
season and postseason for the Yankees in 1998, held left-handed
batters to a .198 average and, more impressive, righties to a .182
mark, admitted that he ached to do more. In Toronto, Lloyd's role
has expanded beyond facing only lefties.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Yankees wanted me to do was get one lefty at a time,''
Lloyd sighed. ``But complaining would have been pretty silly. The
team won every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco jogs 10 miles a day three or four times a week in the
off-season to make sure he has strong legs to go with a strong
stomach. While Orosco said he could still pitch in 100 games a year
if he had to go only an inning each time, he expects to retire his
nasty slider by the time he is 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like teams feel sorry for us,'' Orosco said. ``You
hear people say, `If you're left-handed, you can get a job.' You
still have to earn it. They don't just give it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco earns it. Before Paul O'Neill homered off him last month,
O'Neill was 0 for 16 off Orosco in his career. Just mention Orosco,
Assenmacher (3 for 24) or Lloyd (2 for 11) and watch O'Neill, a
former batting champion, wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys might get one or two outs, but those are the one or
two outs that change the outcome of a game,'' O'Neill said. ``If
they can get left-handers out, they're going to have a job for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time O'Neill grinned during the discussion about his
adversaries was when he mentioned that his 9-year-old, Andy, was a
southpaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws left-handed,'' O'Neill said. ``So he can get me out,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Vosberg, who is now with San Diego and who has been in 10
organizations in a 16-year career, said that being a lefty did not
help him while he languished in the minors for 11 years. Still, the
37-year-old Vosberg was blunt about the lunacy surrounding lefties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a shortage in quality rather than quantity,''
he said. ``A lot of times left-handers can't throw the ball over
the plate. I don't care if you throw 100 miles an hour, you have to
throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman believes Fossas can still do that, so Fossas survives on
perhaps the finest team in the majors. All lefty relievers spoke
reverentially about Fossas and lauded his resilience. But, deep
down, they probably realized that they could be the next Fossas,
too. To Fossas, still speaking like a giddy teen-ager at the prom,
it is an enviable existence. It is the life of a lefty reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be in Cuba,'' said Fossas, whose family left Havana
when he was 13 years old. ``Look at Kosovo. Look at Colorado. I
don't wait for situations like that to happen to get perspective. I
have perspective every day. I'm still in the same la-la baseball
world. If I don't pitch another day in the big leagues, I'm still
the happiest man on Earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
