r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     05-09 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV MOVIE CHRONICLES ORIGINAL ROCKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Filmmaker Irwin Winkler was a driving force behind ``Rocky,''
the fictional
</P>
<P>
   rags-to-riches story of Rocky Balboa that captured the world's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler's son, director Charles Winkler, now gives us the long
overdue story of the (begin ital)real(end ital) Rocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocky Marciano,'' a made-for-television film that premieres
Saturday on Showtime, chronicles the life of one of the sport's
greatest champions _ the only heavyweight titleholder to retire
undefeated _ who was killed in a plane crash in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa and Marciano have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   They started from little _ Marciano was the son of a shoemaker
in Brockton, Mass. _ but ultimately became heroes. They fought more
like Mike Tyson than Muhammad Ali. And, of course, they were both
Italian-American.
</P>
<P>
   However, the similarities don't go much further.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler's film, starring Jon Favreau as Marciano, is not the
feel-good fairytale the Academy Award-winning movie is.
</P>
<P>
   It is a realistic, relatively subtle depiction of a complex man
_ for example, he was notoriously cheap overall, but extremely
generous with his money to those he loved _ and a savage fighter,
and how he became that way.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Marciano the man is particularly gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   Casual sports fans might know the basics of his life and career:
his unique 49-0 record, the fact he was the last great white
heavyweight champion and his untimely death.
</P>
<P>
   However, few know much about the man. Winkler strays from the
facts in many cases but brings the essence of Marciano to life in a
compelling way that gives perspective to his boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   One scene depicts the humiliation his father (played by George
C. Scott) experiences when he's forced to use food stamps, which
seems to explain Marciano's high regard for money and his
tremendous hunger in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   His reverence for his boyhood hero, Joe Louis, reveals both his
sensitivity and unshakable dedication to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano is devastated when he learns he must fight the great
``Brown Bomber,'' proceeds to beat him mercilessly and then again
is heartbroken afterward. Meanwhile, a simple approving nod by
Louis immediately after the bout is stopped symbolizes Marciano's
coming of age as a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Books and articles about Marciano) talk about how Rocky wept
in Louis' locker room after he beat him. Once I found that, I had
my in for the story. It struck me as totally fascinating,'' Winkler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler worked with his father on many films, including
``Rocky'' and ``Raging Bull,'' probably the greatest boxing film
ever made.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears he learned his lessons: The boxing scenes in
(begin ital)his(end ital) movie are excellent. He and boxing
choreographer Jimmy Nickerson (``Rocky,'' ``Rocky 2'' and ``Raging
Bull'') capture Marciano's machine-like determination and
destructive power in a realistic manner.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly riveting and representative of the damage Marciano
could inflict is his bloody bout with Carmine Vingo, who is nearly
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Vingo goes down and winds up in the hospital, you
understand how it happened,'' Winkler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the boxing was shot in the `Rocky' movies,
particularly the later ones, was incredible. Stallone, at that
point, had the method down to a science. In watching all five of
the movies, we really saw how it got slicker and more effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, with `Raging Bull,' I remember seeing
(director) Martin Scorsese spending hours and hours setting one
shot up. He really created art with the camera. We had that to look
at, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Favreau, who wrote and starred in the popular film ``Swingers,''
desperately wanted this part.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, is of Italian heritage _ ``It was a chance to make the
Italian relatives proud'' _ and, he said, every actor relishes the
chance to play a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   He trained for six months, learning the rudiments of boxing and
Marciano's awkward style from Nickerson in Joe Goossen's Van Nuys
gym and building a physique that rivals Stallone's.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he poured over all the material he could find
on Marciano. He was determined to do the legend justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to young people, they say, `Oh, you're re-making
the Stallone movie?''' he said. ``They don't know much about him.
He was one of the first positive Italian role models. He wasn't
associated with the Mafia. He had integrity in a sport that is so
corrupt. All this after starting out as the son of immigrants in a
depressed situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``By his own will, skill and perseverance, he became the only
undefeated champion the world has ever known. It's an inspiring
story that no one has done until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy: Winkler's film has angered Marciano's relatives,
who say he was not connected to the mob and was not desperate to
leave Brockton as the movie indicates.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, organized crime figure Frankie Carbo has invested
in Marciano's career but the fighter never does anything dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to sit and watch and see things, and you'd say,
`That's a lie, that's not factual,' '' Rocky Marciano Jr. told the
Enterprise in Brockton.
</P>
<P>
   Said Peter Marciano, the fighter's brother: ``Speaking on behalf
of the family, we don't want the people of Brockton to think the
Marciano family in any shape or form had anything to do with this
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Winkler defended any inaccuracies in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic problem is taking a man's life story and boiling it
down to 100 minutes,'' he said. ``You have to combine things to try
to illuminate broader themes in the man's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to do this with no disrespect to Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver lining?: It might turn out that the Evander
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis debacle was the best thing that could've
happened to boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the atrocious scoring of the fight has fed
a movement to reform the sport that is picking up momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Muhammad Ali Reform Act, a bill to protect boxers from
exploitation by promoters and managers and require accountability
from sanctioning bodies, was approved last week by the Senate's
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill was passed by the full Senate last year, but the
House never took up the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the (Holyfield-Lewis) fight will provide some
additional pressure,'' committee chairman John McCain, R-Ariz.,
told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, authorities in New York, where the Holyfield-Lewis
draw took place, have established strict criteria by which to
select and monitor judges.
</P>
<P>
   Similar changes are likely to be made across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas watch: Fernando Vargas of Oxnard will defend his IBF
junior middleweight title against 1992 Olympian Raul Marquez on
July 17 at Lake Tahoe on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Vargas' second defense. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990509.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-BUS-CRASH-590&AMP;ADD-     05-09 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-BUS-CRASH-590&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUS CRASH KILLS 23 ON WAY TO CASINO; MANY WERE ELDERLY ON MOTHER'S
DAY OUTING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, Miss., N.J.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A charter bus carrying at least 46 people from a New Orleans
suburb to a Mississippi casino resort, many of them older women on
a Mother's Day trip, veered across a busy interstate highway and
into an embankment Sunday, killing 23 people and injuring 20.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident was not immediately known, but the bus
driver, who was critically hurt, was quoted by the bus company
operator and a hospital official as saying that he had swerved when
another vehicle suddenly passed in front of him. The front of the
bus was mangled, its tires twisted and pushed into the passenger
compartment.
</P>
<P>
   The police do not yet know how fast the bus was traveling.
</P>
<P>
   The bus accident was one of the worst in the nation's history,
according to National Transportation and Safety Board records. The
accident with the largest loss of life was in 1976 when a school
bus crashed in Yuba City, Calif., killing 53.
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred about 10 a.m. as the bus was on its way to
the Casino Magic casino in Bay St. Louis, Miss., just across the
Louisiana line on the Gulf Coast. The bus had started out in
LaPlace, La., about 25 miles west of New Orleans, and was headed
east on Interstate 610 for the 90-mile trip.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the bus veered across three lanes of
traffic, narrowly missing several vehicles. It hit the edge of a
guardrail and veered onto a tree-lined grassy area. It continued to
careen alongside the highway for about 50 yards, crashing through a
chain-link fence and then over a gully and into an embankment, a
police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen people were pronounced dead at the scene and four died
at hospitals, the authorities said. The bodies could not be removed
for four hours after the crash because of the extensive damage to
the front of the bus, which was so crumpled that its front wheels
were two feet off the ground. Rescue squads had to brace the bus
with timbers and use ladders to reach its windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people on top of each other, crushed between twisted
metal,'' Officer Joe Narcisse of the New Orleans Police told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen people were hospitalized and three were released after
emergency room treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The bus was operated by Custom Bus Charters, based in Gretna,
La. Terrell Walker, a spokesman for Custom Bus, identified the
driver as Frank Bedell, 49. Walker and Jerry Romig, a spokesman for
Charity Hospital, where the most-critically injured were taken,
said on CNN that the driver told investigators that he had swerved
to the right when another vehicle cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said that Bedell had worked for the company for three
years and had no record of problems. Walker also told the network
that the bus had new brakes and no record of recent mechanical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Marc Morial said the New Orleans Police Department is
working with the NTSB to investigate the crash. He said the driver
would be tested for drugs and alcohol use, as is customary.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said that 46 people were on the bus, but that the list of
passengers was lost in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Romig said the hospital had opened four trauma operating rooms
and was calling in every available doctor and nurse. He said that
the crash was the worst he had seen in 20 years and that the
outlook for many of the injured was poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some very badly injured people, and the fact that
they're elderly doesn't help at all,'' he said. ``Some were in
their 70s, some in their 80's, and that makes it doubly tough. It
makes it more difficult for them to sustain trauma, especially
chest injuries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Four other gambling charter buses, bound for casinos in Atlantic
City, crashed in New Jersey in late December and early January. The
most serious Atlantic City crash occurred on Christmas Eve, killing
eight people.
</P>
<P>
   As in Atlantic City, which does not have a large enough local
population to support its gambling industry, the casinos along the
Gulf Coast often provide inexpensive package tours, meals or other
incentives to attract customers from hours away, often from
surrounding states. Many of these customers, most of them elderly,
visit only for the day.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, it is a common practice for casinos to pay bus
companies to organize excursions for the elderly, although it was
not immediately known whether Custom Bus had such an arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the passengers on the bus Sunday were members of an
informal club that went to the casino twice a month, George Tassin,
a relative of eight of the passengers, told The Associated Press.
Tassin's wife, daughter and an aunt were among the injured, he
said, as he waited outside the hospital where they were taken.
</P>
<P>
   He said his aunt was making her first trip since the recent
death of her husband. ``My aunt finally decided to go this one time
and this happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the crash site near the St. Bernard intersection several
miles from the French Quarter, bus seats lay on the roadway along
with broken glass and torn clothing. As traffic slowed alongside
Interstate 610, one elderly couple, Gloria and Wayne Bachemin, said
they had taken that charter trip before and had considered taking
the trip to Casino Magic that morning but had a family obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Bachemin worried that one of her friends might have been
a passenger Sunday. ``She was organizing a trip for this weekend,''
Mrs. Bachemin said. ``I just hope it was another bus. She's a
jovial person; she would have been sitting right up front, trying
to get people to sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Four more people had been waiting to board the bus in New
Orleans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
