<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUNDERSON ON DISABLED LIST
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Rangers reinstated right-hander John Burkett from
the 15-day disabled list yesterday, but avoided a difficult
decision by placing left-hander Eric Gunderson on the 15-day
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   That kept the Rangers from exposing Gunderson to outright
waivers by designating him for assignment and from optioning either
right-hander Danny Patterson or left-hander Mike Venafro to
Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin informed Gunderson on Saturday that
the left-hander would be part of the equation in the Rangers'
efforts to make room on the 25-man roster for Burkett unless health
was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'm not 100 percent, but I can pitch,' '' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``There's a difference, though, between being
able to pitch and being healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunderson has experienced tightness in his left shoulder at
times since spring training and has been receiving treatment, Oates
said. Gunderson will remain with the Rangers through this road trip
and undergo a magnetic resonance imaging test Thursday when the
club returns to Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan to send Gunderson on a medical rehabilitation
assignment before reinstating him from the disabled list. Oates
said he will recommend that Gunderson start in order to build arm
strength. PAVLIK DISAPPEARS So, what became of former Rangers
right-hander Roger Pavlik?
</P>
<P>
   No one appears to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where he is,'' Melvin said. ``I haven't spoken to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavlik was limited to 14 innings with the Rangers last season
because of injuries and the 1996 All-Star became a free agent on
Dec. 19 after rejecting the organization's offer of salary
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin received a telephone call recently from Pavlik's agent,
Alan Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who I thought he was calling about,'' Melvin said. ``He
was calling about John Cangelosi.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin does not have any interest in the journeyman outfielder,
who played for the Rangers in 1992. SHAVE MAKES `PLAY OF THE DAY'
The performance Saturday by reserve infielder Jon Shave did not go
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Shave participated in two double plays and made a diving stop of
a ground ball at shortstop that minimized the damage during the
Blue Jays' two-run third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went unnoticed, but he made the play of the day on that
ball up the middle,'' said right-hander Mike Morgan, Saturday's
winning pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as big a play as we've had on this road trip,'' Oates
said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
