<SLUG> BC-PREMIER-BRITISH-COLUMBIA-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREMIER GLEN CLARK ANOTHER POLITICIAN DEFYING THE ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, B.C. _ British Columbia Premier Glen Clark emerges
from a meeting at the provincial Legislature and spots waiting
microphones of his critics in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   He reacts with an almost cheerful defiance that is his political
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reports of my demise have been greatly exaggerated,'' Clark
jokes. He delivers a quick sound bite, warning of ``horror and
anger'' if Alaska catches too many B.C.-bound salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has come through a firestorm reminiscent of the early days
of la liaison de Monica Lewinsky in the United States. The
premier's resignation was widely predicted after the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police raided Clark's Vancouver home two months ago,
supposedly seeking evidence in a gambling case against one of the
premier's neighbors. A BCTV television crew was tipped off, and
filmed the premier during the raid.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it was being revealed that a Clark-championed
project to build two prototype hydrofoil ferries had ballooned to
twice its original budget. The premier's conservative critics were
threatening to mount a recall campaign against all 40 provincial
legislators of the ruling New Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Clinton in January of last year: The only question
seemed to be how many days the guy had left,'' said former Premier
Dave Barrett, a political ally but no personal friend of Clark's.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Clark is still on his feet. The RCMP has downgraded
charges against Clark's neighbor. The recall campaign has
collapsed. Bad economic news was recently broken when
Louisiana-Pacific Corp. announced it would invest $283 million
(Canadian) in four new mills. As Clark's opponents tried to stage a
rally in Nanaimo Thursday, 250 supporters of his government paraded
under the banner: ``Give Us News, Not Right-Wing Propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Most forecasts still say that Clark and the New Democrats will
go down for the count in the next provincial election. He may not
even enter the ring, resigning to allow a new, untarnished premier
to lead his party into battle. Changing heads is a time-honored
formula for survival in Canadian politics.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada's maritime provinces, an old joke goes, politics is a
family tradition. Battles over separation make politics a religion
in Quebec. Politics is a business in self-satisfied, prosperous
Ontario. But in British Columbia, politics is a blood sport.
</P>
<P>
   It is played out over a land mass larger than California, Oregon
and Washington combined. Two-thirds of the province's 4 million
residents are squeezed into 3 percent of its land base, around
Vancouver and on lower Vancouver Island.
</P>
<P>
   The political center in British Columbia is as sparsely
populated as much of the province. Parties of the left and right
face off at the polls. They confront each other daily on the floor
of the B.C. Legislature. Punches were traded at the Nanaimo rally
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its name, the opposition Liberal Party represents
conservatism, tax cutting and free enterprise, and gets heavy
backing from big business. Its contributors include the parent
companies of British Columbia's major news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The New Democrats are closely tied to the 446,000-member B.C.
Federation of Labor. The ``third way'' moderation of Britain's
Labour Party and Germany's Social Democrats hasn't reached
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   The government's new budget anticipates an $890 million
(Canadian) deficit. It is heavy with health, education and
infrastructure spending designed to help jolt the province out of
recession.
</P>
<P>
   The business community, however, wants tax cuts, and is aghast
at the budget. The Clark government ``is beyond salvaging,'' says
Vancouver Mayor Philip Owen, a critic of the premier.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Polls have shown the New Democrats with as little as 18
percent of the vote. Less than 5 percent of those surveyed are
strongly positive toward Clark's performance. Controlled by
billionaire conservative media magnate Conrad Black, Vancouver's
two daily newspapers display their hostility on both news and
editorial pages.
</P>
<P>
   But chances for survival are often measured by the skills of
those seeking your demise. In this respect, Clark may blessed
almost as much as Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party's leader, former Vancouver Mayor Gordon
Campbell, is stiff and ill at ease in the cut-and-thrust of British
Columbia politics. He has fumbled explanations of why Liberal Party
aides were meeting with the RCMP before its raid of the premier's
home.
</P>
<P>
   The RCMP has never clearly explained the purpose of the raid, or
how BCTV was tipped off. A highly placed former police official
told the Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail: ``What I've seen here tells me
someone is after the premier. What they've done is convict him
without a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska may even come to Clark's rescue. U.S.-Canada salmon talks
reportedly have snagged on a call by Alaska to increase its catch
of British Columbia- and Northwest-bound chinook salmon. Such a
demand, if pressed, would vindicate Clark's militant stand toward
the province's neighbor to the north.
</P>
<P>
   In a parliamentary government, there are no set election dates.
The ruling party decides when it will face the voters. New
Democrats have until the spring of 2001 to call the election. The
date of Clark's widely predicted demise is, therefore, controlled
by Clark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
