<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0274 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LUCAS-STARWARS-S     05-09 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LUCAS-STARWARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE LUCAS `SURPRISED' AT ATTENTION FILM IS GENERATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was only fitting that on the day to celebrate the
contributions of mothers everywhere, one of pop culture's biggest
Mr. Moms celebrated his latest child _ the most anticipated movie
in years.
</P>
<P>
   Director George Lucas, a single father of three and the force
behind ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' gushed the
morning after his latest opus was seen at a special screening for
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel proud,'' he said, grinning contentedly Sunday as
reporters swarmed around him with ``Star Wars'' books, posters and
blank scraps of paper to sign. ``Like a very proud mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said he was surprised by the amount of attention his
latest baby is generating _ from the media coverage leading up to
the movie's launch May 19 to perhaps even the sight of usually
detached journalists treating him like, well, a Beatle.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed early reviews that have described the movie, filled
with computer graphics and humor, as being too puerile for some
tastes. ``I expect not to do well critically. I never have,'' Lucas
said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   The box office, however, is an entirely different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said he would be a little disappointed if his $110 million
``Phantom Menace'' does not become one of the top 10 grossing films
of all time, powered by the key demographic that has carried ``Star
Wars'' movies of the past: preteens and teens.
</P>
<P>
   As the old song goes, if you can make it here _ New York _ you
can make it anywhere. So when final credits for ``Phantom Menace''
rolled at the end of Saturday night's screening at a Manhattan
movie house, it appeared the swashbuckling adventure saga was on a
sanguine path.
</P>
<P>
   Polite applause _ punctuated by some lusty cheers _ filled the
theater as house lights came up. The most enthusiastic viewers were
young people, many of them teenagers, who were overheard saying,
``That was so cool'' and ``I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   One man, a 39-year-old New York real estate executive, summed up
the movie this way: ``It was not like the first three,'' referring
to the trilogy of ``Star Wars,'' ``The Empire Strikes Back'' and
``Return of the Jedi.'' ``It was fun. I mean, I enjoyed it. But
would I see it three times in a row? Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' is hardly short on hype. The movie's
producer, Rick McCallum, said the intense attention stems from
``underground'' channels of information, such as Web sites, and to
a lesser degree from traditional media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done 50 percent fewer interviews'' for this movie than
others in the series, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the power and scope of the Internet, McCallum said
he found a 65-page review of ``Phantom Menace'' by a young man who
had not seen the flick. ``It was a review of other people's
reviews,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But hype, in whatever form it comes, has made the movie very
hip.
</P>
<P>
   People outside the theater before the media screening were ready
to fork out $50 for passes issued to reporters. The event also
attracted actors Natalie Portman and Samuel L. Jackson, who are in
the movie, radio shock jock Howard Stern and rap music mogul
Russell Simmons, who are not.
</P>
<P>
   At ground zero of the New York event, the Regency Hotel on tony
Park Avenue, where rooms normally run $350 a night, the presence of
the Lucas and ``Phantom Menace'' stars overshadowed other hotel
guests, including Elizabeth Taylor and George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   But early word on Lucas' newest movie has been mixed. A headline
in the New York Post dubbed the film ``Luke-Warm Skywalker'' _ and
irked ``Star Wars''-holics by publishing spoilers, or key plot
points. In Sunday's New York Daily News, a review of the movie gave
it two-and-a-half stars. Monday's Los Angeles Daily News gives it
three-and-a-half stars.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Levy, a film critic for The (Portland) Oregonian, said he
enjoyed ``Phantom Menace'' but preferred another spring release,
``The Matrix,'' a sci-fi thriller starring Keanu Reeves and
Lawrence Fishburne.
</P>
<P>
   Luaine Lee, who covers Hollywood for Scripps-Howard News
Service, wrinkled her face and said Lucas' flick ``was a little too
long for my tastes.'' Liz Leyden of The Washington Post enjoyed the
movie, but thought it stopped short of ``the sacred aura''
generated by the trilogy. ``Is it sacrilegious for me to say
that?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics said they thought the plot did not rise to
expectations; still others said a ``Star Wars'' series staple _ the
opening scroll of words _ was confusing. ``Got me totally lost,''
one gray-haired critic huffed.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever its perceived shortcomings, the movie has the stuff
the entire world has come to expect from Lucas: swashbuckling
light-saber duels, eye-candy costumes and out-of-this-world special
effects, including an amazing pod race that conjures up images of
the chariot race in ``Ben Hur.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it has some surprises like... well, to say more would
unleash the wrath of Jedis everywhere!
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movie's actors found the experience of being
connected to Lucas' celluloid legacy life-changing and eye-opening.
</P>
<P>
   Portman, a high school senior who plays Queen Amidala, was
stoked to see herself bedecked on the big screen in ornate, regal
gowns, some of which took months to make. ``They were the most
beautiful costumes I have ever seen on film,'' she said Sunday.
``It makes you feel like a queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Best had the challenge of playing a computer-generated
character called Jar Jar Binks,a fresh entry to Lucas' universe.
Best was amazed at how Lucas ``painted in'' digital worlds around
the acting he performed against a blue screen. A graphic artist,
plying high-tech software, then melded computer images with film to
bring his character to ``life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said Best, who cut his acting chops in the
San Francisco production of the musical ``Stomp'' before becoming
Jar Jar Binks _ a character with floppy ears, loopy gait and speech
that sounds like Caribbean patois blended with hip-hop rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those little details, all those computer graphics,'' said
Best, adding, Jar Jar will be a big hit with kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had enough of the bang 'em up, shoot 'em up,'' he said
stroking his neatly trimmed goatee. ``It is nice to have a cute
little scary creature to look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson, who plays a Jedi warrior, said he is still
processing the technical wizardry of the film. While acting, he had
to draw on deep reservoirs of imagination because many of the
creatures and special effects were added to scenes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to see it at least two more times to digest it and be
able to talk about it,'' Neeson said, with a look of marvel on his
face. He was equally amazed by the attention surrounding the movie,
calling it ``a strange hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been wild,'' a wonderfully composed Twentieth Century
Fox publicist said. ``This has been so big. Nothing like it.''
</P>
<P>
   But not bigger than Lucas himself. Sunday morning, he walked in
a conference room, wearing a brown blazer, blue-and-white checked
shirt and a visage of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   He answered question after question. Some smart. Some dumb. He
spoke about his love for fans, for storytelling and of his movies'
universal themes about taking risks and having courage. He said he
had 100 movies burning inside him, but given his age, perhaps only
20 left to direct. He talked about his other passions, family and
writing. And he discussed his plans to finish two more ``Star
Wars'' movies _ chapters two and three _ before pulling the plug on
the series.
</P>
<P>
   What about chapters seven, eight and nine? a reporter asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   Who will direct them then?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one else will,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the mother of the Force got up from a table and slipped
off, presumably to a galaxy far, far away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
