r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     05-09 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF URGENCY HURTING DODGERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eric Karros says it's only May. Gary Sheffield
says that is the Dodgers' biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield said it wasn't three home runs off Chan Ho Park that
killed his team in Sunday's ugly 6-4 loss to the lowly Florida
Marlins in front of 29,397 at Dodger Stadium. He said they blew a
four-run lead in the final four innings because they don't play
with a sense of urgency, especially against a patsy that was
winless in nine weekend games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we are not intimidating anyone,'' Sheffield said. ``We
haven't shown anyone any reason to be afraid of us. We did the
first six games and nothing since then. We're too lackadaisical,
just thinking it's going to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros is not wrong saying the season still has a long way to
go. Maybe it was too much fun starting the season 5-1. After
hearing the San Francisco Giants' loss to the Milwaukee Brewers
kept the 17-14 Dodgers 1{ games back in the National League West,
Karros quipped, ``I don't think we've been eliminated, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is that perception the past few seasons that has found
the Dodgers having to claw and scratch in September without
success. It was an attitude that made management finally realize
they weren't going to win regardless of how many Mike Piazzas they
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other team was supposed to be flat after Friday's game,''
said Sheffield the former Marlin, who singled twice, walked, stole
a base and scored two runs. ``Not us.''
</P>
<P>
   So they added Kevin Brown and things were supposed to change.
When Brown overpowered the Marlins on Saturday night, the crowd
roared its approval. They were booing again on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Park and four relievers walked eight batters. Florida scored two
runs in the sixth, seventh and eighth. Cliff Floyd and Todd
Dunwoody each hit their first home runs of the year; pinch-hitter
Preston Wilson, who seldom plays despite having more home runs
(six) than the rest of the starting lineup combined, tied the game
at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't come inside today,'' reserve catcher Paul LoDuca
said of Park. ``He has a great fastball, but he was keeping it out
over the plate. I don't care who you are, after a while
major-league hitters are going to hit those.''
</P>
<P>
   Park survived a 28-pitch first inning that might have been one
of the worst in recent memory. He walked the bases loaded but came
out of the inning with a 1-0 lead because Marlins starter Jesus
Sanchez walked four.
</P>
<P>
   Park settled down, retiring 11 straight and 12 of 13, and took a
4-0 lead into the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had added to his cushion with a two-run double by
Devon White in the third and an RBI single by Raul Mondesi in the
fifth. But even as Park looked ready to breeze to his third
consecutive victory, there were warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   White felt a tug at his right hamstring running down Greg
Counsell's fifth-inning drive to the gap in right center and left
after his double. White said later the injury is not serious, but
he won't play in tonight's series opener against the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse after Park left the game. Pedro Borbon (0-1)
opened the seventh by walking Floyd, who later scored the winning
run on a bloop single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Florida added another run when Karros threw away a relay during
a rundown play. But damage already was done. Three Florida
relievers, including winning pitcher Brian Edmondson (2-1), limited
the Dodgers to one hit in the final 41/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big inning, then take five innings off,'' Sheffield
said. ``The next thing we know we're down by two and we're trying
to play with a sense of urgency. In Florida, we had a saying, `One
heartbeat.' We've got to be relentless. When you do that, you're
going to win the majority of your games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-09-99 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
