<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-09 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROGAN-RUNNING-LADN     05-09 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGAN-RUNNING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY CONGRESSIONAL RACE'S WINNER COULD TURN OUT TO BE VOTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ With the campaign already heating up for next
year's 27th District congressional race, local officials see
nothing but opportunity for their communities.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Republican Rep. James Rogan and Democratic
state Sen. Adam Schiff, both based in Pasadena, have been focusing
on hot-button issues, attempting to become the hero in the battles
over noise restrictions at the regional airport and a controversial
hillside housing project.
</P>
<P>
   California's 27th congressional district covers the well
established satellite cities of Burbank, Glendale and Pasedena
bordering Los Angeles to the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two favorite sons competing to be the white knight,''
said Rob Sharkey, president of the Glendale Homeowners Coordinating
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank City Manager Robert ``Bud'' Ovrom said the city will
take full advantage of the competition in its fight to get a
mandatory curfew and a noise budget at Burbank Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest is to use both of them to the maximum. We're
willing to exploit them. It will be nonpartisan exploitation,''
Ovrom said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point both men planned their own ``peace summits'' on the
airport issue, which pits airport officials' designs for expansion
against residents' worries over increased noise and traffic in a
high-spending battle spanning years. Rogan is eagerly awaiting an
answer from the Federal Aviation Administration to his question
about whether the airport can impose a curfew without getting
federal approval. Schiff on Friday called on the FAA to grant a
mandatory curfew for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff has asked for a $5million budget allocation from the
state to buy the Oakmont V property in Glendale to preserve the
brushy hillside land as open space. Rogan sought $20,000 in federal
funds to pay for an appraisal of the Oakmont property as the first
step in securing federal money to purchase the land.
</P>
<P>
   If either one is successful in stopping Oakmont V, Sharkey
predicted it will translate into solid votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could bring that trophy home it would guarantee a trip
to Washington,'' Sharkey said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Schiff announced last month that he would take on Rogan,
who soared to national fame as one of the most prominent House
managers in the impeachment of President Clinton _ a role that has
made him a target of Democratic Party wrath and especially
vulnerable because the district could go either way.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rogan resisted GOP pressure to challenge
Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein next year and decided to seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The race is being watched on a national level and will bring in
heavy contributions from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan is hitting up pro-impeachment Republicans who think of him
as a political star, while Schiff works Democrats who want to see
Rogan ousted as revenge for his impeachment role.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle locally has both men focused like never before on
the most emotional issues for their constituents. While both
candidates insist they have been tirelessly dedicated to
constituents' needs since the day they took office, district
residents agree both are taking much more aggressive approached to
local issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of them cared about the airport issue at all until
they were pitted against each other,'' Ovrom said. ``It was a
little awkward during the battling summits.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have insisted they've been working on the
airport issue well before the competition started, with Schiff
noting he called for a mandatory curfew as far back as 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the competition is the fact that they have so many of
the same constituents. Rogan's congressional district is located
completely inside Schiff's state Senate district.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a rematch of sorts. Rogan disposed of Schiff twice in
1994, when they both ran for the 43rd District Assembly seat,
beating him first in a June special election and then again in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan is a former Los Angeles County prosecutor and municipal
court judge and Schiff is a former federal prosecutor. Schiff's
profile has been rising steadily since his 1996 election to the
state Senate and he's expected to provide a strong challenge
against Rogan.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political science professor at Claremont
Graduate School, said the dynamic is interesting because Rogan and
Schiff, who are political opposites, are taking the similar
positions on local issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not leave your opponent alone in the center ring,
especially on issues voters care about,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   This race has started earlier than most, in part because of all
the furor over impeachment, which has been a doubled-edged sword of
sorts for Rogan. He won his second term in November with just
50.7percent of the vote, squeaking by an opponent he outspent by
more than 2 to 1. His 27th District is now 45percent Democrats and
38percent Republicans and voters there supported Clinton in both
1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan's campaign manager Jeff Lennan said he and a cadre of
volunteers are overwhelmed by the task of responding to the 20,000
citizens nationwide who have written Rogan offering to help him
retain his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen his donor base expand considerably,'' Lennan said.
``I was running through our contribution records and we've got 16
donors from Alabama and 23 donors from Connecticut. It's nothing
we've ever seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan recently sent out a campaign fund-raising piece to
conservative activists nationwide seeking ``emergency pledges of
support'' to defend himself against an anti-impeachment backlash.
The mailer is topped with quotes from Democratic officials and
Hollywood media mogul David Geffen, all predicting Rogan's defeat.
Then there is personal letter from Rogan starting with the
question: ``Are we going to let them get away with it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to know from you ... am I going to fight this battle
against Bill Clinton alone? Or can I count on you to help me to
stand against Bill Clinton,'' Rogan writes in the mailer.
</P>
<P>
   Lennan said this mailer was sent out to 60,000 conservative
activists nationwide about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lennan acknowledged that the competition has already started to
impact local issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, these issues are going to be used as political
footballs,'' Lennan said.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff said his competition with Rogan is ``great for the
district.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of months Rogan has had to play catch-up,''
Schiff said. ``I have no doubt we will force him to advocate for a
curfew at the airport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
