<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MOURNING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZO' STAYING IN CHECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Miami Heat center Alonzo Mourning says he
has learned his lesson. Says he won't do it again. Says he has his
temper in check.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Mourning knows until the moment comes when he has to choose
between taking a swing at an opponent and turning the other cheek
and walking away from a potential altercation _ and he chooses the
latter _ no one believes a word he says. Mourning proved last year
that he would rather fight than let cooler heads prevail.
</P>
<P>
   With 1.4 seconds left in Game 4 of last year's best-of-five
first-round playoff series against the New York Knicks, Mourning
was ejected for fighting Larry Johnson. Both players also were
suspended for the decisive Game 5, which Miami lost because the
Heat probably couldn't win the Continental Basketball Association
title without Mourning in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The fight and subsequent suspension meant Mourning had to endure
a summer of radio-talk-show blabber-mouths blaming him for the
Heat's early exit from the playoffs. And it means he has to prove
that he would rather win than fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always my fault, partner,'' Mourning said. ``If we lose,
it's my fault; if we win, it's my fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm going to be the goat, regardless. I'm just being
truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case Saturday when the Heat lost its playoff opener
to the Knicks, 95-75, despite having the home-court advantage.
Mourning scored 27 points on 10-for-16 shooting, but he knows his
image won't improve unless he can lead the Heat to victory in Game
2, and to an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old, seventh-year center from Georgetown says he has
taken steps to control his anger, and they seem to be working.
</P>
<P>
   In the 46 games Mourning played in this season, he was ejected
only once. Two years ago, he fouled out of nine games. Last year,
he sliced the number to five. This year, he drew no
disqualifications except the ejection.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he might be drawing more cheers than jeers this year.
He is considered a top candidate for most valuable player and has
the statistics to warrant consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning, San Antonio's Tim Duncan and Sacramento's Chris Webber
are the only players who averaged at least 20 points and 11
rebounds per game in the regular season. Mourning also led the NBA
in blocked shots with 3.91 per game.
</P>
<P>
   But the most compelling statistics in Mourning's MVP case might
be from the four games he didn't play. Heat opponents scored 96.3
points per game and shot 51 percent from the field while he was
sidelined with an eye injury; in the 46 games he played, Heat foes
averaged 83 points and shot 40 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   He held opposing starting centers to an average of 8.8 points
and 6.6 rebounds per game, while averaging 20.1 points and 11
rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been doing a yeoman's job every day in practice and in
games,'' Heat point guard Tim Hardaway said. ``He's been trying to
do what we ask him to do. We don't even talk about defense, because
he's been exceptional on defense. But he's an all-around ballplayer
now.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Mourning's game was never a question with Heat fans and
the coaching staff. It was his temper that worried them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Alonzo knows what he has to do for us to achieve our
ultimate goal,'' Hardaway said. ``He's one of the nicest guys you'd
ever want to meet, and he has worked extra hard in doing all of the
things that he needs to do in order for us to be considered an
elite team.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat coach Pat Riley has also talked with Mourning about how to
avoid being goaded into adverse situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for us to get to where we want to get to _ and that
is the championship _ we need to have Alonzo on the court as much
as possible,'' Riley said. ``And he knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he knows that he must remain consumed with winning a title,
not consumed with anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult, but you live and learn,'' Mourning
said. ``And I definitely learned. I definitely, definitely
learned.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
