r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-09 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLNESS OF `THE ONLY COACH' CAPS A LOUSY WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ To some, it seems, Tom Landry is still The
Only Coach the Cowboys Have Ever Had.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they know better. All things must change. But Landry was
turned loose one winter's night 10 years ago, and some erstwhile
Cowboys fans haven't darkened the turnstiles at Texas Stadium
since.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Saturday's news of his grave illness, leukemia, must shake
them. It does me.
</P>
<P>
   I thought that Tom Landry, like his golfing friend Bob Hope, was
going to live forever.
</P>
<P>
   He still might. If anyone can invent the perfect Flex defense to
fight leukemia, Tom probably will.
</P>
<P>
   Leukemia is curable, the medical journals say. There are
chemotherapy sessions, radiation treatments, blood transfusions.
And if Staubach could come in in the last two minutes and save him,
you know Roger would.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, this just rounds off a lousy week.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cowboys family gathered in Addison on Saturday for a
memorial service for the late Mark Tuinei, it had the news of
Landry's cancer to add to their sorrow and prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Landry, sick? It can't be. He had had the usual assortment of
old football injuries, especially to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   But Landry had to be the only 74-year-old in the country who was
still at his NFL playing weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just amazing,'' an old rival, Joe Gibbs, had observed
respectfully on a trip through Texas last month.
</P>
<P>
   What Gibbs and others didn't realize was that Landry was already
sick and that Tom's Mount Rushmore facade was about to be
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been ludicrous to see the quiet, dapperly dressed
head coach depicted as a meek, cheek-turning, born-again Christian.
Clearly, Landry forgives his transgressors _ he took Owner Jones
off the hook and accepted a Ring of Honor induction, didn't he?
</P>
<P>
   But as former teammates Pat Summerall and Frank Gifford have
often reminded us, Landry was one mean, head-hunting New York
Giants defensive back. And he certainly didn't coach meek defenses.
</P>
<P>
   His strength, however, has to have tested Landry in the years
since he left the Cowboys. The Landrys, Tom and Alicia, lost their
youngest daughter, Lisa, to cancer four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Landry Childress, like her father, was an exceptional
person. She was diagnosed with cancer in 1991. But she was also
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor advised Lisa to have an abortion so that chemotherapy
treatments could begin immediately. Lisa, however, said no.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after the baby _ they named her Christina _ was born,
the mother underwent a liver transplant. Lisa finally lost her long
fight with the cancer in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never regretted her decision,'' Tom has told us. ``She was
a real inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lisa Landry Childress Foundation was formed in 1995 to honor
her memory and to raise public awareness of organ donations. The
social highlight of the foundation is its annual ``Golf with the
Legends'' tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As testimonial to Tom's own ``legend,'' the field that shows up
for the golf tournament reads like a Hall of Fame roll call. Landry
seemed especially proud last year that ``my quarterbacks'' all
showed up _ Staubach, Danny White, Craig Morton and, yes, even Don
Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   It seems somehow inappropriate to bring up Landry's record here.
His 270 wins are the third most in NFL coaching history. He took
teams to five Super Bowls, winning two. He coached the Cowboys to
20 consecutive winning seasons, a distinction that grows more
remarkable with each passing season. Landry himself was inducted
into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But there I go, sounding like I'm eulogizing the coach, when the
message from the Landry family is that they expect Tom to recover.
</P>
<P>
   It seems incongruous, in a way, to be asking Cowboys fans to
pray for Tom Landry. Ours seem so insignificant for someone who has
walked so tall.
</P>
<P>
   But I think the coach needs us. And if Roger has one more Hail
Mary, now may be the time.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a lousy week.  &LR; tagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lebreton &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
