<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PREFER TO SKIP TALK ABOUT TROUBLE WITH POWER PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ken Hitchcock said it's twice as hard to
score on the power play in the playoffs. And by watching the Stars
the past two seasons, he has obtained plenty of evidence to back
that up.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the rest of the NHL doesn't follow the same
trend. While the Stars have seen their power-play success rate
during the past two seasons decline from 19 percent in the regular
season to 8.9 percent in the playoffs, the rest of the NHL has held
steady at 15 percent in both the regular season and postseason.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's so much harder to find open space in the
playoffs and that's reflected in our power play,'' Hitchcock said.
``I think every aspect of the playoffs is harder for goal scorers
and that means that goal scorers have to work that much harder.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars have yet to lose in this season's playoffs and
Hitchcock continues to say the power play isn't a problem, it's
clear the lack of success with the man advantage can hurt the Stars
in a future series or even tonight when their best-of-seven Western
Conference semifinal series with the Blues moves to St. Louis for a
6:30 game at Kiel Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation right now,'' Stars leading scorer Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``We know it has to get better, so we keep working
at it getting better. But if we start talking about it, start
worrying about it, start holding it up for public debate, we're
just putting more pressure on ourselves and hurting ourselves even
more.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a Catch-22 situation that could begin to steamroll the
Stars if they're not careful. The more they fumble their power-play
chances, the more pressure they feel. The more pressure they feel,
the more they fumble their power-play chances. Game 2 against the
Blues, a Stars' 5-4 victory in overtime Saturday at Reunion Arena,
was clearly the low point for the team's power play in the
playoffs. The Stars went 0-for-4, were outshot 3-1 and gave up four
solid short-handed chances that could have easily been turned into
Blues goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's not taking energy out of our game, we can live
with it,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   But why live with it? Why not thrive on the power play? Why not
use the obvious talent they have with the man advantage _ they have
scored more power-play goals during the past two regular seasons
(151) than any other team in the NHL _ to open up some breathing
room in the playoffs? Why not win a game by more than one goal _
something the Stars have done only once in their six playoff
victories?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we have talented players and we know we can score on
the power play, it's just not going in right now,'' defenseman
Darryl Sydor said. ``Sometimes you just struggle to beat a hot
goaltender in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars must keep finding the hot ones, because no one else
has a problem. During the past two regular seasons, the NHL has
averaged a success rate of 15.1 ('97-98) and 15.8 ('98-99). During
the past two postseasons, the league has averaged 14.1 ('97-98) and
16.5 percent ('98-99).
</P>
<P>
   Power-play success has actually gone up in this season's
playoffs. The Stars, meanwhile have dropped from an 18.8 percent
success rate on the power play during the regular season and an
average of .90 power-play goals per game to a success rate of 5.9
percent and an average of .28 power plays per game in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   And they've done that for three consecutive seasons in the
playoffs. That's not a glitch, it's a serious trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that really hurt last year and something that
obviously has to be better,'' center Mike Modano said. ``We just
have to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are a team that has high skill at the top level in
Modano, Nieuwendyk and Brett Hull _ not a trio that generally likes
to mix it up in front of the net. So is that the reason the power
play is so much worse when it comes to postseason play?
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly think that sometimes the puck just doesn't go in,''
Modano said. ``We've faced some pretty good goaltending in the
playoffs over the past few years and I think that's a big reason.
It's not like we haven't had some great scoring chances.''
</P>
<P>
   With power-play specialists like the aforementioned forward trio
and defensemen Sergei Zubov and Darryl Sydor, the Stars have proved
they have talent with the man advantage. Zubov has quarterbacked
No. 1-ranked power plays with the Stars, Penguins and Rangers.
Nieuwendyk played for a No. 1-ranked power play in Calgary, and
Hull led the Stars with 15 power-play goals _ ranking him fifth in
the NHL during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   So where are the results?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that will only make it worse is if
we just keep talking about it and analyzing it and talking about
it,'' Hitchcock said. ``What you have to do with the power play,
especially in the playoffs, is simplify. You have to shoot the puck
and you have to get traffic to the front of the net, and that's
what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he will play Derian Hatcher in front of the net
on the power play and that the return of Pat Verbeek from
suspension will be important to team grittiness with the man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams we see that are successful are the ones that shoot
the puck on net and then go get the rebound,'' Hitchcock said.
``It's rarely the first shot that scores on the power play. It's
more often the second or third or even fourth. We have to find a
way to get to those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Either that, or get ready for even more pressure from fans,
media and opponents. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
