<SLUG> BC-DRAMA-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARADE' LEADS THE DRAMA DESK AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Parade,'' the financial flop about a 1915 Atlanta
lynching, led all contenders in the 1999 Drama Desk Awards Sunday
night, taking six awards including outstanding new musical.
``Wit,'' which was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for drama last month,
was named outstanding play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swan Lake,'' Matthew Bourne's modern interpretation of
Tchaikovsky's storybook ballet, won five awards, including nods for
outstanding choreography and outstanding direction of a musical for
Bourne. Trevor Nunn was named outstanding director of a play for
his work on Tennessee Williams' ``Not About Nightingales,'' which
won four awards, including three in the major design categories:
lights, set and costumes.
</P>
<P>
   In the acting categories the Drama Desk chose Brian Dennehy (in
``Death of a Salesman'') as outstanding actor in a play and
Kathleen Chalfant (``Wit'') as outstanding actress. For
performances in musicals, Brent Carver (``Parade'') was named
outstanding actor, while Carolee Carmello (``Parade'') and
Bernadette Peters (``Annie Get Your Gun'') shared the award for
outstanding actress.
</P>
<P>
   In a category that is expected to be highly contested in next
month's Tony Awards, the award for outstanding revival of a play
was also shared, with ``Death of a Salesman'' and ``The Iceman
Cometh'' both being named winners. Both plays are nominated for the
Tony for best revival of a play. ``You're a Good Man, Charlie
Brown,'' was named outstanding musical revival.
</P>
<P>
   David Hare, who was overlooked in last week's Tony nominations,
was named as outstanding solo performer for his work in the
autobiographical ``Via Dolorosa.''
</P>
<P>
   The Drama Desk, which is composed of writers and critics who
cover New York's theater world, also gave several special awards,
including an honor for lifetime achievement to the theater
caricaturist Al Hirschfeld, the longtime caricaturist for The New
York Times Arts and Leisure section.
</P>
</TEXT>
