<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT MUCH' LONGER FOR WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK and SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Jerry West took his familiar post in the Forum Club
tunnel on Sunday, and that alone was cause for a headline after a
six-week, self-imposed ban on game-day appearances. But West went a
step further, speaking publicly for the first time in weeks and
hinting once again that retirement was on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on NBC, the Lakers' top executive expressed
disappointment with the team's lack of effort for much of the
season, saying, ``We've been dysfunctional at times.''
</P>
<P>
   So knotted up over his team's play _ and the signing of Dennis
Rodman _ West had rarely attended a game since mid-March. His
hibernation even prompted Hall of Famer Wilt Chamberlain to
publicly criticize West for disappearing during hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the contrary, I've always been here,'' West said. ``It's
hard for me to watch games sometimes. I'm an emotional guy. It's
easier for me to watch games on television than it is at the
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   And when interviewer Jim Gray asked West how much longer he
could do his job, West said: ``Not much. Not much. Not much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you get to the point in your life where if your life
revolves around coming to the office, and one day you win and
everybody (says) what a smart guy you are and when you lose, what a
dumb guy you are,'' he said. ``I'm none of those. I'm me. I'm no
smarter than anyone else, I'm no dumber than anyone else. I care a
hell of a lot more than most people about this sport, particularly
about this team. That's my biggest problem.''
</P>
<P>
   West was complimentary of interim coach Kurt Rambis' performance
but would not rule out former Bulls coach Phil Jackson as a
candidate if Rambis is not retained. Jackson was recently critical
of the Lakers' handling of former Bull Rodman, who was waived after
a series of misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Lakers would consider Jackson, West said, ``He
doesn't think we do things very well around here.'' He also said
the Lakers were ``under pressure to hire a high-profile coach'' and
that Jackson's comments would not disqualify him from
consideration. But he quickly noted the Lakers don't have a
vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt Rambis is our coach right now, OK? I don't think we're
looking for a new coach at this point in time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Rambis) has done a great job under very trying
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   No jitters: Rambis wouldn't admit to being nervous at his first
foray into the postseason as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fun time of the year; it's the most fun time of the
year. So it's not necessarily butterflies of nervousness; it's
butterflies of excitement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference being the coach? Never being able to escape the
game?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an all-day thought process for me,'' he said.
``Basketball and our team is the last thought on my mind before I
go to sleep and the first thought on my mind as soon as I wake up
in the morning.'' &QL; 
Bring back Rodman: Houston forward Charles Barkley, who scored 25
points Sunday, was asked if Rodman could guard him one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. That's why I was sad to see him go,'' Barkley said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
