A0423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT &LR;      05-09 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY GAMES ON SCHEDULE BUT PROBLEMS PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOHN SHAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ In the countdown to the Sydney Olympics _
now fewer than 500 days _ the recent focus has been more on
political problems than progress in preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is ahead of schedule on construction and organization for
the 2000 Summer Games, which are scheduled to open on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Yet controversies involving an Australian delegate to the
International Olympic Committee and the planned site on a Pacific
bay for the beach volleyball competition have entangled the local
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from recent scandals about alleged vote-selling by
IO C members may mean that Sydney receives less money from sponsors
to spend on some venues and comforts than it hoped. The Games'
management, the Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games,
is government-controlled, with a $3 billion mix of official and
private financing.
</P>
<P>
   Delays by the IOC in dealing with allegations of corruption and
freeloading by some of its members _ including the Australian Phil
Coles _ disturb some business groups, slowing the flow of
sponsorship money.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Knight, a senior Sydney politician who is president of
the organizing committee, and his chief executive, Sandy Hollway,
called on Coles last week to resign from the committee, saying it
is inappropriate for him to serve while he remains the subject of
IOC investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Ebersol, chairman of NBC Sports, which will televise the
Games in the United States, and David F. D'Alessandro, president of
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., a major Games sponsor, also
urged Coles to quit.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on Coles mounted Monday when Jackie Kelly,
Australia's Sports Minister, called for his resignation. Coles was
to meet Monday with Australian IOC member Kevan Gosper, who was
expected to push Coles to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney has not lost a sponsor, but it has anxiously noted the
precedent of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which recently pulled its $20
million sponsorship from the 2002 Winter Olympics at Salt Lake
City. Officials of those Games have admitted making extravagant
payments to IOC members who were involved in the vote that gave
Utah the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney's current sponsorship shortfall is about $100 million.
This is manageable, according to Knight, who says it is only a
fraction of the overall budget of $1.7 billion for the specific
staging of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney committee executives say they expect to reach their
sponsorship target of about $500 million, though last week they did
cut $50 million from the budget as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   One sector being considered for cost cutting is the lavish
hospitality being sought by the 1,500 IOC officials and their
guests and staff who are expected to attend the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery for the Games is important to NBC, which is paying
$600 million for the television rights and insisted that organizers
remove obtrusive power lines near some venues at a cost of $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has also encouraged Sydney organizers to resist demands by
residents of the surfside suburb of Bondi that the 10-day beach
volleyball event not be held there. NBC wants beach volleyball at
Bondi because the mile-wide Pacific bay is known internationally
and would make a fine backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, 1,000 angry Bondi residents held a noisy rally at the
beach, protesting plans to build a 10,000-seat temporary stadium
that would occupy much of the center of the beach for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi Mayor Paul Pearce, who faces an election this year, has
lobbied for changes in the volleyball program but admits that NBC
negotiated rights to the venue.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi's Chamber of Commerce president, Gary Marx, says his
members are opposed to the stadium because they fear that
construction will disrupt the retail trade and that the new crowds
will not produce more business.
</P>
<P>
   And Peter Winkler, the protest committee spokesman, charges that
the stadium could damage the beach and would restrict public access
by swimmers, sunbathers and joggers.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials say the 50-foot-high grandstands will leave no
scars, but acknowledge that construction and dismantling will
interfere with use of the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, who include young surfers and aging beach
regulars, vow civil disobedience unless the Games' organizers
retreat to another site. More than 450 have signed pledges to stand
before bulldozers or chain themselves to fences.
</P>
<P>
   There are no similar problems at the other competition sites.
Most of the 20 venues, from the privately financed 110,000-seat
main stadium with boomerang-curve roofs to a mountain-bike track
cut across suburban hillsides, have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Other complaints have not been as dramatic as those at Bondi.
Many residents have been grumbling about traffic snarls and
sidewalk closures caused by a $200 million facelift going on
downtown and by several billion dollars' worth of Olympic-linked
construction elsewhere. And many residents say they will leave town
during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Sydneysiders love sports spectacles, however. More than 100,000
spectators filled the new $425 million Olympic Stadium last month
when it opened with a rugby doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium's first international tryout will come this August _
a football exhibition game between the Denver Broncos and the San
Diego Chargers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
