<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS `LET IT GET AWAY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Forget the Utah Jazz. Ignore the San Antonio Spurs.
Nuke the entire Eastern Conference. There's only two teams truly
worthy of winning the NBA title, at least according to resident NBA
analyst Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the Lakers) don't win the championship, or we don't, it's
a disappointing year _ plain and simple,'' Barkley said. ``Both
teams are built to win the championship. Somebody's going to be
disappointed in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   After Round 1 of this opening-round playoff series, it was the
Rockets' turn to be depressed. They were certain they gave away
Sunday's 101-100 loss to the Lakers before 17,505.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made mental mistakes,'' said Houston coach Rudy
Tomjanovich. ``We can't stop shooting ourselves in the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   But with so many choices, the Rockets just didn't happen to
agree which miscue was the most egregious in the final 80 seconds
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the foul called with 5.3 seconds left, when guard
Sam Mack fell to the ground and made contact with Kobe Bryant, who
made two free throws to give the Lakers a 101-100 lead _ and the
final score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was personally incensed, because I was standing right there
when they called it on Sam,'' rookie guard Cuttino Mobley said.
``He did not foul Kobe. All I have to say is let us dictate the
game, not the refs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was a no-call,'' Tomjanovich added.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was the turnovers. Scottie Pippen lost the ball with
7.6 seconds left and the Rockets in front 100-99. Mobley made an
errant pass with 1:18 left and Houston ahead 97-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some turnovers that really cost us,'' Barkley said.
``We let it get away. That's a no-brainer. It's very disheartening
to lose that game. We gave it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   This being a team of superstars, it would be too clear-cut for
everyone to focus on the turnovers. Pippen focused on a major
coaching decision, questioning Tomjanovich's strategy to foul
Shaquille O'Neal with 28 seconds left and the Rockets ahead 100-98.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed the first free throw and made the second, so the
move paid off, right? Not in Pippen's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think that... was a very smart move,'' Pippen said.
``We should have made them come down and have to work to score. At
least take the time off the clock. We're up two points and we just
allowed them to split the lead and they get the ball back because
now we have to do something at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them the opportunity, and (O'Neal) put us in a
position where we had to score. We just put our backs to the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Pippen was the one who lost the ball on the ensuing
possession.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing the Rockets weren't bitter about was Mobley's
drive at the buzzer, when O'Neal came from behind and blocked the
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a good play,'' Mobley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
