<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-GIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES GIVES $50 MILLION TO PROGRAM HELPING THIRD-WORLD WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Gates, the chairman of Microsoft Corp., has
given $50 million to Columbia University's Joseph L. Mailman School
of Public Health for a program to prevent mothers in developing
nations from dying during childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is the largest foundation grant for a single program in
Columbia's history, said Dr. Allan Rosenfield, the dean of the
School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Gates and his wife, Melinda, gave $3.3
billion to their two foundations, bringing the total assets of both
to nearly $5.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As parents, Melinda and I care very deeply about the health of
mothers around the world,'' Gates said in a statement. ``We're very
excited about this project, because research shows us that nine out
of 10 cases of maternal death in the developing world can be
prevented by providing access to health care services.''
</P>
<P>
   The program will be headed by Rosenfield, an obstetrician and
gynecologist, and Dr. Deborah Maine, a doctor of public health and
a research scientist for the Center of Population and Family
Health, a department in the School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The grant will provide support to government programs as well as
nongovernmental organizations and women's groups whose aim is to
prevent maternal death and disability in developing countries in
Africa, Asia and Latin America. Rosenfield and Dr. Maine said they
would work with organizations like CARE, the World Health
Organization, the United Nations Population Fund and UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield and Dr. Maine first brought maternal mortality and
disability to the attention of the international health community
14 years ago when an article they wrote was published in The
Lancet, the British medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   Every minute, Rosenfield said in a recent interview, a woman in
Asia, Africa or Latin America dies of the complications of
pregnancy or childbirth. In some areas in Africa, he added, one out
of 12 women dies from such complications, compared with one out of
4,000 women in northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in developing countries die, as did women in the West
100 years ago, from hemorrhaging, excess bleeding, infections and
obstructed labor,'' Dr. Maine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some of the poor countries we'll be visiting, they deliver
babies at home with a granny midwife, which is what they call them,
or sometimes with a relative and sometimes by themselves,'' she
added. ``It's sometimes one to 10 hours to the nearest place where
they can get help. We want to find ways to make emergency
obstetrical care more readily available and accessible than it is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Their aim, she said, was not to build new hospitals but to
``improve the functioning and upgrade services in existing
hospitals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
